<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starving Baby Case Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tyler Isaac Walrond likely would have been  
walking by now, if he had lived. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, his parents are in court, arguing over whether his  
mother let her son die of malnourishment by insisting on breast 
feeding him despite her body's inadequate supply of milk. 
</P>
<P>
	Tabitha Walrond, 21, is charged with manslaughter. Her lawyer  
portrays her as a loving mother who was never told that her 
surgically reduced breasts put her at risk of not providing enough 
nourishment for her child. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyler's father, Keenan Purrell, accuses Ms. Walrond of killing  
the 2-month old boy because she was upset that he left her and 
fathered a child with another woman. 
</P>
<P>
	When the baby died on Aug. 27, 1997, he weighed barely five  
pounds; his birth weight was 7 pounds, 15 ounces. Purrell broke 
down in sobs in court Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He looked all shrunken,'' he said of his son the last time he  
saw him. ``I felt like I couldn't hold him tight enough. I couldn't 
let him go ... My son was looking like a head and some twigs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walrond wept as he testified.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tragedy, from the moment this child died to this  
day,'' said her lawyer, Susan Tipograph. ``I think lots and lots of 
people had responsibility for this tragic and unnecessary death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Tipograph said that when her client sought help for her  
baby, a health center turned her away because she lacked a Medicaid 
card. 
</P>
<P>
	Her client, she said, didn't know the child wasn't getting  
enough food, believed it was best to breast-feed him and was never 
warned by doctors that she was at risk for breast-feeding failure 
because of a breast reduction operation she'd had when she was 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Purrell, a 21-year-old former security guard, has testified that  
he spoke to Ms. Walrond only three times during her pregnancy and 
saw his son three times, including the day he died. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Ms. Walrond had refused to give the baby formula, saying  
he should only be breast fed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We argued about whether to feed him the formula,'' he said.  
``She kept saying `I'll take my baby and I'll go home' ... I 
started to say this is my son, this is my house,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mother gave me the bottle and I fed it to him. He sucked it  
down. He really sucked it. I thought ... I've got a greedy baby,'' 
he said. ``I said, `Would you agree to give him a bottle a day? 
It's not going to kill him.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
