<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unser Feeling Fine After Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAZARETH, Pa. (AP) -- Al Unser Jr. is back in his car and barely  
aware of the special equipment he's using this weekend to help him 
drive in the Bosch Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-time CART champion is making his first appearance since  
breaking his ankle in an accident on the first lap of the season, 
March 21 in Marlboro Grand Prix of Miami. He's wearing a protective 
brace of carbon fiber and a special shoe large enough to 
accommodate it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nike's been making my shoes for last couple of years, and they  
jumped right in with both feet to accommodate the brace,'' Unser 
said Friday at Nazareth Speedway. ``Once the race gets going Sunday 
and the adrenaline flows, my ankle will not be an issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although his right ankle is held together by a plate and screws,  
Unser sees it as no impediment. The only change in the car is in 
the throttle spring, which make the accelerator lighter to the 
touch. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I got in the car for first time Monday, the ankle felt  
better than I expected,'' Unser said, alluding to a test in 
Madison, Ill. ``Being in the car is the best therapy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unser, an iron man of the sport, missed the last two races, the  
only time's he's been out of his car since failing to qualify for 
the 1995 Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the ankle is completely healed, Unser can turn all his  
attention to winning for the 32nd time in his career. Although he 
has not prevailed since 1995 -- a span of 54 races -- Unser is second 
only to Michael Andretti in career CART victories. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *KNOWING NAZARETH:* There's a definite hometown advantage to  
racing at Nazareth Speedway, where only five of 12 previous Bosch 
Grand Prix winners have lacked a connection to either track owner 
Roger Penske or the town in the foothills of the Pocono Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Emerson Fittipaldi won the race three times -- twice for Penske.  
Paul Tracy, now driving for Barry Green, prevailed twice for 
Penske, and Danny Sullivan won once. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Rick Mears and Fittipaldi won Marlboro Challenge  
all-star races for Penske on the .946-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice a Bosch winner is Newman-Haas driver Michael Andretti of  
the Nazareth Andrettis. 
</P>
<P>
	Outsiders to win at Nazareth were Fittipaldi for Patrick-Ganassi  
Racing, Arie Luyendyk, Bobby Rahal, Nigel Mansell and defending 
champion Jimmy Vasser. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TIRE WARS:* Firestone, which has dominated rival tire supplier  
Goodyear for the last several seasons in CART, was hoping for its 
third pole in four races in qualifying Saturday for the Bosch Grand 
Prix. Cars on Firestones also have won 22 races in a row, dating to 
Michael Andretti's victory for Goodyear in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Firestone had the pole 18 times to just one for Goodyear in  
1998, and had that same edge in race victories. 
</P>
<P>
	At Nazareth, it was a Firestone rout. Of the top 10, only  
fourth-place finisher Gil de Ferran was on Goodyears. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PIT STOPS:* The Bosch Grand Prix on Sunday caps the first of  
three programs of racing this year at Nazareth Speedway, where Indy 
Lights and Toyota Atlantic cars also run this weekend. Later this 
month, NASCAR takes over with the Busch Series and modifieds, and 
returns in July with its trucks and all-pro cars. The Barber Dodge 
Pro Series also joins the NASCAR program May 22-23, and USAC sprint 
cars participate with the stockers July 16-18. ... Both Paul Tracy 
and Michael Andretti will be seeking a third Nazareth pole 
Saturday. They are tied with Rick Mears for the most in the race. 
... The front row of Patrick Carpentier and Greg Moore last year in 
Nazareth was only the second 1-2 start for Canadians in CART 
history. Tracy had the pole and Jacques Villeneuve started second 
in Phoenix in 1994. ... Andretti, hoping to match Emerson 
Fittipaldi's record of three Nazareth victyories, has been the most 
dominant driver in the event. He has led in eight of 11 races and 
been on the point for 599 laps. ... Tracy set the standard for 
dominance in 1994, leading for all but eight of 200 laps. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
