<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Criminals Fill Up Mental Hospitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAPA, Calif. (AP) -- For 124 years, Napa State Hospital has taken  
care of mental patients in an open, campus-like setting in the 
heart of California wine country. In March, however, the hospital 
erected a 16-foot-high chain-link fence topped with coils of 
glistening razor wire. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason: Nearly 75 percent of the 739 current residents have  
criminal backgrounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty frightening,'' said Myrna Abramowitz, a former  
trustee at nearby Napa Community College. ``What it's turning out 
to be is a penal institution and that worries me a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, only 25 percent of the patients at California's four  
state mental hospitals were sent there by the criminal justice 
system. The rest were mentally ill people who were deemed a danger 
to themselves or others and were committed under civil procedures 
by county mental health departments. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, however, all but the most severely ill civilly  
committed patients have been released, supposedly to get treatment 
in their own communities, under a movement known as 
deinstitutionalization. 
</P>
<P>
	In turn, the Corrections Department and judges have filled the  
beds with mentally ill prison inmates and people found innocent by 
reason of insanity or incompetent to stand trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Carolla, a spokesman for the Virginia-based National  
Alliance for the Mentally Ill, said the trend is nationwide: Mental 
hospitals that once offered psychiatric care in comfortable 
settings were largely emptied during the movement to 
deinstitutionalize the mentally ill and are now being filled with 
criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the reason for the change is financial -- few county  
mental health departments can afford the $100,000 a year it costs 
to keep a patient at Napa State Hospital, said Carla Jacobs, a NAMI 
board member from Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, pressure to accept criminals in the nation's 75,000  
remaining mental hospital beds has increased in the 14 states that 
allow violent sex offenders to be kept indefinitely for treatment 
after serving their prison terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Deinstitutionalization wasn't supposed to work this way,  
advocates for the mentally disabled say. Instead of getting 
medication and psychiatric care in their communities, former mental 
patients have been left on their own, swelling the numbers of 
homeless. Many ultimately commit crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people that are coming into state hospitals now, they're  
coming in the back door after they've been criminalized, rather 
than before the tragedies that put them there,'' Jacobs said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1966, there were 27,000 people in California's mental  
hospitals and 27,000 inmates in the state's prisons and jails, 
Jacobs said. Today, there are just 4,500 mental hospital beds in 
California, and 160,000 inmates in the state's prisons. 
</P>
<P>
	Since California's sex predator law was passed in 1995, the  
state's two hospitals previously designated for the criminally 
insane, Atascadero in San Luis Obispo County and Patton in San 
Bernardino County, have become overcrowded. That in turn has pushed 
``medium- to low-risk'' criminal mental patients to Napa and to 
Metropolitan State Hospital in Norwalk, which also has increased 
security. 
</P>
<P>
	The change at Napa, which is California's oldest mental hospital  
and the county's largest employer with 2,100 workers, has been 
profound. As part of the $10 million security upgrade, police now 
check every car and frisk each visitor. 
</P>
<P>
	This hasn't exactly been heralded by the Chamber of Commerce,  
which prefers to direct the area's 5 million yearly visitors to 
Napa Valley's wineries and spas. 
</P>
<P>
	But state health officials say they have an obligation to treat  
all the mentally ill, including those with criminal records. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly some of these people who have been arrested have  
serious mental illnesses and they need treatment,'' said Stephen 
Mayberg, director of the state Department of Mental Health. 
</P>
<P>
	At Napa, murderers, rapists and arsonists wear khaki uniforms  
and are housed separately from the civilly committed patients, who 
live outside the newly fenced-in wing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I actually feel safer coming to work. People are more in tune  
to security and safety,'' said hospital spokeswoman Lupe Rincon. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, employees must now wear electronic security badges and  
use shuttle buses to get around. And visitors to the criminal side 
must surrender their purses and can't bring in gifts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost impossible to have a therapeutic environment''  
with all this security, Jacobs said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital staff said it's virtually impossible to escape from  
the secure wing. But that hasn't appeased the hospital's neighbors, 
who would have preferred that the lush, tree-lined property be 
converted into an office park in this community 40 miles north of 
San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	They worry that with the security will come an ever-more violent  
population. 
</P>
<P>
	Napa real estate agent R.Q. Williams also scoffs at the  
hospital's construction of a giant berm to shield the fence from 
wine-country visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's going to fool some people, but people that know and  
even visitors are going to ask, `What's going on over there?''' 
said Williams, who has lived in Napa for 25 years. ``It just isn't 
the image that we want to project.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
