<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Issues Arise in Orioles-Cuba Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Federal aviation officials, at the request of  
the FBI and security officials, said today they have banned 
low-level flights over Camden Yards on Monday, when the Baltimore 
Orioles will play the Cuban national team. 
</P>
<P>
	A New Jersey congressman said he would appeal the decision,  
which he said prevents groups from hiring planes to tow banners 
with messages opposing Cuban leader Fidel Castro or urging players 
to defect. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration said flights lower than  
1,500 feet will be banned from 1 p.m. until midnight within three 
miles of the stadium. Fire, police and media aircraft are exempt 
from the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Flights over 1,500 feet will need clearance from Baltimore air  
controllers, which is the usual procedure, said Paul Turk, an FAA 
spokesman in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an unprecedented restriction of First Amendment rights  
without any validation of security concerns,'' said U.S. Rep Bob 
Menendez, D-N.J. ``When did a banner calling for freedom or urging 
people to seek political asylum became a national security risk?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Menendez planned to protest the decision to the FBI and the FAA,  
said his spokeswoman, Yvette Mendez. 
</P>
<P>
	The request, made by Neil Gallagher, the FBI's assistant  
director for national security, said air space was the greatest 
security vulnerability at the event, according to Mendez. 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone call Friday by The Associated Press seeking comment  
from the FBI's public affairs office in Washington was not 
immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Cuban-Americans from New Jersey had planned to hire  
commercial banner towing services to fly anti-Castro and 
pro-democracy messages over the stadium, Mendez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban-American pilot Jose Basulto, president of the Miami-based  
Brothers to the Rescue, has also hinted he may fly over the 
stadium. Basulto said he flew just outside Cuban air space during 
the first game between the Orioles and the Cuban team in Havana in 
March, but did not drop leaflets as planned because of unfavorable 
wind conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Basulto, a veteran of the U.S.-sponsored invasion of Cuba in  
1961, refused to say Friday whether he would violate the FAA order. 
</P>
<P>
	``We reserve the right as guaranteed by the constitution to  
express ourselves. Whether or not we do that, you're just going to 
have to wait and see,'' Basulto said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban-American groups planning to protest against the Castro  
regime have complained repeatedly about the tight security measures 
imposed by the Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles have said they plan to enforce bans on flags,  
musical instruments and other items, and may ask fans who chant to 
leave if it disturbs other fans. Banners will be allowed only 
between innings, and will not be allowed if they are political or 
commercial, the team has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown University law professor and former Massachusetts  
congressman Father Robert Drinan said the Orioles' position might 
not stand up in court. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they allow things between innings and they allow someone to  
bring in something for the Boy Scouts, for example, then they can't 
be the judge of what is political speech,'' said Drinan, a member 
of the advisory board of the American Civil Liberties Union and an 
opponent of the U.S. embargo of Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Free speech rights are clearly guaranteed on city streets and  
Maryland Stadium Authority property outside the stadium gates, the 
Maryland chapter of the ACLU said Friday. The right to use banners 
and signs, however, is less clear inside the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though the stadium is government-owned property, once it  
is leased by the Orioles, they may have control over how attendees 
conduct themselves, including whether they display banners'' the 
ACLU statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
