<DOCNO> APW19990430.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 06:37:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Service Disrupted to Online Bankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Customers at 21 banks, including First Union  
Corp., that use CheckFree for electronic banking services may be 
finding their transactions aren't quite glitch-free. 
</P>
<P>
	Some users of Quicken or Microsoft's Money financial software  
have reported problems either logging on or in getting ``kicked 
out'' before they were ready, said Terrie O'Hanlon, a CheckFree 
spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Customer by customer, the experience is different,'' she said,  
adding that up to 500,000 customers potentially could be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks that use a new transaction processing system called  
Genesis the ones having problems. CheckFree began switching banks 
to the new system six months ago, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief operating officer Pete Sinisgalli said in a statement  
workers had trouble diagnosing the ``root cause'' of the problem, 
but on Thursday believed they had identified it. 
</P>
<P>
	``(We're trying) to resolve this issue as quickly as possible to  
restore uninterrupted service for consumers,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union, the nation's sixth-largest bank, was putting  
together special instructions and information for customers on its 
Web page. The Charlotte, N.C.-based First Union has some 16 million 
customers in the eastern United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of our customers are affected. We don't know how many at  
this point,'' said spokeswoman Danielle Deabler. She estimated the 
total number of customers who bank online as in the ``hundreds of 
thousands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said First Union would work with CheckFree to make sure  
customers weren't charged late fees caused by the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Based in the Atlanta suburb of Norcross, CheckFree Holdings Co.  
has some 2.8 million customers and helps provide electronic payment 
services at 350 institutions. Founded in 1981, the company has 
1,800 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a small percentage of Americans use such services, largely  
because of unfamiliarity or concerns about reliability and 
security. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:24:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Govt. Bonds Plummet / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury bonds staged the steepest one-day fall  
in two months as signs of unexpected economic strength rekindled 
inflation jitters today. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond tumbled 1 7/8  
points, or by $18.75 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, shot up to 5.66 percent from 
Thursday's 5.52 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the biggest drop since Feb. 25, when the long-term  
Treasury fell 2 1/32 points. It was the highest yield since the 
5.67 percent of April 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The rout began after the government reported Friday that the  
U.S. economy expanded at a 4.5 percent annual rate in the first 
three months of the year, much stronger than expected. The selling 
intensified at midmorning as a manufacturing group in the Midwest 
reported the industrial economy was blistering in April as the 
second quarter began. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports raised fears among traders that the economy would  
overheat, despite evidence inflation remains tame. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eventually, down the road, the worry is the Federal Reserve  
might raise short-term interest rates'' to cool off the economy, 
said Maury Harris, chief economist at PaineWebber Inc. While Harris 
believes that won't be necessary, he said the strong economic 
figures Friday clearly surprised traders. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising inflation reduces the value of fixed-income investments,  
such as bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The sharp retreat in bonds also undercut stocks and set back a  
charge toward the 11,000 barrier by the Dow Jones industrial 
average. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell 3/16 point to 5/16 point, while intermediate maturities 
dropped between 17/32 point and 31/32 point, reported Bridge 
Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on three-month Treasury bills was 4.54 percent as the  
discount rose 0.05 percentage point from late Thursday to 4.43 
percent. Six-month yields rose to 4.64 percent, while the discount 
increased 0.07 percentage point to 4.47 percent. One-year yields 
jumped to 4.76 percent as the discount rose 0.08 percentage point 
to 4.53 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, held steady at late Thursday's rate of 4.94 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 123 1/2 from 124 3/16 late Thursday. 
The average yield to maturity rose to 5.28 from 5.24 percent late 
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
