<DOCNO> APW19990430.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NHL Playoff Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The New Jersey Devils are a team still trying to find its rhythm  
in the Stanley Cup playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	So defenseman Scott Stevens hopes they take a page from Tuesday  
night's 4-2 victory at Pittsburgh when they face the Penguins in 
Game 5 of their Eastern Conference series tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to finish our checks, but the bottom line is we want  
to play our game like the other night,'' said Stevens, whose team 
is tied 2-2 in the best-of-7 series, which resumes at the 
Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to play the same way we did the last game. We have to  
play a convincing game, in people's faces, and make it 
uncomfortable for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The top-ranked Devils won the opener 3-1, then lost the next  
two, 4-1 and 4-2, before their Game 4 win. 
</P>
<P>
	In other games tonight, it will be Philadelphia at Toronto, St.  
Louis at Phoenix, Boston at Carolina and San Jose at Colorado. The 
Philadelphia-Toronto and Boston-Carolina series are each tied 2-2, 
while Phoenix leads St. Louis 3-1 and Colorado leads San Jose 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no games Thursday night.  
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins have played three straight games without  
league-leading scorer Jaromir Jagr, sidelined with a groin injury. 
They were 2-1 without him. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr said Wednesday he would play in Game 5, but there was some  
doubt following workouts on Thursday, when the star forward left 
practice early and didn't talk to the media. A decision on his 
availability was expected after this morning's skate or shortly 
before gametime. 
</P>
<P>
	With or without Jagr, Devils goaltender Martin Brodeur thinks  
the Penguins will be tough. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are not going to give us anything,'' he said. ``Sometimes  
when you come in as the first seed and you play the eighth seed, 
you feel you are going to get the chance to win. But these guys 
won't beat themselves. We are going to have to beat them and that's 
what's surprising.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers have also been somewhat of a surprise against the  
Maple Leafs. Like the Penguins, they're missing a superstar 
forward, Eric Lindros, who is recuperating from a collapsed lung. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers tied the series with an impressive 5-2 victory on  
Wednesday. Philadelphia has outshot Toronto 134-71 in the first 
four games, even more surprising because the Maple Leafs were the 
top scoring team in the NHL this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their forechecking has produced most of their scoring  
opportunities,'' Maple Leafs coach Pat Quinn said. ``That's where 
they've been good all season, and for years, and we haven't been 
able to nullify it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins-Hurricanes series returns to Carolina following  
Boston's 4-1 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are at most three games left in this series, so there's  
not a lot of time to wait now,'' Carolina coach Paul Maurice said. 
``I'm happy we've been able to push this thing as far back as we 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks showed the Avalanche they weren't going to go quietly  
with a 4-2 victory Wednesday night in Game 3 after losing the first 
two at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've still got the upper hand,'' San Jose defenseman Bill  
Houlder said. ``We've got some momentum, but momentum is only going 
to last so long -- like the first three or four minutes of the next 
game, if that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Momentum is also the word in the Blues-Coyotes series. The  
Coyotes' 2-1 victory Tuesday night was their third straight after 
they lost the opener. Many of the Phoenix players think Game 4 was 
their best of the series, resulting in a quiet confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``As much as we were happy about winning two games in St. Louis,  
I'd say 15 minutes after Tuesday's game everybody was 
businesslike,'' Rick Tocchet said. ``On the bus, there was no music 
playing, no partying going on. Guys were back to earth. It was just 
a quiet atmosphere. As a veteran player, I love seeing that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:16:03 </DATE_TIME>
