<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Jockey Fighting Back for Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Patrick Valenzuela's intense brown eyes  
gaze across the nearly empty Santa Anita racetrack. The noise from 
winner's circle celebrations and cheering fans is a distant memory. 
</P>
<P>
	So are his days of being first out of the starting gate, urging  
his mount to the lead before the other horses could react. Once in 
front, Valenzuela often stole the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a brilliant rider,'' said Pete Pedersen, a steward at  
Southern California tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	In May 1989, Valenzuela was 26 and at his peak, riding Sunday  
Silence to victories in the Kentucky Derby and Preakness. It didn't 
last. 
</P>
<P>
	Five months later, he was suspended for testing positive for  
cocaine, beginning a descent into drugs and alcohol that plagued 
him for the next 10 years. There were stretches of unexplained 
absences, suspensions and stints in drug rehab for the jockey who 
won nearly 3,000 races and $95 million in purses. 
</P>
<P>
	His share of that money is gone, frittered away on drugs and  
gambling. Today, Valenzuela is only a visitor at Santa Anita. The 
man who once had five vehicles in his driveway arrives in a beaten 
up white car, borrowed from his brother-in-law. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate that I became so successful so quick and  
didn't know what to do with my money, didn't know how to handle it 
and thought it would last forever,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, Valenzuela works pulling weeds in a nursery for $10  
an hour, knowing he once earned his current weekly salary in a 
single day at the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard labor, and it makes me realize that being a jockey  
is a pretty easy living,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a black baseball cap bearing a red question mark, the  
36-year-old Valenzuela talks of another comeback in a sport once 
awed by his talent but now wary of his broken promises. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really want to be back racing. I really want to ride,''  
Valenzuela said. ``The racetrack is my life. This is the only 
livelihood I know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the only time he's at a track now is to attend  
three-times-a-week meetings for recovering alcoholics and drug 
addicts. Valenzuela said he last used drugs in December, stopping 
because, ``It just didn't feel good anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We see Patrick on a regular basis and he's trying to get his  
life in order,'' said Don Murray, executive director of the Winners 
Foundation, a nonprofit support group that helps racetrack 
employees with their problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's impossible for me to predict who's going to make it or  
not. If you're the least bit rebellious, this idea keeps creeping 
in your head, `Nobody can tell me whether I can drink or not.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that Valenzuela would have listened to anyone. He said he  
first tried marijuana at 17 -- the same year he won his first Santa 
Anita Derby aboard Codex in 1980. Then he got into cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was social to go out and have a line, but me, I couldn't  
stop at a line. I had to go for a whole pile,'' he said. ``Here 
were women who loved me and here was this powder, and I couldn't 
understand why I was going to the powder. I was destroying 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At times, he would go months without using drugs. Success always  
found him again. In 1990 he won riding titles at Hollywood Park and 
Del Mar, and won two $1 million Breeders' Cup races. He would go on 
to win four more Breeders' Cup races. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took that for granted,'' Valenzuela said. ``I would always  
come back and make it to the top and then ... do drugs and party 
until I was blue in the face and couldn't come to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela admitted he rode when he was hung over, but not when  
he had been drinking or using drugs. Instead, he just disappeared, 
stiffing owners and trainers from California to New York to 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela's jockey's license was suspended in 1997 after he  
failed to fulfill his riding commitments at Santa Anita. Donald 
Calabria, his lawyer, was to meet Sunday with stewards at Hollywood 
Park to seek a license for Valenzuela to exercise horses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to show the (California Horse Racing) board, stewards  
and race industry who this young man is and what he's put behind 
him,'' Calabria said. ``He's confronted his demons. ... Just let 
him know what the perimeters are so he can earn a living exercising 
horses and not working in a nursery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela hasn't been on a horse since December 1997, when he  
was thrown off and tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right 
knee. He said he weighs 130 pounds, about 15 pounds over his riding 
weight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm more of an asset to the game than I am destructive  
to it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedersen is one of three stewards who will hear Valenzuela's  
case. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd be most interested in what he's doing and not what he  
intends to do,'' Pedersen said. ``He's about as likable as you'd 
find under normal circumstances. Nobody knows what goes through his 
mind when the pressure gets there. He hasn't handled pressure that 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if he is granted an exercise license, Valenzuela knows he  
faces a tough time persuading trainers to allow him to work their 
expensive thoroughbreds. 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela had another setback recently when he was charged with  
robbing a cab driver of $150 at gunpoint. He spent 24 days in jail 
before the charges were dismissed because of a misidentification 
and lack of evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``This hurt me a lot,'' he said. ``My reputation wasn't that  
great, but ... it sure made me look like a criminal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Fame jockey Bill Shoemaker would bet Valenzuela gets  
another chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as he does his work and stays straight, keeps his  
weight down, does everything he should do, I don't see why he 
couldn't do it,'' he said. ``You can't help but like him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela says he's broke and lives with relatives. As he tries  
to recover from alcoholism and drug addiction, he also is dealing 
with the aftereffects of two divorces. He has four daughters -- ages 
15, 13, 10 and 5 -- and is seeking visitation rights with his 
youngest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret a lot of the things I did to myself and to my  
family,'' he said. ``I wish I could've seen from the outside what 
they were seeing. I might have stopped a long time ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If his latest comeback doesn't work out, Valenzuela said he  
might become a trainer. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter if I can ride or not, it's going to be OK,'' he  
said. ``I won't go out and use (drugs) over it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *End Adv for May 1-2    	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mob Lawyer Runs for Mayor of Vegas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Old-timers around here wistfully remember the  
days when the mob ran the casinos, when the likes of Tony ``The 
Ant'' Spilotro and Meyer Lansky kept brutal order in glitter gulch. 
</P>
<P>
	Oscar Goodman remembers the days. He spent decades, after all,  
trying to keep those unsavory characters out of the slammer. 
</P>
<P>
	But now Goodman is courting a different clientele. He wants to  
be mayor of Las Vegas, the mouthpiece for all its citizens. His 
work for wiseguys? Fuhgetaboutit. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people just have the image of the mob lawyer  
things,'' Goodman said. ``But I honest to God believe I'm going to 
be the best mayor Las Vegas ever had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some wince at the prospect of the devil's advocate running what  
used to be a wide-open mob town. But Goodman's candidacy is playing 
so well that he is the front-runner among nine candidates in 
Tuesday's nonpartisan primary election. 
</P>
<P>
	Now 59, the man who played himself in the movie ``Casino'' is  
going after the position being vacated by Jan Jones with the same 
vengeance he used to defend Spilotro, the gangster who reputedly 
placed a rival's head in a vise and squeezed his eyeballs out. 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, his candidacy isn't playing well everywhere in a  
city that has always struggled for respectability. One rival 
candidate, Arnie Adamsen, said the election of Goodman would ``set 
our city's reputation back 50 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Las Vegas Chamber of Commerce has endorsed Adamsen, a  
12-year member of the city council, and the powerful police union 
wouldn't think of supporting a man who fought them in court for so 
many years. 
</P>
<P>
	But Adamsen and developer Mark Fine, one of the other leading  
candidates, have spent much of the primary attacking each other, 
playing right into Goodman's campaign. A poll released this week 
showed Goodman, a registered Democrat, leading the race with 36 
percent support, followed by Fine with 21 percent and Adamsen with 
20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll of 418 registered voters, conducted by Mason-Dixon  
Polling &AMP; Research Inc. for the Las Vegas Review-Journal and 
KTNV-TV, had a margin of error of 5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	If no candidate wins a simple majority next week, the top two  
vote-getters will face off in the June 8 general election. 
</P>
<P>
	Only in the last week has Adamsen gone on the attack, running a  
commercial with clips of Goodman seeming to suggest the government 
should sell drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those are his words, and he either has to defend them or eat  
his words,'' said Adamsen, who bills himself as ``Mr. Traffic 
Signal and Mr. Crossing Guard'' for his work on safety issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those were just sound bites,'' Goodman said. ``Everything was  
tongue-in-cheek. People have to have a sense of humor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodman's more outlandish statements from the past haven't  
seemed to hurt him as he wages a populist campaign portraying 
himself as a defender of the defenseless. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the guy who continued to insist there ``is no Mafia''  
even after the bodies of Spilotro and his brother were found in an 
Illinois cornfield in 1986. Goodman later admitted it might not 
have been a farming accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodman came to Las Vegas in 1965 and got his first big break  
when he was hired as legal counsel to Lansky. But even though he 
reveled in the courtroom battles, Goodman said he never socialized 
with mob clients. 
</P>
<P>
	Adamsen said Goodman would not only make a lousy mayor, but  
would be particularly bad for a city dominated by casino 
corporations. 
</P>
<P>
	But some of Goodman's old adversaries say he would do just fine.  
Former federal prosecutor Lamond Mills, who battled Goodman in 
court, did a television commercial praising his former antagonist. 
</P>
<P>
	``This town has been run by the good old boys and real estate  
developers for a long time,'' Mills said. ``If Oscar is elected 
he'll take this system and stand it on its head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Goodman knows it is his celebrity and not his working  
knowledge of city problems that is making him the front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm colorful and that's what got me in the limelight. If I  
were a podiatrist running for mayor you wouldn't be here,'' he told 
a reporter. ``I don't apologize for one day in my life.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:56:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Economy Grows at 4.5 Percent Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The remarkable U.S. economy grew at a strong  
4.5 percent annual rate in the first three months of this year, far 
above expectations, as consumers spent at the fastest pace in more 
than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported that the solid growth in the  
gross domestic product, the total output of goods and services, 
came despite the fact that the nation's trade deficit, battered by 
overseas economic turmoil, soared to a record level from January 
through March, subtracting 2.4 percentage points from overall 
growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Without this drag from trade, which amounted to a loss of $55.6  
billion in output, the GDP would grown at an even more remarkable 
6.9 percent in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The GDP report underscored the view of most economists that  
Americans are enjoying the best combination of strong growth, low 
unemployment and low inflation in three decades. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Clinton administration, worried about rising  
protectionist pressures spawned by such higher trade deficits, has 
stepped up pressure on Japan and Europe to do more to boost their 
own growth as a way to increase U.S. exports and begin to narrow 
the trade deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4.5 percent growth rate for the first quarter, more than a  
percentage point higher than many economists had been expecting, 
was faster than the 3.9 percent growth turned in for all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The new GDP figure underscored that the U.S. economy has managed  
to prosper despite nearly two years of global currency turmoil that 
has pushed one-third of the world economy into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of overseas markets has been offset by American  
consumers, who increased spending at a 6.7 percent rate in the 
first three months of the year, the largest advance since a 7.2 
percent rise in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong spending has been bolstered by the lowest  
unemployment in nearly three decades, a soaring stock market and 
record highs for consumer confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers are so confident that they are dipping heavily into  
savings to finance their buying binge. The GDP report showed that 
the personal savings rate, savings as a percentage of disposable 
income, dropped to a negative number of minus 0.5 percent in the 
first quarter, an all-time low. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the strong consumer demand and tight labor markets,  
inflation remained a no-show in the first three months of the year. 
A price measure tied to the GDP rose at an annual rate of just 1 
percent, little changed from a 0.9 percent increase in the fourth 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Falling import prices, including big drops last year in  
petroleum prices because of slumping global demand, have played a 
major role in keeping U.S. inflation under control. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the low inflation, the Federal Reserve has been able  
to permit faster economic growth than it would normally sanction 
with the unemployment rate at a 29-year low of 4.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Normally by this time, the central bank would have started to  
raise interest rates to slow economic growth and keep tight job 
markets from pushing inflation higher. 
</P>
<P>
	But a report Thursday showed that employers' cost for wages and  
benefits increased by the smallest amount on record, reinforcing 
the belief of many economists that the Fed will leave interest 
rates alone, possibly for the rest of this year, hoping that growth 
will slow on its own. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4.5 percent total GDP increase in the first quarter was down  
from a 6 percent surge in the final three months of last year, the 
biggest quarterly advance in nearly 15 years, a growth spike that 
was aided by a temporary narrowing in the trade deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first quarter, the 6.7 percent increase in consumer  
spending followed a strong 5 percent advance in the fourth quarter. 
Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of total economic 
activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Business investment, which has been a driving force throughout  
this expansion, now the longest in peacetime history, was strong in 
the first quarter as well, rising by 10 percent with heavy 
investment in computers continuing, a gain in that category of 10.5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Housing construction, which has been propelled by low mortgage  
rates and low unemployment, jumped 15.6 percent, the fastest 
advance in a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
