<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dress Codes Tighten After Shootings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Trench coat bans and school uniform proposals are  
sweeping the country as school districts try to bust up cliques, 
create conformity and keep youngsters from smuggling weapons 
following the Columbine High massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what causes a lot of children to get to the point  
where they break is because of feeling they are outcasts, and a lot 
of it has to do with how they dress and how they are able to 
look,'' said Alderman Sidney Turnipseed, who has asked the county 
school board in the Memphis suburb of Collierville, Tenn., to 
consider requiring uniforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, killed 13 people before  
committing suicide April 20 at their Littleton, Colo., school. The 
teens were part of the so-called Trenchcoat Mafia and shared a 
predilection for dark ``Goth'' culture. 
</P>
<P>
	According to diary entries, their rage stemmed partly from  
feelings that they were social outcasts in a teen-age pecking order 
dominated by popular athletes. Harris and Klebold were apparently 
able to hide weapons beneath their long black coats. 
</P>
<P>
	While there have been other horrifying school shootings over the  
last two years -- in Pearl, Miss.; Jonesboro, Ark.; and Springfield, 
Ore. -- Littleton seems to be the first to prompt such widespread 
discussion on school dress. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of trench coat prohibitions -- in place already in  
Littleton; Portsmouth, N.H.; Henrietta, N.Y.; Hamblen County, 
Tenn.; and Scottsboro, Ala., for example -- consider the rule akin 
to metal detectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dress code measures are aimed at imposing conformity and  
limiting adolescent isolation. President Clinton has said that 
school uniforms or a ``nonprovocative-dress'' code could address 
``this whole black trench coat deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Kids have always had different styles and fashions and fads  
that indicate rebelliousness, but when it reaches a point where it 
can also conceal weapons, then you need to address the potential 
danger,'' said Ron Stern, an elementary administrator in Granite 
City, Ill. The school board in the St. Louis suburb is considering 
a ban on trench coats. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics called such views misguided.  
</P>
<P>
	``Just because we have chains and spikes doesn't mean we're  
gonna go shooting people,'' said Patrick Connor, a 15-year-old 
freshman in the western Massachusetts community of Pittsfield, 
where city council members this week narrowly defeated a bid to 
prohibit ``flamboyant and excessively morbid'' dress. Connor wears 
a jacket with metal studs. 
</P>
<P>
	Dress code opponents said children will poke fun at others no  
matter what they wear, uniforms will not stop kids from forming 
cliques, and bans will do nothing to address the social isolation 
many youngsters feel. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to change the behavior of children who are  
deeply enough disturbed to do something like the two shooters in 
Colorado did,'' said Marc Posner, a researcher at the Education 
Development Center in Newton. 
</P>
<P>
	While such ``knee-jerk'' dress codes won't prevent another  
Littleton, they might reassure some students -- and certainly many 
parents, said Charles Figley, who directs The Traumatology 
Institute at Florida State University. 
</P>
<P>
	But some wondered at what point clothing bans will stop.  
</P>
<P>
	``I almost wish somebody in a football jersey had done it. What  
would they do then?'' asked Sarah Wunsch, an attorney with the 
American Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts, which opposes 
dress codes. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools must do their homework, however, if they want a clothing  
code to survive a legal challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Attire is considered a form of free expression and a  
constitutional right. Dress codes have only been upheld when 
schools could prove that the regulations addressed a specific 
problem, said June Arnette, associate director of the National 
School Safety Center in Westlake Village, Calif. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
