<P>
	Airline Again Cancels Flights  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Alaska Airlines is blaming what it calls an  
illegal slowdown by its mechanics' union for delays in repair and 
maintenance that have forced cancellation of more than 200 flights 
since Sunday. Mechanics are taking longer than expected to repair 
planes, leaving aircraft unready for takeoff, said airline 
spokesman Jack Evans in Seattle. As a result of the delays, 35 
flights were canceled Tuesday, 52 Wednesday, 46 yesterday and 31 by 
mid-morning today, Evans said. Cancellations usually number about 
five a day. The mechanics' union -- the Airline Mechanics Fraternal 
Association -- has been in contract talks with the airline since 
last summer. 

</P>
<P>
	Virgin Won't Fly on New Year's Eve  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Virgin Atlantic Airways said today it will  
ground its 25-plane fleet on New Year's Eve -- to give its employees 
a special night off, not because of any concern that computers will 
malfunction due to Y2K problems. Most airlines are expected to keep 
flying on New Year's Eve, although many are weighing a reduction in 
overseas flights because of uncertainty about how computers in some 
foreign countries and airports will handle the switchover from 1999 
to 2000. Virgin Atlantic's mass cancellation is the first such 
action taken by an international carrier. A British regional 
carrier, Jersey European Airways, has said it won't fly Jan. 1 to 
give its employees time to celebrate. 

</P>
<P>
	Volvo Increases Share in Scania  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Volvo announced today that it has  
increased its stake in rival Swedish truck- and bus-maker Scania to 
about 15 percent. Volvo surprised the business community in January 
with the announcement that it had bought 13 percent of the shares 
in Scania and that it was seeking to merge. But talks between Volvo 
and the Investor holding company, which holds 45 percent of the 
shares in Scania, broke down this spring. Volvo in January sold its 
small but prestigious passenger car division to Ford Motor Co. for 
$6.45 billion, saying it wanted to concentrate on its other 
business areas including trucks, buses, heavy equipment, and marine 
and aeronautical engines. 

</P>
<P>
	Economy Grows at 4.5 Percent Rate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The economy keeps surging, defying  
expectations with a brisk 4.5 percent growth rate for the first 
three months of the year. Economists marveled at the ``wondrous'' 
performance and President Clinton said: ``America's economic 
expansion continues to grow steady and strong.'' First-quarter 
growth in the gross domestic product, a measure of the nation's 
total output of goods and services, was faster than the economy's 
3.9 percent growth for 1998, the Commerce Department said today. It 
exceeded most analysts' predictions by a full percentage point and 
continued the country's longest period of economic expansion in 
peacetime history. 

</P>
<P>
	Justice Probes Underwriting of IPOs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department is investigating  
possible anti-competitive practices in securities firms' 
underwriting of initial public offerings of stock, a department 
spokeswoman said today. The investigation was disclosed in a filing 
with securities regulators by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., Wall Street's 
largest privately held securities firm, which is scheduled for its 
own IPO next week. Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. also confirmed 
today that the department had requested documents. Merrill Lynch &AMP; 
Co. and J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. both declined to confirm or deny that 
they, too, had received a subpoena. Goldman, Sachs said in a 
Securities and Exchange Commission filing today that the department 
had issued it a civil subpoena for information ``with respect to 
its investigation of an alleged conspiracy among securities 
underwriters to fix underwriting fees.'' 

</P>
<P>
	US To Bring 7 New Cases Before WTO  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today targeted  
Europe, India, South Korea, Canada and Argentina for various 
alleged unfair trade practices. U.S. Trade Representative Charlene 
Barshefsky said the administration would bring seven new cases 
before the World Trade Organization in a variety of disputes 
ranging from European aviation practices to Indian barriers 
affecting U.S. automakers. The cases were being brought under a 
section of U.S. trade law that allows the United States to impose 
economic sanctions if a country does not agree to reform. 
Barshefsky said the new raft of trade cases is intended to ensure 
that the United States receives benefits negotiated in global trade 
talks before negotiations begin again in November. 

</P>
<P>
	New Zealander Nominated To Head WTO  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Former New Zealand Prime Minister Mike Moore was  
nominated today to head the World Trade Organization in a close 
race that pitted him against Thailand's deputy prime minister. Ali 
Mchumo, chairman of the WTO's decision-making council, told council 
members he proposed Moore because he had support from 62 nations, 
three more than Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand. The meeting was 
adjourned to let members weigh the nomination. With a new round of 
trade talks looming and a ministerial conference coming up in 
Seattle in November, the role of WTO director-general is regarded 
as key. The organization is responsible for pushing through 
agreements to liberalize global commerce and set free trade rules. 

</P>
<P>
	Brazilian Economy Cuts 3M Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	MAPLEWOOD, Minn. (AP) -- 3M reported a 4 percent drop in  
first-quarter earnings due to the weak Brazilian economy and a 
strong dollar overseas. The Maplewood-based maker of Scotch brand 
tape, scouring pads and other consumer, industrial and electronics 
products, said today it earned $384 million, or 95 cents per share, 
compared with $400 million, or 98 cents a share, a year ago. That 
was above Wall Street's expectations. Analysts surveyed by First 
Call Corp. expected earnings of 91 cents a share. Changes in 
currency exchange rates reduced earnings by an estimated 2 cents a 
share. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan's Jobless Rate Hits Record  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Corporate restructuring efforts helped send Japan's  
jobless rate to yet another record high of 4.8 percent last month. 
The latest government unemployment rate figure reported today 
topped the previous all-time high of 4.6 percent set in February. 
Jobs remain scarce and the situation is unlikely to improve soon, 
government officials say. The jobless data are likely to heighten 
pessimism about the nation's economy, which could further hurt 
chances for a turnaround as worried consumers curtail spending. 
Lackluster consumer spending is a major reason the Japanese economy 
has not been able to rescue itself. 

</P>
