<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Awards F-16 Fighter Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Greece awarded Lockheed Martin a $2  
billion contract for more than 50 F-16 jet fighters as part of its 
program to modernize its armed forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Premier Costas Simitis also announced that France's Dassault  
Aviation will be given a contract for 15 new Mirage 2000-5's and an 
order to upgrade 10 others in Greece's fleet of about 60. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not say how much that contract -- which will include new  
weapons systems for all Mirage aircraft -- was worth. Each plane has 
an estimated cost of about $55 million. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the last such aircraft contract expected to go to an  
American company. Simitis said that from 2005, Greece will begin 
flying the Eurofighter, built by a four-nation European consortium 
led by British Aerospace and Dassault. 
</P>
<P>
	Simitis said Greece will buy between 60 and 90 Eurofighters  
after becoming a partner in the consortium. He added that up to 80 
percent of the aircraft will be built here and are expected to be 
delivered by 2010. 
</P>
<P>
	``By deciding today that in the future Greece will participate  
in the Eurofighter program, we have decided on a homogenization of 
the armaments of our air force,'' Simitis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greece currently flies a variety of American and French jets,  
mostly F-16's and Mirage 2000's. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Martin's F-16 beat out Boeing's F-15E, the Mirage and  
Russia's Su-27. The first jets are expected to be delivered in 
about a year. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials are also lobbying Greece for naval and army  
contracts, including the M1-A2 Abrams battle tank. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
