<DOCNO> APW19990430.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 03:14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Snow and rain showers spread across the Rockies early today,  
while a slow-moving storm dumped rain in the Southeast. The rest of 
the country was mostly dry. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure should continue to deliver tranquil conditions to  
the northern United States, from New England west to the upper 
Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Partly cloudy skies were expected in the Lower Mississippi  
Valley and the central and southern Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered thunderstorms, some producing hail, were possible  
along with the rain showers from the Carolinas down to Florida. On 
Thursday, at least two tornadoes hit the Florida Panhandle, 
knocking down trees in parts of Okaloosa County and dumping hail 
the size of large marbles. 
</P>
<P>
	In the western part of the country, a persistent trough of low  
pressure should bring snow to the high elevations of the Rockies 
from Montana all the way south to Arizona. Ten inches could 
accumulate in some areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain showers and scattered thunderstorms should continue in the  
lower elevations across the region, with the strongest storms in 
southeastern Colorado, eastern New Mexico and western Texas. A few 
of these storms could contain large hail, damaging winds or even 
tornadoes. 
</P>
<P>
	In the far West, dry conditions should prevail along the coast.  
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Thursday was 90 degrees at Lake Charles, La. The low was 19 at 
Saranac Lake, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 40s and 50s in the  
Rockies; the 50s and 60s in New England and mid-Atlantic states; 
the 60s and 70s in the Plains, Northwest and Southwest; and the 70s 
and 80s in south Texas and Florida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 07:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Cool on Civility Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some ideas generated at a bipartisan retreat  
aimed at making Congress a more civil place are receiving a cool 
reception from key House Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	They suggested that proposals for fundamental changes in how the  
House runs would not be welcome, partly because they are not 
needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our differing beliefs many times simply result in an honest  
and vigorous debate. Nonetheless, incivility in the House is 
rare,'' said Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., chairman of a House Rules 
subcommittee that held a hearing on the proposals Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lead organizers of last month's congressional weekend in  
Hershey, Pa., touted the benefits of having 190 of the House's 435 
members gather to form across-the-aisle relationships and craft 
solutions to the House's ills. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an experiment and it will succeed only if we have that  
bone-deep understanding that democracy is difficult,'' said Rep. 
Tom Sawyer, D-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	But organizers declined to detail the proposals they will  
include in their final report to House leaders, saying they wanted 
to present them first to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and 
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers intend to set only a few goals and realize they need  
both leaders' cooperation, said Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Linder, though, said that while events such as the Hershey  
retreat are ``very helpful to the level of discourse, wholesale 
changes do not appear to be necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., the committee chairman: ``The  
most important thing we can do to improve civility is to provide 
opportunities for members and their families to get to know each 
other on a more personal level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the first Hershey conference in 1997, organizers pressed  
scores of recommendations, but few were adopted. This time, they 
hope for more success with a narrowly focused effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Minority Democrats -- still smarting that GOP leaders barred a  
censure vote during the impeachment debate and upset over committee 
representation -- vented the most frustrations at the retreat. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus, their suggestions focused more on changing how the House  
operates, while Republican ideas tended toward speaking 
respectfully during debate, said a top Hershey organizer, Rep. Anna 
Eshoo, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the ideas discussed were forming an oversight committee to  
set standards for the majority party's treatment of the minority 
and developing a less grueling schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	For the civility campaigners, the biggest key to change lies  
with House leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who our leaders are set our tone around here,'' LaHood said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:26:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tokyo Exchange Trading Floor Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- During the late 1980s, the daily frenzy on the  
floor of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was a symbol of Japan's energetic 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	But recession has since replaced boom. And today, computers and  
cost-cutting put an end to the 120-year old tradition of 
face-to-face trading on Asia's largest exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge open floor of the Tokyo exchange was once crowded with  
more than 2,000 traders, fighting for position as they used a 
complex sign-language to buy and sell stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, after the end of the trading day, it was the site of a  
closing ceremony replete with confetti and party noisemakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The floor long ago stopped being the center of trading activity.  
Securities companies began switching to faster and more reliable 
electronic trading systems in the early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	By last year, all Japanese stocks could be traded by computer  
while fewer than 10 percent could be traded directly on the floor. 
Only about 100 employees still worked on the floor and trading 
there accounted for a scant 0.2 percent of Tokyo volume. 
</P>
<P>
	Securities companies and the exchange will save money by moving  
those workers to more productive jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, it is an epoch-making event but we don't think much  
about it,'' said Isao Kawanaba, a spokesman for Japan's biggest 
brokerage, Nomura Securities. ``There are very few people working 
there now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura's last floor traders would be transferred to other  
divisions, Kawanaba said. 
</P>
<P>
	Computerization isn't the only reason Tokyo trading has become  
more subdued in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	A prolonged economic downturn and a decade-long decline in stock  
values has forced Japan's biggest brokers to cut back. 
</P>
<P>
	During Japan's ``bubble'' economy, Tokyo's benchmark stock index  
was more than twice its current value. And at the peak of market 
activity in 1988, there was more than twice as much trading as last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Floor trading is still done in New York and Frankfurt, Germany  
but other major exchanges have ceased already and gone completely 
electronic. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1986, stock exchanges in Hong Kong, Singapore, London, and  
Paris have closed their trading floors. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have been traded on a Tokyo exchange since 1878, though  
the market was closed for almost four years from 1945 as the 
country focused its attention on repairing its war-torn economy. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. occupation forces used the trading floor briefly as a gym  
and dance hall before the exchange opened again in 1949, following 
Japan's defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge trading floor, with it's 165-foot-high ceiling, will be  
remodeled for use as a stock and corporate information center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:26:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tokyo Exchange Trading Floor Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- During the late 1980s, the daily frenzy on the  
floor of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was a symbol of Japan's energetic 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	But recession has since replaced boom. And today, computers and  
cost-cutting put an end to the 120-year old tradition of 
face-to-face trading on Asia's largest exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge open floor of the Tokyo exchange was once crowded with  
more than 2,000 traders, fighting for position as they used a 
complex sign-language to buy and sell stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, after the end of the trading day, it was the site of a  
closing ceremony replete with confetti and party noisemakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The floor long ago stopped being the center of trading activity.  
Securities companies began switching to faster and more reliable 
electronic trading systems in the early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	By last year, all Japanese stocks could be traded by computer  
while fewer than 10 percent could be traded directly on the floor. 
Only about 100 employees still worked on the floor and trading 
there accounted for a scant 0.2 percent of Tokyo volume. 
</P>
<P>
	Securities companies and the exchange will save money by moving  
those workers to more productive jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, it is an epoch-making event but we don't think much  
about it,'' said Isao Kawanaba, a spokesman for Japan's biggest 
brokerage, Nomura Securities. ``There are very few people working 
there now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura's last floor traders would be transferred to other  
divisions, Kawanaba said. 
</P>
<P>
	Computerization isn't the only reason Tokyo trading has become  
more subdued in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	A prolonged economic downturn and a decade-long decline in stock  
values has forced Japan's biggest brokers to cut back. 
</P>
<P>
	During Japan's ``bubble'' economy, Tokyo's benchmark stock index  
was more than twice its current value. And at the peak of market 
activity in 1988, there was more than twice as much trading as last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Floor trading is still done in New York and Frankfurt, Germany  
but other major exchanges have ceased already and gone completely 
electronic. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1986, stock exchanges in Hong Kong, Singapore, London, and  
Paris have closed their trading floors. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have been traded on a Tokyo exchange since 1878, though  
the market was closed for almost four years from 1945 as the 
country focused its attention on repairing its war-torn economy. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. occupation forces used the trading floor briefly as a gym  
and dance hall before the exchange opened again in 1949, following 
Japan's defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge trading floor, with it's 165-foot-high ceiling, will be  
remodeled for use as a stock and corporate information center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
