<DOCNO> APW19990430.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 11:24:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Calls Meeting on Violence  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says he's inviting  
representatives of the entertainment industry, religious groups, 
weapons producers and others to the White House in May for a 
strategy session on youth violence. He says there's ``no simple 
single answer'' to the violence that broke out in Colorado last 
week. But he says there shouldn't be any fighting over who is to 
blame. Instead, he says, everyone should be looking for ways to 
take responsibility. He said he has ``listened carefully'' to what 
students, teachers, parents and others have said in the aftermath 
of the Colorado tragedy. 

</P>
<P>
	Jesse Jackson Meets U.S. Soldiers  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson held a prayer  
session with three American POWs today, but was told not to expect 
them to be freed anytime soon. The men were in good health, Jackson 
told CNN, saying ``our country should be proud of them.'' The civil 
rights leader added that the men have been kept isolated from one 
another in a military jail. He brought the men ``letters from 
family members, wives, spouses ... bibles and other religious 
paraphernalia.'' Shortly before the meeting, Assistant Foreign 
Minister Nebojsa Vujovic said the men's release ``is not on the 
agenda.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Panel Sets Up Kosovo Vote Showdown  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Setting up a showdown vote Monday, a committee  
today sent to the Senate without recommendation a proposal to widen 
President Clinton's authority to wage war in Yugoslavia. Senate 
leaders indicated they would try to kill the proposal, which would 
allow use of ground forces. The 14-4 vote by the Senate Foreign 
Relations Committee, sending the measure to the floor without a 
recommendation, comes as the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia 
intensifies. The committee was so deeply divided that the only 
motion to win a majority was the one to send it to the floor 
without a recommendation. 

</P>
<P>
	Terrorism Death Toll Hits Record  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Terrorism took a record-high toll around the  
world in 1998, with 741 people killed and 5,952 injured. The 
bombings at two U.S. embassies in Africa caused many of the 
casualties. About 40 percent of the worldwide attacks -- or 111 of 
them -- were aimed at U.S. targets. Seventy-seven were bombings of 
multinational oil pipelines in Colombia. The State Department, in 
its annual report to Congress, made no changes in listing Cuba, 
Iran, Iraq, Libya, North Korea, Sudan and Syria as sponsors of 
terrorism. The bombing at the U.S. Embassy in Kenya last August 
killed 291 people. The attack in Tanzania killed 10. 

</P>
<P>
	Colo. Deputy Was Warned About Gunman  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The sheriff's deputy stationed at Columbine High  
School had been keeping an eye on gunman Eric Harris for about a 
year before last week's massacre, officials confirmed today. The 
sheriff's deputy stationed at Columbine, Neil Gardner, received a 
report in March 1998 that Harris was detonating pipe bombs, the 
Denver Rocky Mountain News reported today. Sheriff's spokesman 
Steve Davis today confirmed that Gardner had been watching Harris 
``for quite some time,'' but without proof of a chargeable offense, 
there was nothing that he could do. 

</P>
<P>
	Bus of Deaf Children Crashes  
</P>
<P>
	BRAIDWOOD, Ill. (AP) -- A bus carrying deaf children to a  
spelling bee flipped over on Interstate 55 today, killing one man 
and injuring 23 people, one critically. The bus was carrying deaf 
schoolchildren from the John Powers Center in Vernon Hills, a 
Chicago suburb, to the gathering in downstate East Peoria when it 
crashed near Braidwood, about 50 miles southwest of Chicago. The 
man who died was the father of a girl on the bus. A 31-year-old man 
is in critical condition at Provena Saint Joseph Medical Center in 
Joliet. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Bring 7 New WTO Cases  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today targeted  
Europe, India, South Korea, Canada and Argentina for various 
alleged unfair trade practices against American companies. U.S. 
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said the administration 
would bring seven new cases before the World Trade Organization in 
a variety of disputes ranging from European aviation practices to 
Indian barriers affecting U.S. automakers. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 26; Nasdaq Gains 10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 26.34 points at 10,852.04. Gainers on the New York Stock 
Exchange led losers 1,449-1,425. The Nasdaq was up 10.92 at 
2,539.36. 

</P>
<P>
	GM Plans Ads During 2002 Olympics  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Despite revelations that Salt Lake City officials  
bribed members of the International Olympic Committee, General 
Motors Corp. is moving ahead with plans to use the Olympics as a 
marketing platform to boost its slumping U.S. market share, the 
Detroit News reported today. GM signed a $1 billion pact in July 
1997 to become the official car and truck of the U.S. Olympic 
Committee through the 2008 Olympic games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  

</P>
</TEXT>
