<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:55:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Firms Blamed for Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most people believe credit card marketing to  
people under the age of 21 should be restricted, according to a new 
survey by the Consumer Federation of America. 
</P>
<P>
	A majority of people also believe credit card companies share  
the blame with debtors for the rising tide of personal 
bankruptcies, according to the survey released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighty percent of respondents said they supported proposals to  
restrict credit card marketing to people under the age of 21, while 
17 percent opposed them. The remaining 3 percent didn't know or 
didn't answer. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, 74 percent of those polled said the credit card networks  
were at least partly responsible for the alarming increase in 
bankruptcy filings, while 22 percent said the companies were not 
responsible for it. Four percent of those polled said they didn't 
know, or refused to answer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Consumer Federation concluded, in a separate report on  
credit card debt, that consumers recently have exercised more 
restraint while card issuers have expanded their marketing and 
lines of credit. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings come as legislation that would make it harder for  
people to erase their debts in bankruptcy court advances in 
Congress. This week, parallel bills cleared the House and Senate 
Judiciary Committees and are now awaiting votes by the two 
chambers. 
</P>
<P>
	The bipartisan legislation, being pushed by banks, credit card  
companies and retail businesses, is opposed by consumer groups, 
unions, civil rights groups and some Democratic lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Credit card issuers are shameless to lobby for personal  
bankruptcy restrictions while they aggressively market and extend 
credit,'' said Stephen Brobeck, the Consumer Federation's executive 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	He was joined at a news conference by officials of Consumers  
Union, U.S. Public Interest Research Group and the United Auto 
Workers union. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for the American Bankers Association couldn't  
immediately be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the strong economy, the number of Americans filing  
personal bankruptcies last year reached a record 1.4 million, up 
more than 300 percent since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks, big credit card networks, notably Visa and MasterCard,  
and retail-business groups say their losses from forgiven debts in 
bankruptcy have forced them to raise interest rates for consumers 
who handle credit responsibly. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Chapter 13 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, people must repay  
their debts according to a court-ordered plan. Credit card 
companies complain that too many people take shelter under the more 
lenient Chapter 7, which erases debts, when they could afford to 
restructure debts under Chapter 13. 
</P>
<P>
	But consumer groups and other opponents maintain the legislation  
favors corporate profits over the needs of families struggling with 
debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone survey on bankruptcy blame, conducted by Opinion  
Research Corp. from April 22-25, covered a national sample of 1,011 
adults. The margin of error is plus or minus 3 percentage points. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
