<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Gear for `Dirty Election' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Breaking ideological barriers, India's  
major political parties are groping for new friends among old 
enemies in what the prime minister predicts will be a ``dirty 
election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Based on their recent performance at the polls, the Hindu  
nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party of Prime Minister Atal Bihari 
Vajpayee and the Congress party of his main political rival, Sonia 
Gandhi, are unlikely to win a parliamentary majority on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	With another coalition government appearing inevitable, the two  
parties are already racing to align with the dozens of regional or 
special-interest parties that have emerged in recent years, each 
with tiny pockets of influence that could prove critical. 
</P>
<P>
	``This election is not going to be easy,'' Vajpayee was quoted  
as saying in Saturday's edition of the weekly newspaper, India 
Today. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is going to be a dirty election,'' he said. ``We are in the  
midst of a do-or-die election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Vajpayee lost his majority by a single vote.  
Already new alignments are emerging. 
</P>
<P>
	At least two partners in Vajpayee's coalition -- the Samata Party  
of Defense Minister George Fernandes and the regional Trinamul 
Congress -- this week sought an electoral alliance with a socialist 
group they had previously assailed in Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	From the opposition benches, Ramvilas Paswan, a powerful leader  
of the underclass and longtime Vajpayee critic, indicated he would 
support Vajpayee's party. A southern Indian party known by its 
Tamil acronym, DMK, has already switched sides and is Vajpayee's 
newest ally. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1989, no single party has won enough votes to come to  
power alone. All but one of the seven coalition governments since 
then have fallen within about a year after taking office when 
alliances snapped under coalition strains. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee sewed together 19 disparate parties into a coalition a  
year ago. By earlier this month, it had reduced to 16. His party 
lieutenants are now trying to bind them together with a common 
election manifesto. 
</P>
<P>
	The centrist Congress party also is seeking support from  
regional groups in India's 31 states and federally run territories. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress announced Friday that Mrs. Gandhi would run for a seat  
in Amethi, a farming constituency in the northern state of Uttar 
Pradesh once represented by her slain husband, former prime 
minister Rajiv Gandhi. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be the first election contested by Mrs. Gandhi, who is  
being projected as a candidate for prime minister. To qualify for 
the post, she must acquire a seat no later than six months after 
taking office. 
</P>
<P>
	An even larger issue is her ancestry. Italian-born, Mrs. Gandhi  
adopted Indian citizenship only 16 years after her marriage. Some 
Indians say only natural-born citizens should qualify for prime 
minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Another problem for Congress is that some alignments that might  
be acceptable at the national level are rejected at the state 
level, where the parties may be competing for the same class of 
voters. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times of India highlighted the mind-boggling political  
arithmetic in a front-page cartoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your calculation of tie-ups and alignments is too risky,''  
said one character, filling a chalkboard with complicated 
equations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find at the end we will be cooperating with our sworn  
opponents.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
