<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed early  
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting conflicting views 
about the outlook for U.S. farm products. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat and soybean futures were pressured by  
heavier-than-expected deliveries of supplies for the May contract -- 
a sign that farmers are settling for lower prices amid fears 
matters will become worse in the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But corn and soybeans found some support on conflicting  
forecasts for weather next week in Midwest growing regions. The 
National Weather Service is calling for above-normal rainfall, 
which could delay fieldwork. But some private forecasters are 
saying skies will remain clear at least through Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also found support in some contract months, moving higher  
on marginal export demand and news the government made another 
large purchase for donation to needy countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.66 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1/4 cent to $2.19 a bushel; July oats fell 3/4 cent to $1.18 3/4 
a bushel; July soybeans were unchanged at $4.48 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and lean hogs futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle and pork bellies 
retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .05 cent to 61.67 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 71.27 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .08 cent to 58.65 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .40 
cent to 58.55 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
