<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Campaign Aides Working for Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senior advisers to Dan Quayle's 2000  
presidential campaign voluntarily went without paychecks recently, 
padding his fund-raising totals for the public reporting period 
that ended March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is very common in campaigns. There is an understanding  
that you have to do whatever is needed to put the FEC report in the 
best possible light,'' campaign spokesman Jonathan Baron said. 
``Nobody's here for the money and that's the way it should be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Top officials of former American Red Cross President Elizabeth  
Dole's campaign also were not paid in March, nor was anyone who was 
working for publisher Steve Forbes' campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle reported raising $2.1 million in the first quarter of  
1999, second only to early front-runner Texas Gov. George W. Bush 
in a field of at least 10 potential candidates. Much of that money 
was raised through direct mail, which is expensive; he spent $1 
million on fund raising. 
</P>
<P>
	The former vice president had 35,251 contributors, more than the  
23,339 people who gave to Bush. Overall, Quayle spent $1.6 million 
on the campaign. He would have spent even more without the help 
from a number of senior staff who did not get paychecks at the end 
of the reporting period. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the Quayle campaign ran into the red. He had reported  
debts of $675,788, compared with a campaign bank account balance of 
$500,443. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander was the only other  
candidate to run a deficit during the first three months of 1999. 
He reported owing $212,405 and having just $86,916 in the bank. 
Spokesman Steve Schmidt said everyone was paid regularly. ``Nobody 
had to defer payroll to artificially inflate the FEC reports,'' 
Schmidt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Dole campaign officials were not paid during March, FEC  
reports show. Campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer did not return a 
phone call Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes' paychecks are being issued two weeks behind the pay  
period, meaning that the first checks went out in April. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a standard accounting procedure,'' spokeswoman Juleanna  
Glover Weiss said. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, advisers for GOP nominee Bob Dole missed paychecks to  
help the campaign get through lean times. Baron said Quayle is 
having no trouble meeting his payroll, though he knows fund-raising 
will be a major challenge in 1999 and 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be nip and tuck all the way through because  
there's a big field and we're a resurgent campaign,'' Baron said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
