<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Doubts It Can Repay Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's foreign debts are simply too large for  
the country to repay over the next decade, the finance minister 
said Friday in a stark assessment of the country's long-term 
financial problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Mikhail Zadornov's comments were in line with what private  
economists have been saying, and the Russian government has warned 
for some time that it will have to restructure the country's $150 
billion in foreign debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Zadornov was unusually frank in acknowledging that Russia  
won't be able to meet its debt obligations for years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if the economic situation changes drastically, we will  
not be able to make foreign debt payments over the next 10 years 
according to the original schedule,'' Zadornov said, according the 
Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Russia had been paying back several billion  
dollars a year on its foreign debts. But the debt service jumped to 
$17.5 billion this year and will remain in that neighborhood for 
years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia would have had trouble coming up with that kind of money  
under any circumstances, but an economic crisis that hit last 
August has been bleeding the country's hard currency reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	The reserves now stand at less than $11 billion, a paltry sum  
for a country of Russia's size and population. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia reached a tentative agreement with the International  
Monetary Fund on Wednesday for new loans worth $4.5 billion, but 
that will be used to pay back part of the money Russia already owes 
to the IMF. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has already defaulted on a number of foreign debts in  
recent months, and more missed payments are likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Zadornov said Russia has reached a preliminary agreement with  
the Paris and London clubs -- which represent some of Russia's 
largest international creditors -- to defer payments for 1999 and 
2000, the Interfax news agency reported. But he said the creditors 
need to look beyond that. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Russia can receive the IMF loan, it will need to  
implement a number of reforms, and it's not yet clear whether the 
hard-line parliament will approve them. 
</P>
<P>
	Vladimir Ryzhkov, who heads the pro-government Our Home is  
Russia faction, said lawmakers were unlikely to approve more than a 
few of the bills demanded by the IMF. He said the legislators don't 
want to back unpopular financial measures, particularly with 
parliamentary elections set for December. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF is calling for steps that include an overhaul of the  
nation's banking system and a reduction of the budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF announced a $22.6 billion rescue program for Russia just  
before the August crash, but it cut off lending afterward. Russia 
and the IMF have been negotiating for months on the new loan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
