<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Drunken Driving Levels Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fighting teen-age drinking and driving appears  
to have stalled after a decade of dramatic progress, a new study 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	The prevalence of teen drunken driving fell about 40 percent  
between 1984 and 1997, says the study by Patrick O'Malley of the 
University of Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	But a closer examination of the 1990s showed the progress may  
have peaked in 1992, O'Malley reported Thursday in the American 
Journal of Public Health. Since then, teen drunken driving rates 
have largely held steady -- although O'Malley did find a slight, not 
statistically significant, increase between 1995 and 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	What halted the progress?  
</P>
<P>
	O'Malley theorizes that teen-agers heard a lot more about the  
dangers of drunken driving in the 1980s and early 1990s than they 
do today. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of activity and attention paid to the problem  
between 1984 and 1992,'' O'Malley said, recalling the 1980s passage 
of 21 as the drinking age, major Mothers Against Drunk Driving 
campaigns and much publicity about designated drivers. ``Some of 
that attention has dissipated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government recorded a 59 percent reduction in  
alcohol-related traffic fatalities among 15- to 20-year-olds 
between 1982 and 1997, said alcohol expert Ralph Hingson of Boston 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	But the new findings ``should be of concern,'' because they  
suggest newer teen drivers aren't getting the message, Hingson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said part of the problem is lack of enforcement of ``zero  
tolerance'' laws that are supposed to require that drivers' 
licenses are immediately revoked if teens drive after consuming any 
alcohol. Many teens aren't even aware of those laws, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, at least a third of stores sell alcohol without  
checking the customer's age, added Alexander Wagenaar of the 
University of Minnesota, who studies compliance with alcohol laws. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Malley used data from one of the longest-running surveys of  
teen health issues, run by his university. His findings: 
</P>
<P>
	--In 1984, 31.2 percent of high school seniors reported driving  
after drinking sometime during the previous two weeks. In 1995, 15 
percent did; in 1997, it was 18.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--In 1984, 44.2 percent of high school seniors reported being a  
passenger in a vehicle driven by someone who had been drinking 
sometime during the previous two weeks. In 1995, that had dropped 
to 23.1 percent; in 1997, it was 26.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--When asked about having consumed five or more drinks, 18.3  
percent admitted driving after heavy drinking and 25.4 percent 
admitted being a passenger of a heavy drinker in 1984. In 1997, 
those numbers were 11.5 percent and 15.4 percent, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	--As for peer pressure, 30 percent of seniors in 1984 said their  
friends would strongly disapprove if they drank and drove. That hit 
50 percent in 1992 and has stayed flat, at about 48 percent in 
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
