<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rules in Child Deaths Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- A judge has ruled that four children cannot  
stay in their old home where four other youngsters were believed to 
have been slain. 
</P>
<P>
	Juvenile Judge Michael Murphy on Thursday placed the children --  
a 12-year-old boy and three girls, ages 11 to 8, who have been in 
separate foster homes -- in the custody of a grandmother, Cecile 
Marshall. 
</P>
<P>
	The coroner ruled the four deaths were homicides by  
asphyxiation, but no charges have been filed. Police suspect one of 
the girls might have suffocated the victims, ages 1 to 3, but they 
have no proof. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue before the judge was whether the girl and the three  
other children would be allowed to live together again at the home 
of Regina Moreland. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said there was no evidence that the children were at  
risk from Ms. Moreland, 40, so it was not immediately clear why he 
did not allow the children to return home. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Moreland, who was the grandmother of three of the children  
who died and a great-aunt of the other, maintains that the deaths 
in 1997 and 1998 stemmed from natural causes and that her home is 
safe. She fought for the return of her three children and a 
grandchild. Ms. Marshall is her mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are ``extremely disappointed'' with the judge's  
decision, added Jim Knight, spokesman for the prosecutor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going back into the same situation they were in,''  
added Ann Stevens, a spokeswoman for the Montgomery County Children 
Services Board. ``There's no way that children services can assure 
the protection of these children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a custody hearing in March, a mental health worker said  
the girl police suspect in the deaths told her she sometimes held 
her hand over the mouths of the children to get them to stop 
crying, something her siblings also did. 
</P>
<P>
	But the girl denied causing their deaths, saying she believed  
other family members were responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl's therapist said he believes she is innocent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
