</P>
<P>
	EDS To Cut 5,200 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	PLANO, Texas (AP) -- Electronic Data Systems Corp. will cut 5,200  
jobs, or about 4 percent of its worldwide work force, in an attempt 
to reclaim its leadership in the computer services business. EDS 
chairman and chief executive Richard H. Brown put a figure for the 
first time on a much-anticipated cost-reduction plan. Brown 
promised analysts at a meeting in New York yesterday that the cuts 
would be coupled with more rapid revenue growth. EDS stock was up 1 
11/16 at 53. 

</P>
<P>
	Repsol Offers $13B for YPF  
</P>
<P>
	MADRID, Spain (AP) -- The Spanish energy company Repsol is  
offering $13.4 billion for the Argentine oil giant YPF in a deal 
that would create a more formidable Latin American rival to the 
state oil companies of Venezuela and Brazil. The deal announced 
late yesterday would also be the latest merger in the rapidly 
consolidating oil industry. Last December, Exxon and Mobil agreed 
to merge in a deal now worth nearly $88 billion that will create 
the world's largest oil company. Earlier this year, BP Amoco 
announced it planned to acquire Atlantic Richfield Co. in a deal 
now valued at nearly $30 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Greece Awards F-16 Fighter Contract  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Greece awarded Lockheed Martin a $2  
billion contract for more than 50 F-16 jet fighters as part of its 
program to modernize its armed forces. Premier Costas Simitis also 
announced that France's Dassault Aviation will be given a contract 
for 15 new Mirage 2000-5's and an order to upgrade 10 others in 
Greece's fleet of about 60. He did not say how much that contract -- 
which will include new weapons systems for all Mirage aircraft -- 
was worth. Each plane has an estimated cost of about $55 million. 
Lockheed Martin's stock was trading at 43 11/16, up 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia: We Can't Pay Debts  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia has no chance of making its foreign debt  
payments over the next decade, even if it receives more loans, the 
finance minister said today. And a leading lawmaker said parliament 
will probably approve only one-third of the measures the 
International Monetary Fund wants passed in return for new loans. 
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov told reporters that Russia has 
reached a preliminary agreement with the Paris and London clubs -- 
which represent international creditors -- to defer payments for 
1999 and 2000, the Interfax news agency reported. But he said the 
creditors need to look beyond that. 

</P>
<P>
	China Orders Firms To Get Y2K Ready  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's securities regulator urged listed firms  
today to take the Year 2000 computer problem seriously and purge 
their computer systems of any glitches, the official Xinhua News 
Agency reported. In an open letter, the China Securities Regulatory 
Commission told the 878 listed firms to spend enough money and 
acquire enough expertise to modify and replace key computer systems 
so that they will not fail at year's end, Xinhua said. Experts fear 
that computers that use only the last two digits to mark the year 
will mistake 2000 for 1900 and malfunction. 

</P>
<P>
	Barksdale Invests $5M in Web Grocer  
</P>
<P>
	BELLEVUE, Wash. (AP) -- HomeGrocer.com, an Internet grocery  
shopping and home delivery business, has landed the first 
investment by a group headed by former Netscape Communications 
Corp. president James Barksdale. The Barksdale Group, formed 
specifically to aid new Internet businesses with high growth 
potential, is putting $5 million into the year-old company, a 
spokesman said yesterday. Barksdale formed his venture capital firm 
after receiving $700 million last month when Netscape was purchased 
by America Online for $10 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	GM Plans Ads During 2002 Olympics  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. is moving ahead with plans  
to use the Olympics as a marketing platform to boost its slumping 
U.S. market share. This is despite revelations that Salt Lake City 
officials, who will host the 2002 winter games, bribed members of 
the International Olympic Committee. The controversy has driven 
some sponsors, including Johnson &AMP; Johnson, away. GM signed a $1 
billion pact in July 1997 to become the official car and truck of 
the U.S. Olympic Committee and 41 governing sports groups through 
the 2008 games. GM's stock was up 1 3/8 today at 91 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	`Wallstreet.com' Sells for $1M  
</P>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Eric ``Wall Street'' Wade and his two  
partners sold Wade's Internet name -- wallstreet.com -- for more than 
$1 million. Players Only, a Venezuelan company, bought the name and 
plans to use the site for a gambling game based on stock 
performance. Players Only has said it will offer stock quotes, 
company information and online trading -- along with gambling. Wade, 
a former Albuquerque stockbroker, and a friend registered 
wallstreet.com for $70 in 1994. They had planned to develop a 
full-scale financial services site, but then started getting 
unsolicited offers for the name. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Gross domestic product: grows at 4.5 percent annual rate  

</P>
</TEXT>
