<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Court: UN Official Is Immune </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- The World Court has ruled that a  
senior U.N. representative is immune from multimillion-dollar libel 
lawsuits filed by several Malaysian companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The court granted U.N. Special Rapporteur Param Cumaraswamy  
immunity Thursday for allegedly defamatory comments because the 
remarks made in 1995 were related to his U.N. duties. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's president, U.S. judge Stephen Schwebel, ruled that  
legal immunity should be enjoyed by independent officials working 
as U.N. rapporteurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Cumaraswamy, a former chairman of the Malaysian Bar Council, is  
alleged to have libeled several Malaysian businesses in an 
interview with International Commercial Litigation magazine in 
which he said he was investigating alleged manipulation of the 
Malaysian judicial system. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Court, the highest U.N. judicial organ, said the  
Malaysian government should not have allowed libel lawsuits 
totaling $112 million to be filed against Cumaraswamy. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Friday that he  
accepted the World Court's ruling, the national news agency Bernama 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the United Nations and Malaysia pledged to abide by the  
ruling of the court, formally known as the International Court of 
Justice. Schwebel ordered Malaysia to inform national courts of the 
ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
