<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Pushing Youth Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At a fund-raiser for the state Democratic party,  
Sen. Chuck Schumer spoke of his pleasant anticipation of working 
with the first female senator from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The question is who he meant: the dinner's honoree, Rep. Nita  
Lowey, or another guest -- Hillary Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Still tight-lipped about her political plans, Mrs. Clinton spent  
Thursday in New York and plans to return in eight days for her 
third visit in as many weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton was principal for a day at a junior high school,  
then addressed the $250,000 fund-raiser for the state Democratic 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowey, the guest of honor, plans to run for the Senate seat  
being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000 if Mrs. Clinton 
doesn't. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look forward to working, starting in January 2001, with the  
first woman senator of New York State,'' Schumer told his fellow 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton didn't indicate whether she intends to be that  
woman. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's talked to a lot of people, heard different opinions,  
gotten advice,'' spokeswoman Marsha Berry said. ``She's still 
weighing opinions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Mrs. Clinton's comments throughout the day focused on  
issues related to the high school massacre in Littleton, Colo. At 
both the school and the dinner, she called for a national campaign 
against youth violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady said additional limits should be placed on access  
to weapons for young people, and urged parents and consumers to 
limit their children's exposure to violent movies and video games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to do something about the culture of violence,'' she  
said. ``How do we send a signal to people who produce such media 
and to people who consume it? How do we create the same mind-set 
that turned drunk driving into a socially unacceptable act?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton spent two days in New York City and Long Island  
last week, and is to return to the state May 7 for an AFL-CIO 
meeting in Buffalo on working women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
