<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Washes Out Calif. 500 Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FONTANA, Calif. (AP) -- Umbrellas and ponchos instead of suntan  
lotion and shorts were the order of the day Friday as steady 
showers washed out practice and qualifying for the NASCAR 
California 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Dark skies prevailed over the California Speedway, keeping  
drivers and cars in the garages, and fans huddled under the 
grandstand. It was the first time in the speedway's three-year 
history that rain interrupted the schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've probably helped my golf game watching the Golf Channel,''  
Dale Jarrett joked. ``All we can do is hang out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rain had stopped by late afternoon, allowing an abbreviated  
practice for Saturday's Auto Club 300 Busch Series race. Practice 
for the Winston West 200 was pushed back to Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``You travel all the way across the country and you get one hour  
of practice before the race, so that makes it difficult,'' said 
Jarrett, who was forced out before the halfway point of last year's 
California 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where good notes come into play. We have to go back to  
the first year when we ran the whole race,'' he said. ``We'll look 
at that so we can be best prepared whenever do get that practice 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LABONTE KEEPS ON GOING:* Call him Mr. Consistency. Terry  
Labonte is scheduled to start his 612th consecutive NASCAR race 
Sunday. He hasn't missed one since joining the circuit full-time in 
1979. 
</P>
<P>
	He broke Richard Petty's record of 514 straight starts in April  
1996 at Martinsville, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte is one of just three drivers to complete all 500 laps of  
the first two California 500s, along with Jeff Gordon and Ricky 
Rudd. Labonte finished second in the inaugural race in 1997 and 
third last year. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MARTIN LANDS IN CEMENT:* Mark Martin joined a very short list  
of drivers on the California Speedway's Motor Walk of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin, winner of last year's California 500, put his footprints  
in cement Friday, alongside those of '97 winner Jeff Gordon. Both 
drivers also have bronze plaques marking their victories. 
</P>
<P>
	``The speedway is fantastic,'' Martin said. ``It was way neat to  
win the California 500 last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *VIDEO RACING:* Jeff Gordon's fondness for video games paid off  
against his fellow drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, Bobby Labonte, Mike Skinner, Ward Burton and Jeff Burton  
tested their video driving skills on a Daytona USA game Thursday at 
an Ontario restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, at 27 the youngest of the group, finished first in the  
20-lap race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to admit I've got one of these at home, so I've got a  
little bit of an advantage,'' he said. ``Man, that was an awesome 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The video game race matched each of the drivers with five fans  
randomly selected in a nationwide drawing for the Winston No Bull 5 
sweepstakes. 
</P>
<P>
	If Gordon, Labonte, Skinner, Ward Burton or Jeff Burton wins  
Sunday's race, they'll earn $1 million for themselves and the same 
amount for the fan matched with them. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RACY CLOTHING:* Fashion-conscious women who are race fans don't  
have to settle for buying the usual souvenir T-shirts and baseball 
caps this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Kristi Markel and Wendy Misner have developed a line of  
sportswear for the estimated 40 percent of NASCAR fans who are 
women. The items, ranging from $18 hats to a $55 crop polar fleece 
jacket, were to go on sale Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``As race enthusiasts for almost 20 years, we've seen that most  
fanwear is meant for the male consumer,'' said Markel, co-founder 
of Enginewear. ``This leaves a vastly untapped female market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The line, dubbed ``racy clothing for women,'' also includes a  
lycra body suit and a round neck baby doll T-shirt. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BIRTHDAY BOYS:* Blow up the balloons and light the candles.  
NASCAR drivers Elliott Sadler and Michael Waltrip celebrated 
birthdays Friday. Sadler, a rookie, turned 24. Waltrip turned 36. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale Earnhardt, who won last week at Talladega, turned 48  
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
