<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Laser Co-Inventor, Physicist Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Nobel Prize-winning physicist Arthur  
Schawlow, a co-inventor of the laser, has died at 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Schawlow, who died Wednesday after being stricken with leukemia,  
worked with Charles H. Townes to develop in 1960 the means of 
producing a concentrated beam of light. 
</P>
<P>
	Lasers are now a $3.5 billion industry, used in fiber optic  
telecommunications, scientific research, compact disc players and 
vision correction and other types of surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair received a patent for their invention but didn't profit  
from it because they were working at Bell Labs. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1961, Schawlow joined the physics department at Stanford  
University. In 1981, he won the Nobel in physics for his 
contributions to laser spectroscopy, the study of how atoms and 
molecules react to light. 
</P>
<P>
	Schawlow used most of his Nobel Prize money to start a  
foundation and group home for autistic children. 
</P>
<P>
	Schawlow attended the University of Toronto on a mathematics and  
physics scholarship. A postdoctoral fellowship sent him to Columbia 
University to work with Townes. 
</P>
<P>
	Schawlow married Townes' sister, Aurelia, in 1951. She died in  
1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Schawlow liked to demonstrate his laser ``ray gun'' to students  
by beaming it through a transparent balloon to pop a dark Mickey 
Mouse balloon inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a son, two daughters and five grandchildren.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 02:34:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises, Japanese Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen in Tokyo today  
despite an indication from a top Japanese economic official that 
the government may consider new stimulus steps. The Tokyo stock 
market's main index lost 1.42 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.58 yen at late afternoon, up 0.50 yen from  
its level of 119.08 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its 
overnight New York level of 119.03 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 240.71 points,  
or 1.42 percent, closing the week at 16,701.53 points. The Nikkei 
dropped 15.03 points, or 0.09 percent, Wednesday. Tokyo financial 
markets were closed Thursday for a national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar advanced as interbank dealers bought the U.S.  
currency despite remarks by Japan's Economic Planning Agency chief, 
Taichi Sakaiya, who said in Washington late Thursday that Japan 
would mull measures to stimulate the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakaiya, speaking after meeting with U.S. Deputy Treasury  
Secretary Lawrence Summers, denied that the government was 
considering a supplementary budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sakaiya's comment may suggest there was a progress toward new  
fiscal steps for the economy. But his words are a bit too vague to 
sell off dollars on,'' said Minoru Shioiri, assistant manager of 
foreign exchange at Nippon Credit Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors were waiting for the outcome of the summit  
between Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and U.S. President Bill Clinton 
in Washington on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite some signs of improvement, Japan's economy remains weak  
as the country struggles to bail out of its worst recession in 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 118.95 yen and 119.68 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 126.86 yen, down  
from 127.22 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Japanese technology shares dropped in line  
with the decline of similar shares overnight in New York. Also 
dampening the Tokyo market was Sony Corp.'s recent announcement of 
falling profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentiment among investors turned bearish quickly today following  
the release of fresh data on the state of Japan's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony said Wednesday that its net income plunged nearly 20  
percent in the fiscal year ending March 31 because of recession at 
home and abroad. Sony stock closed today's trading at $93.70, down 
$4.60 from Wednesday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The Management and Coordination Agency said Japan's jobless rate  
climbed to a record high 4.8 percent in March as corporate 
restructuring efforts forced more people out of work. The previous 
record was 4.6 percent, registered in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the agency said spending by Japanese wage earners  
last month fell 3.6 percent from the year-earlier month in real 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 535  
million shares, down from Wednesday's turnover of 677 million 
shares. Declining issues outnumbered advancers 646 to 512, with 163 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 10.52 points, or 0.78 percent, to 1,337.12 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.405 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.465 
percent, pushing its price up to 103.49 yen from 102.94 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Japan will be closed Monday through  
Wednesday because of national holidays. The markets will reopen on 
Thursday. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
