<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Scandal Means Fewer Perks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The damage to the IOC's budget caused  
by the Olympics bribery scandal is hitting home to committee 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Rogge, a senior executive board member and chairman of  
the IOC coordination commission, said Friday that the IOC has 
agreed to cut the cost of services it will demand from Sydney to 
help meet a reduced budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games already  
had announced it will cut $48.7 million from the budget for the 
Games, blaming in part a dropoff in sponsorship from the corruption 
scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge met with Sydney Olympic sponsors on Tuesday and apologized  
for the damage the scandal caused to the games' marketing 
potential. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, we played a role in the difficulties,'' Rogge said  
Friday at the end of commission's visit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will take our responsibilities. By reducing the services  
that SOCOG will have to provide to us, we're going to give them a 
substantial saving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Services to the IOC are included in the host city contract.  
Rogge said IOC members' travel, accommodation and some other 
running costs are paid for by the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said the budget shortfall -- $32.5 million of expected  
sponsor revenue written off and an extra $16 million allocated for 
contingencies -- was not all the IOC's fault. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Knight, president of the organizing committee, blamed  
the sponsorship shortfall on the IOC scandal. He said the IOC 
accepted that ``they are some of the problem and they must go some 
way towards assisting us to resolve it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After visiting venues and being briefed on Sydney's readiness,  
Rogge said preparations were generally on schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Two areas had been singled out for special attention -- the  
budget and technology. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a delay in the implementation and testing of the sport  
results system -- a major headache at Atlanta in 1996 -- has been 
addressed with more personnel and money. 
</P>
<P>
	One venue problem still exists -- some local residents oppose  
part of Sydney's Bondi beach being closed for the beach volleyball. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight said he would consider legal action against the local  
council if it sought to withdraw from an in-principle agreement to 
hold the competition on the beach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans Coming, Orioles Hurting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles would rather have the day  
off. 
</P>
<P>
	When their series with Cuba was first announced last month, the  
Orioles were considered one of baseball's best teams. They were 
also one of its highest-paid teams, with a nearly $80 million 
payroll and a lineup featuring Albert Belle, Cal Ripken and Will 
Clark. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with the rematch at Camden Yards on Monday, the Orioles  
have the worst record in baseball, the fans are booing and manager 
Ray Miller is in danger of losing his job. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken and Clark are on the disabled list, Belle is hitting .243  
and the pitching has been awful. 
</P>
<P>
	Quite plainly, the Orioles have a lot more to worry about than  
facing a Cuban all-star team, the first time a squad from the 
communist nation is playing a major league club in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think this team needs a distraction right now,''  
shortstop Mike Bordick said. ``We'll play hard and play to win, but 
we've got issues that we have to straighten out. First and 
foremost, we have to focus on our season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Almost 300 Cubans, including journalists, retired players and  
students, are expected to fly to Baltimore. Baseball-crazy Cubans 
back home hope the game will be broadcast live on television. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban-Americans from Miami and the New York-New Jersey  
metropolitan area are planning a protest at Camden Yards. They 
regard the game as a public relations coup for Cuban leader Fidel 
Castro. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the game in Havana a month ago, Castro will not be in the  
stands. Neither will President Clinton, or any other high U.S. 
official. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department isn't talking much about the game, except  
to acknowledge that a few of its employees might show up -- if they 
buy their own tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Clinton administration official briefed reporters  
Friday on the nearly sold-out game, but said his name couldn't be 
used. ``We're not in the position of encouraging defection; we're 
not in the position of discouraging defection,'' he said when asked 
about the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	He said no special measures were being taken to deal with any  
defectors but added that Immigration and Naturalization Service 
personnel would likely be at the game. There is also no indication 
the Cubans will be bringing along security personnel to deflect any 
defectors, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibition, which comes in the middle of a 12-game  
homestand, robs the Orioles of one of their two scheduled off days 
in May. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can always use an off day at home. They don't come around  
too often,'' reliever Mike Timlin said. ``But it's on the schedule 
and we've got to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the Orioles traveled to Havana on March 28 for the historic  
first game, there was an air of mystery and excitement. The players 
knew little about Cuba and even less about the national team, which 
had fared well in Olympic competition but had never taken on a 
major league team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like a playoff atmosphere,'' Bordick said. ``It seemed  
like as soon as the game started, then all of a sudden we 
understood it was our country against their country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles got all they could handle before winning 3-2 in 11  
innings. Baltimore is heading into this game after failing to have 
back-to-back wins all season. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a different kind of hoopla this time,'' said catcher  
Charles Johnson, who hit a two-run homer against the Cubans. ``I 
don't think there's the same amount of tension for this game. Part 
of the reason is the way we've been playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller wants to win the game, but not at the expense of ruining  
a starting rotation that has struggled all season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles will start Scott Kamieniecki, who is on the disabled  
list and hasn't pitched for Baltimore this season because of a 
hamstring injury. His start against Cuba is essentially a 
high-profile rehabilitative assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles desperately need some positive signs in a season  
gone awry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it will be something that pulls us together and sets us  
off,'' Timlin said. ``You never know.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
