<DOCNO> APW19990430.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 08:15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Midwest Attendants Want To Unionize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Flight attendants for Midwest Express Airlines  
voted to unionize, becoming the second group of employees at the 
airline to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 360 eligible attendants, 204 voted for Association of  
Flight Attendants representation, according to results the National 
Mediation Board certified Thursday in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted a voice on the job and security for our future,''  
said Sue Stein, one of the attendants who led the organizing drive. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote means the union, affiliated with the AFL-CIO, will  
represent all attendants at the airline. The union asked to begin 
contract negotiations, but no meeting date was set. 
</P>
<P>
	David C. Reeve, the airline's senior vice president of  
operations, said he was disappointed with the result of the 
election, but the Oak Creek-based company supported the employees' 
right to decide the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Midwest Express pilots are the only other unionized group at the  
airline. They are represented by Air Line Pilots Association and 
are negotiating their first contract. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:52:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Wrestles With Picking New Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization was due to make a  
final, desperate effort today to agree on a new leader after moves 
to appoint a former New Zealand premier ended in deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
	Renato Ruggiero of Italy, the WTO's director-general for the  
past four years, is stepping down, leaving the 134-nation body in 
crisis over his replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	A meeting Friday of the WTO's decision-making council bogged  
down in procedural wrangling for eight hours, as supporters of 
Thailand's Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi sought to 
block the nomination of New Zealander Mike Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	Ali Mchumo, the WTO council chairman adjourned the discussions  
until midday today. To avoid leaving themselves without an official 
head, delegates ``stopped the clock,'' meaning that they will treat 
the new meeting as still taking place on April 30, Ruggiero's last 
day in office. 
</P>
<P>
	Mchumo had earlier proposed to delegates that the U.S.-backed  
Moore be approved by consensus since he had the support of 62 
nations, three more than Supachai. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Japan, Malaysia, India and other Asian nations demanded  
a vote. This runs against the WTO's time-honored rule that all 
decisions be reached by consensus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Essentially it became a case of Supachai supporters calling  
for a vote and Moore supporters saying no vote,'' said WTO 
spokesman Keith Rockwell. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, 50, has been involved in trade and foreign policy issues  
as a legislator for more than 20 years, nine of them as a minister. 
He was prime minister for eight weeks before his Labor party lost 
office in 1990. He is a supporter of free trade, but also an 
advocate for underprivileged and less powerful smaller states. 
</P>
<P>
	He is known for his no-nonsense, ``no-baggage'' approach to his  
responsibilities and wants to revamp the public image of the WTO, 
which is generally seen as remote and bureaucratic. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO post is seen as a key one, with a new round of trade  
talks looming and a ministerial conference coming up in Seattle in 
November. The organization is responsible for pushing through 
agreements to liberalize global commerce and set fair trade rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Supachai, backed by Asia and Australia, the Middle East and  
several European countries, was long the front-runner and was 
widely perceived as the candidate of developing nations. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the all-important backing of the United States,  
Moore had support from South America and the Caribbean. In the 
closing stages of the contest he picked up backing in Africa, 
diplomats said, and that tipped the balance. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe was divided between the two candidates, but European  
nations at Friday's meeting all indicated they would go along with 
Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether Mchumo would be able to force through a  
decision -- repeating efforts prior to Friday's deadline all ended 
in failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Many nations fear a leadership vacuum at a time when the WTO is  
caught up in high-profile disputes between the United States and 
European Union over bananas and hormone-treated beef. 
</P>
<P>
	Underlining the sensitivity of the job, the United States on  
Friday targeted Europe, India, South Korea, Canada and Argentina on 
Friday for alleged unfair trade practices against American 
companies and said it would bring seven new cases before the WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
