<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Insurer Head Fired in Bank Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRIESTE, Italy (AP) -- The takeover battle for one of Italy's  
largest banks, Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, on Friday claimed 
the job of the chairman of Europe's third-largest insurer. 
</P>
<P>
	Antoine Bernheim was fired Friday at a board meeting of  
Assicurazioni Generali SpA. Named to replace him was Alfonso 
Desiata, chairman of Generali's 54-percent-owned life insurer 
Alleanza Assicurazioni SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Generali's largest shareholder is the investment bank  
Mediobanca, which wanted Bernheim out because he tried to stay 
neutral in the takeover battle for Banca Commerciale Italiana, the 
fourth-largest bank in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank is in merger talks with Banca Intesa SpA but has also  
received a rival $15.3 billion takeover bid from UniCredito 
Italiano SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Banca Commerciale owns 7.8 percent of Mediobanca and is  
Mediobanca's main outlet for selling the corporate bonds and other 
products it underwrites for virtually every top Italian company. A 
takeover of the bank could threaten the secretive investment bank's 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Generali owns 5 percent of Banca Commerciale. At least half of  
Generali's board members represent Mediobanca or its close business 
allies or are Generali executives close to Mediobanca. 
</P>
<P>
	The relationship between Mediobanca, one of the most powerful  
behind-the-scenes players in the Italian business world, and the 
independent Bernheim has been tense since he took over at Generali 
four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A Frenchman who is a partner in Lazard Freres, Bernheim tried to  
shake up the staid insurer with a series of acquisitions and 
consolidations. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Friday his ouster was initiated ``to settle old  
scores.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
