<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Seeks New Auto Pollution Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency is about  
to propose tough new pollution controls on motor vehicles that for 
the first time would require popular sport-utility vehicles to be 
as clean-running as automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil companies also would have to produce much cleaner gasoline  
under the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The stringent new requirements, some of which would be phased in  
over the next decade, were given the nod this week by the White 
House and could be announced any day, administration officials said 
Thursday. The officials spoke only on condition they not be named. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA has told auto and oil industry representatives that  
dramatic, although technologically feasible, reductions in tailpipe 
emissions and cleaner gasoline are needed if state and local 
officials are to cut smog and soot to meet federal air quality 
requirements as well as reduce dangerous toxic chemicals and soot. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called Tier II auto emission controls would require  
automakers on a fleet average to cut smog-causing chemical 
emissions and other pollution by up to 80 percent and take into 
account SUVs, light trucks and minivans that comprise half of all 
vehicles sold. 
</P>
<P>
	SUVs and pickup trucks currently can emit two and three times as  
much smog-causing nitrogen oxide than automobiles, although some 
models are considerably cleaner. 
</P>
<P>
	In another new twist, the EPA will require that the oil industry  
reduce the amount of sulfur in gasoline by as much as 90 percent 
nationwide, according to sources familiar with the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the auto emissions and gasoline requirements would mirror  
what California already has proposed, although the two plans are 
not identical. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers have argued that they cannot meet the tougher  
tailpipe requirements without low-sulfur gasoline because sulfur 
inhibits pollution control equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	``This decision will define whether or not areas meet their  
federal health-based standards for smog and other pollutants,'' 
said William Becker, whose association represents state and local 
air pollution control officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The association has estimated that the proposed sulfur  
reductions in gasoline alone would cut smog-causing nitrogen oxide 
in half, equivalent to removing 54 million cars from the nation's 
roads. 
</P>
<P>
	The new requirements are not expected to be made final until the  
end of the year and then the automakers will be given until 2004 to 
begin phasing in the cleaner vehicles over a number of years. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulations, considered by EPA officials as the agency's  
most important environmental initiative this year, are expected to 
unleash intense lobbying from the two powerful industries most 
affected -- oil and automobiles -- as both seek to mold it more to 
their liking. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers in recent months have become resigned to the  
prospects of much tougher pollution control requirements for both 
cars and SUVs, but have argued for more time to comply. 
</P>
<P>
	A proposal recently floated by auto manufacturers would cut  
average fleet nitrogen oxide emissions to 0.07 grams per mile for 
all vehicles, including SUVs and light trucks, by 2011. The average 
is 0.4 grams per mile currently for cars and 0.7 grams to 1.1 grams 
per mile for SUVs. 
</P>
<P>
	The automakers' proposal would have a phase-in that was two  
years longer than what the EPA had been considering and would 
condition the reductions on even stiffer sulfur reductions in 
gasoline than the EPA has had in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``To have the cars and trucks converge is a big step forward,''  
Josephine Cooper, president of the Alliance of Automobile 
Manufacturers, said in a recent interview, adding that manufactures 
must have adequate time to comply -- and much cleaner gasoline. 
</P>
<P>
	But with about one in every two vehicles sold now a light truck,  
SUV or minivan, environmentalists have argued that emission 
reduction gains will be lost if these vehicles are not required to 
meet as strict standards as automobiles and more quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, said Samuel Leonard, General Motors' director for  
emissions and fuel efficiency, is that the exhaust from a large SUV 
has to be three times cleaner to meet the same gram-per-mile 
requirement as a car because the engine is doing three times the 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	The automakers have argued that they can't meet the new  
requiremetns unless sulfur levels in gasoline are cut from its 340 
parts per million now to 30 parts per million, or perhaps even 
lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a reduction would add 5 cents to 6 cents a gallon to the  
price of gasoline and require $4 billion to $5 billion in 
retooling, driving some small refiners out of business, the 
American Petroleum Institute has argued. The oil industry has 
proposed limiting low-sulfur gasoline to 22 Eastern states and for 
the time being cutting sulfur only in half. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA, according to sources, has stood firm on insisting  
low-sulfur gasoline be required nationwide. To ease the burden on 
small, mostly Western, refiners, the proposal would provide some 
flexibility, including an extended timetable. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
