<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Winston Championship Talk Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FONTANA, Calif. (AP) -- Seven months and 25 races from the end of  
the Winston Cup season, the top drivers already are being bombarded 
by questions about the championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``It used to be that you didn't even think about that until  
maybe September, or at least midway through the summer,'' said 
Rusty Wallace, who won the series title in 1989. ``These days, it 
starts before Daytona.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rain all day Friday washed out the first day of practice and  
qualifying for the California 500, leaving all the drivers time to 
kill. Inevitably, the rainy day talk turned to the championship 
battle, which currently has Jeff Burton leading Dale Jarrett by 40 
points and teammate Mark Martin by 85 after nine races. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin agrees with Wallace that nobody really thought about the  
championship early in the season when he first came into Winston 
Cup racing in 1981. But that doesn't mean it's a bad thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way it is now, I think a team and driver need to start  
considering points in the 125-mile qualifying race in Daytona,'' 
Martin said. ``You don't want to wreck your good car and have to 
race in the Daytona 500 with something that isn't as good. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I almost think it makes it better. You don't have guys  
doing as many stupid things because they want to make sure they're 
there at the end of the race, getting a decent finish that gets 
them some points.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As proof of his theory, Martin points out that there have  
already been seven race winners this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the end, it puts more cars in the mix, more cars in  
contention. But it takes a lot of the fun out of the year. I didn't 
sleep much the night after Texas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin was referring to the race in March at Texas Motor  
Speedway, where a deflating tire sent him careening into the wall 
for a 34th-place finish. 
</P>
<P>
	The intense Martin blamed himself for the incident because he  
had watched as both Jeff Gordon and Mike Skinner had crashed after 
their right front tires went flat earlier in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I should have enough experience to know that was going to  
happen,'' Martin said. ``I should have driven slower. Jeff Burton 
drove slow enough and finished seventh. I'd have given anything in 
the world to have run seventh, or ninth or 10th that day. I 
couldn't sleep because I was thinking about the 100 points we 
lost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, the two-time defending series champion and winner of  
three of the past four titles, is fifth in the standings, an 
imposing 210 points behind Burton and 61 behind fourth-place Bobby 
Labonte. 
</P>
<P>
	He has fallen into that hole mostly because of three finishes of  
36th or worse, resulting from two accidents and an engine failure. 
Despite early-season problems and that big deficit, Gordon remains 
the choice of many to win another title. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, Jeff Gordon is still the one to beat,'' Jarrett said.  
``He's the only one in the top five who has won a championship. The 
rest of us have to prove we can get it done. 
</P>
<P>
	``You sure can't count those guys out of it. I kind of laugh  
when I hear people saying they're too far back to win the 
championship. Heck, we have 25 more races left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett, who has been third, second and third in the standings  
the last three years, said, ``Anybody who finishes in the top three 
for about six straight races is going to make up a lot of ground, 
and I think those guys could certainly do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At one point last season, Gordon had a run of 17 consecutive  
top-five finishes. He wound up the 1998 season with 13 victories 
after winning just three times through the end of May. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have a year like we had last year, it's easy to say,  
`We're having a horrible year.' Yet we're fifth in the points,'' 
Gordon said. ``We're just trying to get some consistency. We've 
still got time to get it going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Is there too much emphasis on the championship?  
</P>
<P>
	``We can still have a great season even if we don't win the  
championship, but the championship is our ultimate goal every 
year,'' Gordon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
