<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  N. Albania Chaos Hinders Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- Mike McDonagh took all the necessary steps  
to organize an aid convoy in northern Albania -- he hired the 
trucks, got them loaded, and made sure special police armed with 
automatic rifles led the way. 
</P>
<P>
	When gunfire greeted the convoy snaking through the hills above  
Bajram Curri, the six gray-clad policemen jumped out and fired off 
a few bursts, then beckoned the trucks onward. 
</P>
<P>
	It was all in a day's work for international aid agencies  
operating in this impoverished region, where miserable roads, no 
airport or local communications network and general disorder 
combine to make it even harder to help the hundreds of thousands of 
refugees from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're in Europe but in some ways you're at the end of the  
world,'' said Ray Wilkinson, a former journalist now working as 
spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The international relief effort for Kosovo refugees was  
criticized when ethnic Albanians began pouring over the borders 
from the Serbian province after NATO began bombing Yugoslavia on 
March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Caught off guard by the initial wave of scores of thousands into  
Albania, Macedonia and the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, the 
UNHCR and other agencies were slow to set up refugee camps and 
provide the usual blankets, cooking equipment, food and other aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Relief officials acknowledge they were unprepared for the sudden  
onslaught, but they also note that political problems in Macedonia 
and the logistical nightmare of Albania share at least some of the 
blame. 
</P>
<P>
	The hardships are daunting:  
</P>
<P>
	-- A crumbling, limited road system that makes overland transport  
extremely slow and damaging to vehicles. Three relief workers and 
their Albanian driver died earlier this month when their vehicle 
slid into a ravine. 
</P>
<P>
	-- No airport exists in the northern border region, requiring aid  
agencies to rely on the poor roads or transport helicopters to get 
supplies into the area. When refugees flood the border, their tiny 
tractors hauling wagons laden with goods and people clog the 
winding, mountain roads. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The virtually non-existent telephone network in the north  
makes satellite phones the only reliable means of communication. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Disputes with district officials, landowners, police and  
others in the Kukes district. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Banditry in the clan-based region that has increased in recent  
weeks, including muggings and harassment of refugees, petty theft 
of relief supplies and even armed robbery. Policemen, soldiers and 
private guards brandish automatic rifles, while handguns get 
flashed regularly on the street. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonagh of Concern Worldwide knew the risks of running his  
four-truck convoy hauling flour, sugar, blankets and other items to 
Kosovo refugees in Bajram Curri, a notorious bandit town a few 
hours north of Kukes. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost every journalist who has gone there got robbed, including  
a group from The Associated Press, while the Organization of 
Security and Cooperation in Europe lost two vehicles at gunpoint. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonagh arranged with officials in Kukes for six special  
policemen in a blue, marked police van to ride in front until 
Bajram Curri, where a second group of seven would take over for the 
drive to the border village of Tropoja. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a huge problem,'' he said after the brief encounter with  
unsuccessful bandits. ``We're trying to get food to 2,500 refugees. 
So far they've been supplied by choppers ... but it's not enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. World Food Program has managed to bring the needed 100  
tons of food aid to the region each day using helicopters and 
trucks, said spokeswoman Angela Walker. But it hasn't been easy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually when you think of a European country, you transport by  
road,'' she said. ``But the roads here are very difficult. The 
tractors are going 2 miles per hour, you can't get trucks up here. 
... It's tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Due to security fears, the agency has banned any driving after  
dark. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're afraid that people are going to be held up,'' Walker  
said. ``It's scary because everyone here has guns. Someone said 
it's like the OK Corral or Dodge City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Increasing dispute with local authorities, including the police,  
also causes problems. Wilkinson of the UNHCR told of a failed 
effort to construct a new camp for refugees who crossed over on the 
cumbersome tractors hauling wagons overladen with people and 
possessions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was your normal difficulty,'' he said. ``We abandoned it  
because control of the land was disputed by two villages and it 
couldn't be resolved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next day, he said, poor local Albanians looted the tents and  
building supplies at the site. 
</P>
<P>
	Some relief agencies complained Thursday that local police  
detained at least two truck drivers for lacking proper papers for 
the goods they were hauling. Relief workers called it the latest 
example of increasing harassment by local authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it continues,'' said John Palmer of Goal, an Irish relief  
agency, ``we've told them we'll have to reconsider our 
participation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
