<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs $2.4B for Water Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Thursday to authorize $2.4  
billion over five years for 161 new or modified water projects 
around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, passed by a 418-5 vote, is similar to a measure  
that foundered last year in part because of controversy over 
several flood control and water supply provisions affecting 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bill we bring to the floor today breaks that impasse,''  
said Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House Transportation 
and Infrastructure Committee. ``People are not getting everything 
they want here. But it is a balanced compromise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The California provisions involve increasing flood protection  
along the American and Sacramento rivers and studying whether to 
raise the Folsom Dam in that area by 6 1/2 feet. Stripped out were 
items opposed by the Clinton administration that would have 
diverted water supplies in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from California, the measure increases federal cost  
sharing for many deep water harbor dredging projects, extends 
authorization for Everglades restoration in Florida and authorizes 
$100 million for a variety of flood control projects that do not 
involve building structures. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate passed a similar bill last week. A conference  
committee will attempt to work out a final compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
