<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Down 89.34 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as fears about inflation  
and rising interest rates resurfaced and foiled the Dow Jones 
industrials' attempt to reach 11,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow fell 89.34 to 10,789.04, ending the blue chip index's  
advance on its latest milestone when it was only 39 points away. 
Nonetheless, the Dow surged 10.3 percent during April, and reached 
new closing highs 13 times during the month. It was up 99.37 for 
the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader market indicators were mixed on Friday, with the Nasdaq  
composite rising a modest 14.41 to 2,542.85, and the Standard &AMP; 
Poor's 500 index falling 7.65 to 1,335.18. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow, which traded as high as 10,961.71, began sinking after  
the bond market dropped in response to the Commerce Department's 
report that the U.S. economy grew at a strong 4.5 percent annual 
rate in the first three months of this year, far above 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond traders reacted to an inflation measure tied to the gross  
domestic product, which rose at an annual rate of 1.4 from January 
through March, up from 0.8 percent in the fourth quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase overshadowed the solid growth in the GDP, the total  
output of goods and services, which soared despite the nation's 
worsening trade deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond market yields soared to 5.66 percent from late Thursday's  
5.52 percent as investors feared the economic strength would 
reignite inflation and prompt the Federal Reserve to push interest 
rates higher. Higher rates raised the specter of high borrowing 
costs and lower corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was down more than 223 points during afternoon trading  
before regaining some ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like the bond market clobbered the stock market,''  
said David Orr, chief economist at First Union Capital Markets 
Group in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The down mood was compounded by a report from corporate  
purchasing executives that said manufacturing activity surged in 
the Midwest during April. The report by the Purchasing Management 
Association of Chicago is often viewed as a precursor to the survey 
on the economy by the National Association of Purchasing 
Management, which issues its own survey on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors have been generally calm about inflation and interest  
rates in recent weeks, focusing instead on first-quarter earnings 
reports. As recently as Thursday, a government report found wages 
moved up at their slowest pace on record, indicating inflation well 
under control. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anyone is worried about inflation today, they forgot to  
read the newspaper yesterday,'' said Charles Crane, market 
strategist at Key Asset Management. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Dow stocks, American Express slipped 4 7/8 to 130 11/16  
and J.P. Morgan fell 3 1/4 to 134 3/4 because a rise in interest rates 
is likely to hurt financial service companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But technology stocks rallied after three days of losses,  
contributing to the rise in the Nasdaq index. America Online rose 1 
3/8 to 142 3/4 and Amazon.com was up 3 13/16 to 172 1/16. IBM advanced 
4 3/8 to 209 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard rose 1/2 to 78 7/8 after a Merrill Lynch analyst  
said the personal computer maker will likely top second-quarter 
earnings estimates of 79 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	A Dow stock that did well Friday was Minnesota Mining and  
Manufacturing, up 3 3/8 to 89, after 3M reported higher than expected 
first-quarter profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts said the interest rate concerns gave investors a  
reason to collect profits after the market's April surge. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you consider the market has risen almost 1,000 point in  
the past four weeks investors have a good excuse to sit back and 
enjoy some of their recent winnings,'' Crane said. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.79 to 634.30,  
and the American Stock Exchange composite fell 2.03 to 776.97. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index, which reflects the performance of  
small-company stocks, edged 0.04 lower to 432.81. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated volume came to 1.13 billion shares, down from 1.22  
billion Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.4 percent,  
Germany's DAX index rose 1.1 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 rose .08 
percent, and France's CAC-40 rose 0.8 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
