<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avalanche Kills Climber in Alaska </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- A mountain climber fell 1,200 feet to  
his death in Wrangell-St. Elias National Park when an avalanche 
swept him over a cliff. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Haberl of Whistler, British Columbia, was climbing with two  
companions on an unnamed peak on Thursday afternoon when they 
became caught in a slow-moving, 4-foot-deep slide. 
</P>
<P>
	Two were able to break free, but Haberl was swept away. His  
companions found his body as they descended the mountain. 
</P>
<P>
	Haberl's death is Alaska's 12th avalanche fatality this year.  
Two snowboarders were killed in a slide on Tuesday near Juneau, and 
six people died in a mid-March avalanche southeast of Anchorage. 
</P>
<P>
	Four people died in Alaska avalanches in 1998.  
</P>
<P>
	Wrangell-St. Elias National Park is about 275 miles east of  
Anchorage and a few miles west of the Canadian border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
