<DOCNO> APW19990430.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 12:25:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Balkans Tourism Another Casualty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Fears of an escalating conflict in Yugoslavia have  
caused an increasing number of American tourists to cancel trips to 
Greece, Croatia and other countries in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. travel agencies report a sharp decline in airline and hotel  
bookings, and cruise ship companies are rerouting their vessels 
away from the eastern Mediterranean. 
</P>
<P>
	Even travel to Italy has been affected, due in part to frequent  
TV images of NATO bombers taking off from an airbase in Aviano, 
north of Venice. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are saying, 'OK, I'd rather travel domestically this  
year.' As a result, we're seeing our U.S. and Canada business up 
very strongly,'' said Steve Kang, managing director of Maupintour, 
a tour operator based in Lawrence, Kan. Bookings for tours to 
Turkey, Greece and Italy have plunged by 25 percent or more, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Europeans too are becoming more cautious. Some British and  
German vacationers are taking a dimmer view of Croatia's sunny 
coastline, and cruise operators have scaled back trips on the 
Danube River. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics are hard to come by, but analysts at  
PricewaterhouseCoopers estimate that hotels and travel companies 
have already lost business worth $100 million due to the effects of 
fighting in Kosovo and NATO's air raids on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The accounting firm predicts that losses will grow if NATO  
deploys ground troops or if the conflict spills beyond Yugoslavia's 
borders. 
</P>
<P>
	International Tours Fifth Avenue, a New York-based travel  
agency, reports that 70 of its 500 customers have canceled trips to 
southeastern Europe, including Greece and southern Italy. Scott 
Winsten, a senior vice-president for the firm, attributes many of 
the cancellations to a poor grasp of geography. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have no concept where anything is, whether it's Kosovo,  
Jamaica, Bermuda or the Bahamas,'' he said. ``They get very 
confused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But even one of his employees, Caroline Starr, is advising her  
customers to avoid Venice and other parts of eastern Italy for fear 
of an unexpected influx of ethnic Albanian refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Travel agencies that specialize in trips to the Balkans have  
suffered the worst. 
</P>
<P>
	Adriatic Sunshine Travel, a Chicago-based agency that organizes  
trips to Croatia and Bosnia, has seen sales plunge by 80 percent -- 
a crisis that owner Mirna Jelovac calls the worst she's experienced 
in 10 years of operations. 
</P>
<P>
	For Audrey Oster, a New York artist, uncertainty about the  
Balkan turmoil is not reason enough for her to scrap her vacation 
plans. She and her husband are planning to fly next month to the 
Greek island of Corfu, which lies just miles off the Albanian 
coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's certainly been a little bit of a question in my head,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although they haven't bought their tickets yet, she said when  
they do, she'll make one practical concession: ``I'll probably buy 
trip insurance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Physical danger is less the problem than concerns about possible  
airport closures and the need to make time-consuming detours, 
travel agents say. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines began feeling the effect of the conflict when NATO  
launched its air campaign. Military aircraft snarled air traffic in 
Frankfurt, Germany, causing one of Europe's biggest carriers, 
Lufthansa, to delay some flights and cancel others. 
</P>
<P>
	Lufthansa, British Airways and other airlines have been forced  
to divert Asia-bound flights around the conflict zone, adding up to 
an hour to each journey. 
</P>
<P>
	Some luxury cruise operators have stopped calling on ports in  
the Adriatic and eastern Mediterranean and have rerouted their 
ships further west. 
</P>
<P>
	Carnival Corp., the world's largest cruise line, no longer lets  
its ships stop at the Croatian port of Dubrovnik. Company spokesman 
Tim Gallagher said the company could lose $50 million in business 
if the conflict in Kosovo drags on into the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	German tourists are continuing to travel to Hungary, which  
borders northern Yugoslavia, but the number of Germans traveling by 
road to Croatia has decreased by as much as 20 percent, said Bernd 
Rimele of TUI Deutschland, a charter tours company based in 
Hanover, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The Association of British Travel Agents sees a decrease of less  
than 5 percent in the number of Britons making trips to Greece and 
southeastern Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	``British holiday-makers don't scare too easily,'' said ABTA  
spokesman Sean Tipton. 
</P>
<P>
	One effect of the conflict has been unforeseen bargains.  
</P>
<P>
	The recently remodeled Hotel Excelsior in Dubrovnik, Croatia, is  
struggling to fill its 172 rooms, and management has slashed rates 
by 30 percent since the NATO bombings began. A double room now goes 
for $42.45 per person. 
</P>
<P>
	Layoffs may be in store if more guests fail to arrive.  
</P>
<P>
	``Of course we worry about that,'' said reception clerk Joseph  
Barcot. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
