<DOCNO> APW19990430.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 01:24:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Bids $3M at Online Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HADDONFIELD, N.J. (AP) -- Andrew Tyler had the winning bids on an  
antique bed, a 1971 red Corvette and an oak cradle. But the 
eighth-grader lost out on the 1955 Ford convertible, a Van Gogh 
painting and a rare Superman comic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really didn't know what I was doing,'' Andrew said Thursday  
from his home in this Philadelphia suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	What he was doing was bidding money he didn't have via the  
Internet auction house eBay -- $3 million in bids from a boy with a 
weekly allowance of $15. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, nearly half the offers the 13-year-old made during the  
bidding frenzy -- for $925,012 worth of merchandise -- were accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	Then mom and dad found out.  
</P>
<P>
	``Our kid is the nicest kid,'' said his mother, Ingrid, who  
found out last week. ``I was horrified. I could not believe it -- 
until I actually talked to my son.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tyler said she confronted Andrew and he admitted placing  
the bids. 
</P>
<P>
	``To him it was like a game. He didn't know it was real money,''  
she said. ``He really didn't know this was for real.'' 
</P>
<P>
	eBay said Andrew's account has been suspended and the sellers  
who accepted his deadbeat bids have been notified. When someone 
successfully bids via eBay, payment and delivery are worked out 
between the winning bidder and the seller. 
</P>
<P>
	As for eBay's security procedures, spokesman Kevin Pursglove  
said the company has a strict policy against bidding by anyone 
under 18. But he said eBay largely works on the honor system. 
</P>
<P>
	In a three-week period, Andrew bid on 13 items, including $1.2  
million for a medical office in Jacksonville, Fla., $500,000 for 
the Van Gogh, $120,000 for the first Superman comic book and 
$35,000 for a replica of a Viking ship. 
</P>
<P>
	While eight of the bids failed, Andrew had the winning bid on  
five items, including the bed that belonged to Sir John A. 
Macdonald, Canada's first prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	The bid for the 1860s bed stood at $12,000 until Andrew  
demolished the competition -- he offered $900,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew admits he was lucky to get off with just losing his  
Internet privileges. ``My parents are just mad at me, nothing 
else,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 08:25:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bitter Scottish Derby Seen Up Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Claudio Reyna has played in the World Cup, two Olympics and  
captained a side in the German Bundesliga. He's even dodged 
projectiles while hostile fans spat on him during a World Cup 
qualifier in Costa Rica. 
</P>
<P>
	Some feel that's little preparation for an ``Old Firm'' clash.  
</P>
<P>
	Few matches around the world compare to the Glasgow derby  
between Rangers and Celtic, a 109-year-old grudge match that, on 
Sunday, Reyna will become the first American to see from field 
level. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obviously one of the more traditional rivalries,'' the  
25-year-old international said by phone. ``Its one of the biggest 
games in the world. Every time they play, it's THE game of year. 
The atmosphere, whether at Ibrox (Stadium) or Celtic Park, is 
incredible. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are not many places in the world like it,'' added Reyna,  
who lines up for Rangers. ``I'm really excited. The guys have told 
me all about it. The fans are so passionate. The guys were telling 
me today, that Ibrox will be full with 50,000 fans watching the 
game on two giant TV screens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's more than a traditional intra-city rivalry, even by soccer  
standards. Separated by a mere five miles, the two clubs are worlds 
apart. 
</P>
<P>
	The game's passion dates back to the medieval animosity between  
Catholics (Celtic) and Protestants (Rangers). Add the fact the two 
clubs have won 83 Scottish league titles and 57 Scottish Cup 
titles, making the matches very often for some type of crown, and 
it's wise not to wear Rangers blue or Celtic green on game day -- 
unless seated with like-minded folk. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last decade or so, the game has changed somewhat. Instead  
of relying on predominantly homegrown Protestant or Catholic 
players, both sides have become very international, signing players 
from across Europe and throughout the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the management of both clubs is now foreign.  
</P>
<P>
	``Even with that, even though the game on the pitch has changed  
quite drastically, with a frenzied first 25 minutes with adrenalin 
pumping, even though all that has changed, you still have a hot 
atmosphere, a bitter atmosphere,'' Glasgow Daily Mail sports writer 
Peter Jarbin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reyna has had only a couple of weeks to adjust to Scottish life  
since transferring from Germany's VfL Wolfsburg on April 2. On top 
of that, his first child, Jack, was born April 10. He left the baby 
and his wife Danielle, a former member of the U.S. women's team, in 
Germany. They are expected to arrive in Scotland next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting used to it,'' Reyna said. ``Obviously it's a new  
country. Everybody has been very nice at the club. It's made the 
transition a lot easier, adjusting to the Scottish game. I've got 
two games under my belt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the big challenge is so many supporters. It was so  
exciting for me ... stepping on field there were 50,000 people,'' 
Reyna said, describing a 3-1 victory over Aberdeen. 
</P>
<P>
	Reyna has been overseas his entire professional career, starting  
with Germany's Bayer Leverkusen in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a member of the 1994 U.S. World Cup team, but didn't  
play. He was the playmaker in France '98, playing every minute, but 
is remembered most for being fouled early in the first game against 
Germany by Jens Jeremies and not being effective after that. 
</P>
<P>
	When he returned to Germany after the World Cup, Reyna struggled  
to regain his place at Wolfsburg. When he finally did, he was 
largely praised, but Reyna began looking elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Having gone from a modest German club to one of the oldest and  
most famous in the world -- Rangers was founded in 1872 -- Reyna 
understands the significance of an American playing soccer abroad 
at the highest level. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being an American is even more of a challenge,'' Reyna said.  
``You have to prove Americans can play at a big club. It's a little 
bit of a responsibility for America, that if I do well it may give 
an opportunity to others.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
