<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palladium Futures Prices Plunge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *By CLIFF EDWARDS    	
</P>
<P>
	Palladium futures prices plunged 10 percent Friday on the New  
York Mercantile Exchange after large deliveries of the metal 
boosted speculation Russia is exporting again following a lengthy 
absence. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, cocoa rose sharply, as did wheat and soybeans.  
</P>
<P>
	Palladium tumbled at the beginning of trading and never  
recovered on news as much as 160,000 ounces of palladium, or nearly 
10 times the daily recent average, was sold overnight in London. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge sale pointed to Russian selling, since that country  
controls nearly 80 percent of the world's supply. South Africa 
exports much of the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has not made large-scale shipments of the industrial  
metal since December, the third consecutive year it has held 
supplies off the market, purportedly because of bureaucratic 
delays. 
</P>
<P>
	Western manufacturers rely on the metal for use in cleaner  
burning automobile emission-control devices, in jewelry and in 
electronics. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium demand has been increasing steadily for the past four  
years as more countries set tough pollution-control standards, but 
prices for the metal have tumbled in recent weeks amid fears 
manufacturers weary of the repeated delays may find alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium for June delivery fell 32.90, or 9.8 percent, to $308  
an ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures rose sharply on the Board of Trade of the City of  
New York as chocolate manufacturers became heavy buyers amid 
speculation that prices had fallen to their lowest for the 
foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures have plunged in recent weeks as crops poured in  
from harvests of major West African manufacturers. With the major 
candy-making season still months away, manufacturers have been 
content to sit on the sidelines and wait for prices to fall to 
their lowest. 
</P>
<P>
	July cocoa rose $13 to $1019 a ton.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat and soybean futures on the Chicago Board of Trade were  
pressured early in the session amid heavier-than-expected 
deliveries of supplies for the May contract -- a sign that farmers 
are settling for lower prices amid fears matters will become worse 
in the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But wheat later rose on marginal export demand and news the  
government made another large purchase for donation to needy 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans found some support on conflicting forecasts for weather  
next week in Midwest growing regions. The National Weather Service 
is calling for above-normal rainfall, but some private forecasters 
are saying skies will remain clear at least through Wednesday. That 
will encourage corn planting and could lead to more of that crop 
getting into the ground over soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat rose 4 1/2 cents to $2.68 a bushel; July soybeans rose 2  
cents to $4.86 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
