<DOCNO> APW19990430.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 10:41:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans $20M for Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senators will postpone a showdown over  
allowing President Clinton to use ``whatever means necessary'' to 
win the battle against Yugoslavia, Senate Minority Leader Tom 
Daschle said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle, D-S.D., made the prediction as the U.S.-led NATO  
bombing of Yugoslavia intensified dramatically and the United 
States committed more long-range bombers to the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle told reporters that he and Senate Majority Leader Trent  
Lott, R-Miss., will join forces against considering a motion by 
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., that would allow Clinton to use the 
force necessary -- including ground troops -- to prevail against 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. Daschle predicted the 
leaders will prevail in the vote Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we need to do is to follow the advice of the president,  
who admonished us to give the war effort and the air mission time 
to function, time to work. I believe that it is working,'' Daschle 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	His remarks came in the wake of House refusal to endorse the  
bombing campaign against Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, a House committee approved nearly $13 billion to pay  
for Pentagon operations in the Balkans and elsewhere. Clinton, who 
had asked for half as much money, today directed the State 
Department to release up to $20 million in existing emergency funds 
to aid Kosovo refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also formally directed the State Department to begin  
clearing the way for up to 20,000 refugees to come to the United 
States for shelter with volunteers and relatives here. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said  
the bombing campaign has entered the ``domination phase.'' That 
means warplanes try to hit enemy troops on the ground, in addition 
to the supplies and infrastructure that support Milosevic's 
military machine. 
</P>
<P>
	In what was apparently the largest onslaught to date, NATO  
planned 670 air sorties throughout the day and night Thursday to 
take advantage of clearing weather. Of those, 296 were listed as 
attack or combat flights and the others a mixture of support and 
reconnaissance. 
</P>
<P>
	``So today's a big one,'' Shelton said at a briefing for  
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton was to begin visiting U.S. air crews in the region today  
as part of a short trip to the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO is conducting air operations over Yugoslavia both day and  
night, virtually around the clock,'' Shelton said. ``Our military 
strikes have taken a heavy toll on Milosevic's forces and his 
security infrastructure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton noted clear skies were predicted over Yugoslavia for the  
next several days, which should allow for more bombing runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clouds hamper the lasers and other precision instruments that  
guide many missiles and bombs, and pilots have turned back or held 
off on dropping bombs when weather interfered. 
</P>
<P>
	The $12.9 billion spending package approved Thursday by the  
House Appropriations Committee was double what President Clinton 
requested. It will cover the fighting and buttress Pentagon needs 
around the globe. House floor debate is expected next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, Defense Secretary William Cohen announced he was  
sending 10 additional B-52 bombers to Europe, more than doubling 
the number now flying long-range bombing missions from a base in 
England. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO bombing campaign that began March 24 was designed to  
force the Serb-led Yugoslav government to accept conditions for 
peace in the province of Kosovo, and allow ethnic Albanian refugees 
to return to their homes under the protection of an international 
peace-keeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	Refugees and aid workers report a string of atrocities,  
including mass killings, by Serb forces inside Kosovo and hundreds 
of thousands of refugees have fled the southern Serbian province in 
recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbia, led by Milosevic, is the dominant of two republics that  
make up Yugoslavia. Other Slavic countries have split from the 
federation since the end of the Cold War. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbia wants to retain control of Kosovo, which it regards as  
the republic's cultural cradle despite the fact that ethnic Serbs 
were actually a minority there until a few weeks ago. NATO wants 
the province to be autonomous but still remain a nominal part of 
Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional Democrats invoked the suffering of the refugees as  
they accused Republicans of undermining American troops with an 
unexpected 213-213 House vote Wednesday to withheld support for the 
NATO air campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri called the  
vote ``a low moment in foreign policy and the history of this 
institution.'' He blamed ``a small but determined extreme 
majority'' for orchestrating the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the House majority whip, noted that  
26 Democrats also voted against the airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The partisan finger-pointing came as a 10-member congressional  
delegation led by Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., headed to Vienna, 
Austria, to meet with members of the Russian parliament to discuss 
possible ways of resolving the Balkans crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
