<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 14:35:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Police Tactics Debated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A judge has freed a teen-ager who confessed to  
fatally stabbing a woman who, it turns out, was never stabbed at 
all. The case has stoked the debate over whether Chicago police are 
bullying people into admitting to crimes they didn't commit. 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Huggins, 16, had spent more than a year behind bars  
awaiting trial. He was acquitted by a judge Thursday after a 
medical expert testified that the victim, 26-year-old Lorraine 
Gates, was beaten and strangled, not stabbed. 
</P>
<P>
	It was one of four murder cases whose unraveling has proved a  
major embarrassment to Chicago-area law enforcement authorities in 
the last three years. The cases have prompted demands from defense 
attorneys for an investigation of police conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``The police have a saying -- `Let's make him talk,''' Huggins'  
attorney, Andre Grant, said Friday. ``Unfortunately, that means, 
`Let's make him admit things that the physical evidence tells us 
simply could not have happened.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said they accept the decision of Circuit Judge  
Thomas Sumner to free Huggins. But they still say Huggins was the 
killer. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Benjamin, a spokesman for the state's attorney's office,  
noted that Huggins in his statement said he stabbed and punched the 
woman. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are often inconsistencies in people's statements, even  
when they confess to crimes that they commit,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his decision, the judge suggested that the zeal of police and  
prosecutors to solve the case clouded their judgment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes in this system -- in this process we have which is  
presumed to ferret out the truth -- the truth gets obscured in the 
process of winning and losing,'' Sumner said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that besides the inconsistency involving stab wounds,  
the victim's DNA was found in blood on a jacket belonging to 
another teen. 
</P>
<P>
	Huggins' lawyer is scheduled to go to court May 14 to seek a  
special prosecutor to investigate police handling of another case 
that has haunted Chicago for months -- the beating death of 
11-year-old honor student Ryan Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	Two boys, 7 and 8, were charged with Ryan's murder in August  
after six hours alone with Chicago detectives who said the boys had 
confessed. The boys supposedly admitted they killed her for her 
bicycle. The charges were dropped after semen was found in her 
clothing. An ex-convict has since been charged with the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, four men who served years behind bars for a 1978 gang  
rape and double murder that evidence shows they didn't commit 
agreed to a $36 million settlement with Cook County, whose 
sheriff's police made the arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the so-called Ford Heights Four said their clients  
were the victims of a racially motivated frameup. The defendants 
were freed as the result of work by a Northwestern University 
journalism class. 
</P>
<P>
	More work by Northwestern journalism students resulted in the  
Feb. 5 release of 43-year-old Anthony Porter, who spent 16 years in 
prison for a double homicide in Chicago. Another man now admits he 
pulled the trigger. 
</P>
<P>
	After admitting their mistake in the Ryan Harris case, Cook  
County State's Attorney Richard Devine and Chicago Police 
Superintendent Terry Hillard announced new safeguards to prevent a 
repeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Murder suspects will be allowed to give a videotaped statement  
after they are questioned, and youngsters who are being questioned 
by police will have the right to have their parents in the room. 
</P>
<P>
	But Grant said it will take more to solve the problem. He said  
the federal government eventually will be forced to investigate the 
way Chicago police take confessions in homicide cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eddie Huggins didn't confess to a thing,'' Grant said. ``He  
just parroted back what he was told. He was a 15-year-old kid who 
was frightened, frightened and intimidated.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
