<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 154.06 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply Friday after a glowing  
report on the U.S. economy rekindled inflation fears. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 154.06 at 10,724.32. The Dow, which had moved higher in the 
morning, began sinking after the bond market became unnerved by the 
economic data. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also fell. The Nasdaq composite index  
was down 23.94 at 2,504.50. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 
20.27 to 1,322.56. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market dropped markedly in response to the Commerce  
Department's report that the U.S. economy grew at a strong 4.5 
percent annual rate in the first three months of this year, far 
above expectations, as consumers spent at the fastest pace in more 
than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The department reported that the solid growth in the gross  
domestic product, the total output of goods and services, came 
despite the fact that the nation's trade deficit, battered by 
overseas economic turmoil, soared to a record level. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond market yields soared to 5.66 percent from late Thursday's  
5.52 percent as investors feared the economic strength would 
reignite inflation and prompt the Federal Reserve to push interest 
rates higher. Higher rates raised the specter of high borrowing 
costs and lower corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bonds got hit pretty hard,'' said Bob Basel, a head trader at  
Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Dow stocks, American Express slipped 5 1/16 to 130 5/16  
and J.P. Morgan fell 4 to 134 because a rise in interest rates is 
likely to hurt financial service companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart, another Dow stock, fell 3 1/8 to 43 1/4.  
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks returned most of their early gains. America  
Online fell 3 5/8 to 137 3/4. Amazon.com was down 1 3/4 to 166 1/2 
</P>
<P>
	But Hewlett-Packard rose 7/8 to 79 1/4 after a Merrill Lynch analyst  
said the personal computer maker will likely top second-quarter 
earnings estimates of 79 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues were marginally ahead of decliners on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 721 million shares, 
slightly below Thursday's level. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 7.84 to 630.25 , and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 4.24 to 774.76. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:55:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Service Disrupted to Online Bankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Customers at 21 banks, including First Union  
Corp., that use CheckFree for electronic banking services may be 
finding their transactions aren't quite glitch-free. 
</P>
<P>
	Some users of Quicken or Microsoft's Money financial software  
have reported problems either logging on or in getting ``kicked 
out'' before they were ready, said Terrie O'Hanlon, a CheckFree 
spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Customer by customer, the experience is different,'' she said,  
adding that up to 500,000 customers potentially could be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks that use a new transaction processing system called  
Genesis the ones having problems. CheckFree began switching banks 
to the new system six months ago, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief operating officer Pete Sinisgalli said in a statement  
workers had trouble diagnosing the ``root cause'' of the problem, 
but on Thursday believed they had identified it. 
</P>
<P>
	``(We're trying) to resolve this issue as quickly as possible to  
restore uninterrupted service for consumers,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union, the nation's sixth-largest bank, was putting  
together special instructions and information for customers on its 
Web page. The Charlotte, N.C.-based First Union has some 16 million 
customers in the eastern United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of our customers are affected. We don't know how many at  
this point,'' said spokeswoman Danielle Deabler. She estimated the 
total number of customers who bank online as in the ``hundreds of 
thousands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said First Union would work with CheckFree to make sure  
customers weren't charged late fees caused by the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Based in the Atlanta suburb of Norcross, CheckFree Holdings Co.  
has some 2.8 million customers and helps provide electronic payment 
services at 350 institutions. Founded in 1981, the company has 
1,800 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a small percentage of Americans use such services, largely  
because of unfamiliarity or concerns about reliability and 
security. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 07:35:09 </DATE_TIME>
