<HEADLINE> China Vows To Boost Tax Collections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China is intensifying tax collections to try to  
boost government revenues to 20 percent of gross domestic product 
within three to five years, state media reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Government revenues last year accounted for 12.4 percent of the  
$963 billion economy, the China Securities News reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice Finance Minister Lou Jiwei vowed to boost that to 20  
percent, with about two-thirds of the tax total coming from central 
government collections, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tax revenues this year are expected to total $130 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	``Reform of the management of the government's budget will take  
some time ... but the government is committed to the development of 
an effective fiscal system,'' Lou was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
