<HEADLINE> Dollar, Gold Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose today against most other  
major currencies in European trading. Gold prices also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 119.59 Japanese yen from 118.90 yen late  
Thursday, and was higher against the euro, the currency of 11 
European nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro fell to $1.0584 by late in the day in Europe from  
$1.0597 late Thursday. It briefly traded at a new intraday low of 
$1.0555 before recovering. The previous intraday low was $1.0561 on 
April 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Thursday included 1.5230  
Swiss francs, up from 1.5168, and 1.4583 Canadian dollars, down 
from 1.4663. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6105, down from $1.6114.  
</P>
<P>
	At midday in New York, the dollar was quoted at 119.35 yen and  
1.5248 Swiss francs. The euro was trading at $1.0567 and the 
British pound was quoted at $1.6082. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates in Europe, the dollar was worth 1.8479 German marks, up from 
1.8456; 6.1976 French francs, up from 6.1900; 2.0821 Dutch 
guilders, up from 2.0796, and 1,829.43 Italian lire, up from 
1,827.19. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $286.50 per troy ounce, up from $283.10  
on Thursday. In Zurich the bid was $286.15, up from $282.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $2.50 in Hong Kong to close at $286.15.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.34 per troy ounce, up from $5.33.  
</P>
</TEXT>
