<HEADLINE> Harassment Suit Against Coach Moved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- A federal judge has transfered a $12  
million lawsuit accusing the University of North Carolina women's 
soccer coach of sexual harassment and misconduct to Greensboro from 
Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	Two former players filed the lawsuit against Anson Dorrance  
eight months ago. Earlier this week, U.S. District Judge Ann Claire 
Williams of suburban Chicago agreed to transfer the lawsuit, but 
denied a dismissal motion by UNC attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	In successfully arguing for the case's transfer, UNC lawyers  
said it would be expensive and time-consuming for attorneys and 
witnesses to have to travel regularly to suburban Chicago, the home 
of plaintiffs Debbie Keller and Melissa Jennings. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said the case belongs in North Carolina since ``almost  
all of the critical events giving rise to this lawsuit occurred in 
North Carolina'' and all the defendants live here. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll go where we have to go,'' said Marcy DeFalco, an  
attorney for Keller and Jennings. ``The court could have dismissed 
our case entirely. We still feel that we have a strong case, 
regardless of whether it's in Illinois or North Carolina.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
