<HEADLINE> Newsweek, Washington Post Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reporters for Newsweek and The Washington Post  
won journalism prizes for writing about President Clinton and the 
Monica Lewinsky affair, while a reporter for Knight Ridder was 
recognized for a story about Clinton's trip to Africa last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The awards will be presented Saturday night at the 85th annual  
dinner of the White House Correspondents' Association. Clinton's 
attendance at the dinner was in doubt for a while, supposedly 
because of White House irritation at the prospect of the president 
having to shake hands with Newsweek's Michael Isikoff, who is 
credited with breaking the Lewinsky story. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton now plans to attend, but he is expected to arrive after  
the presentation of the awards. ``The president will get there when 
he gets there,'' spokesman Joe Lockhart said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Isikoff won the Edgar A. Poe award for his coverage of the  
Lewinsky scandal. In addition, John Harris of The Washington Post 
won the Aldo Beckman award for a full range of presidential 
coverage, and Jodi Enda of Knight Ridder won the Merriman Smith 
award for presidential writing under deadline pressure, for her 
reporting from Rwanda. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Bill Lambrecht of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch won  
the Raymond Clapper Memorial Award for a series of articles 
examining the worldwide use of genetically engineered crops. Lee 
Davidson of the Deseret News in Salt Lake City won second place for 
a series on the results of a 1990 law designed to compensate cancer 
victims of atomic testing. 

</P>
</TEXT>
