<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Candidates Oppose Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Few of the Republican presidential contenders  
see a need for new gun control legislation in the wake of high 
school shootings in Colorado. Instead, they're urging enforcement 
of existing laws and scrutiny of a violence-tinged popular culture. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole favors child safety locks for firearms ``whether  
voluntary or through federal legislation,'' according to her 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The front-runner for the nomination, Texas Gov. George W. Bush,  
expressed support for legislation to extend the requirement for 
instant background checks to purchases made at gun shows. But he 
did so only after a bill to that effect died in committee in the 
state legislature, and sponsors said they had detected no effort on 
his part to win passage. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the others seeking the nomination said no further  
legislation is needed, and none reacted more vehemently that Pat 
Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those brutal and nihilistic killers in Colorado violated 19  
federal and state gun and explosive laws,'' he said in a written 
statement. ``To suggest that passage of a 20th or 21st or 22nd 
might have prevented this atrocity is delusional and demagogic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle, in a television interview  
shortly after the shootings, also turned aside a question about new 
legislation. ``So I hope we don't try to use this as an excuse to 
go and take away guns. Let's focus on the behavior,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes said that ``in terms of guns, I think we need to  
enforce laws that are on the books.'' He said the shootings 
``underscore the need to be teaching our children morals and values 
obviously at home, but particularly in the schools now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A week after the shootings, President Clinton proposed new  
legislation to curb the availability of guns, particularly to 
juveniles. Although no bill has yet been sent to Congress, 
Democrats in both houses are expected to push for a vote later this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, campaigning in Iowa this week, called  
for tighter controls on guns as well as reduced violence in the 
popular culture. His only rival for the Democratic presidential 
nomination, Bill Bradley, voted for gun control legislation while 
in Congress. ``Better gun control measures need to be a part of an 
overall response to what happened,'' said his spokesman, Eric 
Hauser. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, who receive handsome contributions from the  
National Rifle Association, traditionally have opposed gun 
legislation. Perhaps as a result, the issue customarily plays 
little if any role in contests for the GOP presidential nomination, 
but is more likely to arise during a general election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Bush and Mrs. Dole -- who departed cautiously  
from party orthodoxy on abortion earlier this year -- have indicated 
support for gun control measures in recent days. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's belated support for the proposed Texas law extending  
background checks to gun show purchases stirred controversy there. 
</P>
<P>
	But Karen Hughes, an aide to Bush, said the governor has  
``consistently supported since 1994 the idea of instant background 
checks at gun shows to make sure the people we don't want to sell 
guns to are not buying guns.'' She noted that Bush previously 
signed legislation prohibiting anyone from carrying a weapon within 
300 yards of a school, and holding adults criminally liable if they 
allow a juvenile access to a loaded gun. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she wasn't aware of any position Bush had taken on  
calls for child safety locks on guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Ari Fleisher, a spokesman for Mrs. Dole, said the former Red  
Cross president supports a gun lock proposal. ``She is for child 
safety locks whether voluntary or through federal legislation. She 
supports child safety locks,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole also joined the ranks of Republicans suggesting a look  
at the impact of current culture on behavior. ``While we can never 
have censorship, corporate America in Hollywood, TV, the makers of 
video games, have a responsibility to remember the community to 
think about the message they put out,'' Fleisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other GOP candidates made similar points, although they,  
unlike Mrs. Dole, said they saw no need for additional legislation 
to control guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think people believe this can be fixed by passing a  
handful of laws,'' said Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, who voted for a 
ban on assault-style weapons that cleared Congress in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though people in the polls have a visceral reaction  
against guns, they don't think that new laws will fix this.... They 
know this thing has to be solved from within families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain of Arizona was one of four lawmakers who wrote  
Clinton after the shootings to call for a close look at ``the 
entertainment media and the violent images and message with which 
they are bombarding our children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer said that rather than approve new legislation,  
``political leaders can use their moral authority to shame the 
people that are making a lot of money in the popular culture by 
serving up Marilyn Manson and death games and very explicit and 
gory murders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement issued shortly after the shootings, Lamar  
Alexander said, ``This will not be stopped by more laws coming out 
of Washington.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
