<DOCNO> APW19990430.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:53:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Spares Dogs, Banishes Them </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Two dogs sentenced to death for causing an  
ostrich stampede that left 12 birds dead and another dozen missing 
were spared when a judge banished them from the state instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Nikita, a Siberian husky, and Max, a Doberman pinscher, were  
ordered put to death last month under a law dealing with dogs that 
chase, injure or kill livestock or poultry. 
</P>
<P>
	The dogs' owner, Gina Park, appealed the order, and Judge  
Stanley P. Klein on Thursday imposed a lesser penalty because the 
dogs peacefully followed animal control officers' commands. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they were perpetually vicious, the last thing that would  
happen is they would surrender,'' Klein said. ``I don't believe 
that the dogs have forfeited their right to live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Klein banished the dogs from Virginia and bordering states.  
</P>
<P>
	A weeping Ms. Park declined to comment after the ruling.  
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Fouche, the ostrich breeder, said the ruling was fine.  
``As long as they're going to be kept from doing it again,'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
