<DOCNO> APW19990430.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angry Drivers Boycott Gas Pumps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	On the day that cyberspace activists called for a nationwide gas  
boycott, Erika Litchfield was filling up her Land Rover at a 
Chevron Station, where the truck swallowed up a hefty $30 in fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no choice. I'm stuck with this,'' she said at a station  
in San Francisco's tony Pacific Heights, where classical music 
filters through speakers at the pump. ``It's awful, isn't it? Trust 
me, if I had a choice I'd boycott.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Choice or not, it seemed as if many motorists ignored the  
Internet campaign calling for a one-day ``Gas Out'' in protest of 
escalating fuel prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron spokesman Mike Libbey said late Friday afternoon that  
the ``Gas Out'' had ``virtually no impact'' on business at its 
8,000 stations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the message has been that consumers are frustrated by  
the sudden rise in prices and think it isn't warranted and we hear 
that,'' Libbey said. However, he said Chevron has no plans to lower 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Global agreements to cut oil production has sent the price of  
gas skyrocketing more than 20 percent in recent weeks. Explosions 
and problems at refineries in California contributed to an 
especially sharp spike in prices there, prompting an investigation 
by California's attorney general. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest Lundberg Survey of 10,000 gas stations nationwide  
showed the average prices at self-service stations was $1.17 per 
gallon for regular gasoline, $1.27 for mid-grade and $1.36 for 
premium. 
</P>
<P>
	The average price in California for unleaded regular, self-serve  
gasoline is up 42 cents from last month, to $1.64 per gallon, the 
American Automobile Association said. Selected markets in 
California, however, report prices of more than $2 a gallon for 
premium grades. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the ``Gas Out'' originated in an e-mail message, it was  
tough to tell exactly who promoted it and how widespread it was, 
though reports Friday suggested it was concentrated in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	The owner of a Shell station in Vancouver, Wash., who supported  
the boycott said she ``definitely'' noticed a drop in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not long enough. If they did it from Friday to Monday, it  
would definitely have an effect,'' said Karen Rock. ``But they 
can't do it. People aren't willing to walk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Hedgecock, a radio talk show host and former San Diego  
mayor who has led ``Buy No Gas Fridays'' in the city for the past 
month, said he plans to continue the boycott. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not just here today,'' he said as he and 30 listeners  
protested outside a Chevron station to the supportive honking of 
passing drivers. ``We're going to do this every Friday until the 
prices come down in line with the national average.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Lambert, a new sport utility vehicle owner in Newark,  
Calif., said he urged six friends to join him in a daylong boycott 
in an e-mail message a month ago. Within days, he said, others 
rallied to the cause and forwarded e-mails of their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time we did something about the price of gasoline in  
America! ... Let's have a GAS OUT!'' read one message that showed 
up in computers in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Ross Relles, the owner of a Sacramento, Calif., Chevron station  
charging $2.07 for full service premium, complained that business 
Friday was down by as much as 50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoever is promoting this idiotic day, all it's hurting is the  
small retailers like me,'' Relles said. ``We should be absolutely 
swamped because it's not only Friday but it's pay day.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 12:15:20 </DATE_TIME>
