<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 07:15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Volvo Increases Share in Scania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Volvo announced Friday that it has  
increased its stake in rival Swedish truck- and bus-maker Scania to 
about 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Volvo surprised the business community in January with the  
announcement that it had bought 13 percent of the shares in Scania 
and that it was seeking to merge. 
</P>
<P>
	But talks between Volvo and the Investor holding company, which  
holds 45 percent of the shares in Scania, broke down this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Volvo in January sold its small but prestigious passenger car  
division to Ford Motor Co. for 50 billion kronor ($6.45 billion), 
saying it wanted to concentrate on its other business areas 
including trucks, buses, heavy equipment, and marine and 
aeronautical engines. 
</P>
<P>
	The seller of the latest Scania shares was not disclosed. The  
purchase, which includes call options, will give Volvo 15.6 percent 
of the share capital and 15.1 percent of the voting rights once the 
options are exercised, Volvo said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 17:42:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Police Monitored Eric Harris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Police began keeping an eye on Columbine  
High School gunman Eric Harris a year ago after learning he 
threatened to kill a schoolmate and others, and often talked about 
making and blowing up pipe bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	But aside from watching Harris, sheriff's deputies said there  
was little else they could do because the parents who tipped police 
off to the threatening behavior wanted to remain anonymous. They 
also found no evidence of lawbreaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without the ability to speak to a victim or positively  
identify a suspect, elements of a crime could not be established,'' 
sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbine students returned to school on Friday for the first  
since the April 20 attack. Many students reported to nearby 
Chatfield High for orientation before classes resume Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been without seeing my friends for almost two weeks and  
the only goodbye was, `Run!'' said Jennifer Despain, a 16-year-old 
sophomore. ``I really want to get back and see my teachers and hold 
a pencil in my hand and do math equations or something. Something 
that's not funerals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are still seeking evidence as to whether others  
helped Harris and Dylan Klebold plot their assault. The gunmen 
killed 12 students and a teacher before committing suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	About a year before the assault, Neil Gardner, the sheriff's  
deputy stationed at Columbine, received a ``suspicious incident'' 
report that Harris' Web site discussed detonating pipe bombs and 
committing mass murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The March 1998 report came from Randy Brown, who claimed his  
18-year-old son Brooks had been repeatedly threatened by Harris, a 
schoolmate. Brown gave the sheriff's office printouts of Harris' 
Web site warnings, which included threats to kill. 
</P>
<P>
	``God, I can't wait until I can kill you people'' read one of  
the postings. ``I'll just go to some downtown area in some big 
(expletive) city and blow up and shoot everything I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the Browns refused to let their son's name be used  
in the investigation, and they also declined to file a formal 
complaint that would have allowed investigators to directly 
question Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	A threatening e-mail sent to Brooks Brown was deleted, so  
investigators were not able to follow up that lead. And detectives 
tried but could not find Harris' Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	A call to the Browns' home went unanswered Friday, but the  
Browns told NBC News that the sheriff's department response 
``ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We were hoping they would go to the school. We were hoping  
they would go to the parents,'' Judy Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner was at Columbine when Harris, 18, and Klebold, 17,  
attacked the school with bombs and assault weapons, and exchanged 
fire with one of the gunmen. 
</P>
<P>
	The sheriff's department said Gardner had been keeping an eye on  
Harris at school, observing his actions and noting his associates. 
But, without proof of a chargeable offense, there was nothing he 
could do, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In light of the information available at the time, reasonable  
action was taken with all reports received by the Brown family,'' 
Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown eventually made peace with Harris, and ran into him the  
day of the shooting as he was walking out of the high school to 
smoke a cigarette. An approaching Harris warned him to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said he was not surprised at the violent rampage.  
</P>
<P>
	``He did it because he hated people,'' Brown said.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, investigators are negotiating with the lawyers of the  
parents of the gunmen over the terms of a police interview. 
</P>
<P>
	So far the only person arrested in the attack is a hardware  
store clerk accused of concocting a story about selling the gunmen 
material used in their bombs. Others have been questioned, but 
prosecutors declined to label them as suspects. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun dealer Larry Russell told the Denver Rocky Mountain News  
that he sold the semiautomatic pistol used in the shootings to an 
unidentified adult last year. He said the TEC DC-9 was one of 
several he bought from a gun dealer in a closeout sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell said he sold the gun at a gun show in Denver last year.  
But he didn't keep a record of the sale and isn't sure when he sold 
it, or who bought it. He said he is sure the buyer was not a minor. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell said he has seen pictures of gunmen Harris and Klebold,  
and did not recognize them. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, authorities arrested a 34-year-old woman accused of  
calling in a phony bomb threat that briefly forced the evacuation 
of a high school. On Thursday, deputies arrested a hardware store 
clerk whose claims of selling bomb materials to Harris and Klebold 
proved unfounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 17:42:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bus Carrying Deaf Children Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRAIDWOOD, Ill. (AP) -- A bus carrying deaf children to a  
spelling bee flipped over on a highway Friday, killing a father. 
</P>
<P>
	Four adults were seriously hurt in the crash. None of the 16  
children aboard suffered major injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the bus swerved across the median into oncoming  
traffic about 50 miles southwest of Chicago, clipped a car and 
flipped over. The car's driver was not injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said they did not know why the bus driver lost  
control. Police Master Sgt. Ty Simmons said it is possible she may 
have fallen asleep. Witnesses said the bus was moving at high 
speed. 
</P>
<P>
	No citations had been issued.  
</P>
<P>
	The children from the John Powers Center in Vernon Hills, a  
suburb, were en route to the State of Illinois Deaf Spelling Bee in 
East Peoria. The event was canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	The one fatality was a father of a girl on the bus. Another man  
who was thrown from the bus and pinned underneath was in critical 
condition and three women were listed in serious condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The charter bus driver, Renee Rand, had a permit to drive school  
buses, but it was suspended in 1995 after she received two tickets 
within a year for speeding, according to Anne Dybek, a spokeswoman 
for the secretary of state's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Rand reapplied for her school bus permit in April 1996 but was  
rejected because she failed fingerprint checks aimed at weeding out 
people with criminal convictions, said Dybek. She did not know what 
caused Rand to fail. 
</P>
<P>
	Rand most recently was cited for driving without insurance.  
Dybek said Rand's driving privileges were scheduled to be suspended 
starting July 17, unless she provided proof that she has insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
