<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Onion Book 1st on Best-Seller List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Remember the immortal headlines? ``Zapruder  
Family Wowed At Home Movie Screening.'' ``Nancy Reagan Ends 
Nation's Drug Problem With Very Special `Diff'rent Strokes' 
Appearance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe not. But hundreds of thousands of book buyers are seeing  
them now in the skewed story of the 20th century according to The 
Onion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our Dumb History,'' the Madison-based parody newspaper's  
``retrospective'' book, was released less than a month ago. On 
Sunday, it will be at the top of The New York Times' paperback 
nonfiction best-seller list. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty amazing,'' Rob Siegel, The Onion's senior editor,  
said of the book's success. ``We didn't expect it, but we have a 
pretty solid, devoted, sizable underground fan base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book contains front page headlines and stories, putatively  
from old issues of The Onion, documenting historical events from 
1900 to 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	All are written and designed by staff members of the satirical  
paper, which is actually only 11 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	A story dated Nov. 9, 1960, on John F. Kennedy's election to the  
White House calls him ``our nation's first handsome president'' and 
cites experts who noted that previous chief executives were 
``mildly attractive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The paper is a pretty big task to do every week,'' Siegel  
said. ``We spent basically two full years working round the clock, 
putting out the paper and the book.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The weekly paper started in Madison and now has offices in  
Chicago, Denver and Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	It features irreverent, off-the-wall headlines such as ``Soul  
Train Derails New Snacks'' and ``Social Security System Overhauled 
to Provide Early-Death Incentives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inside, there are serious movie and music reviews.  
</P>
<P>
	About 500,000 people read The Onion online at its Web site --  
www.theonion.com -- every week, Siegel said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Onion has a deal to do a second book -- a compilation of  
material from the newspaper -- for Crown Publishers, a division of 
Random House that published ``Our Dumb Century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A television special for NBC on ``Our Dumb Century'' also is in  
the works, Siegel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 06:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Rejects Teen's Confession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A judge acquitted a 16-year-old boy who had  
confessed to stabbing to death a woman who, according to the 
coroner, had not been stabbed at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook County Judge Thomas Sumner said Thursday that no physical  
evidence tied the suspect, Eddie Huggins, to the slaying of 
Lorraine Gates, 26, in January 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Huggins, who was charged as an adult with murder, has been in  
custody for more than a year. Though he gave a confession to 
police, Huggins says he didn't kill her and claims he signed the 
confession only after threats and hours of questioning by police 
officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sumner -- who heard the case without a jury -- suggested law  
enforcement authorities lost sight of their duty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes in this system -- in this process we have which is  
presumed to ferret out the truth -- the truth gets obscured in the 
process of winning and losing,'' the judge said in announcing his 
verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Lary Simms, a former assistant Cook County medical examiner,  
testified that police knew within hours of Huggins' arrest that an 
autopsy showed Ms. Gates had died from blunt trauma and 
strangulation, not stabbing. 
</P>
<P>
	Huggins' attorneys called the case a travesty of justice and  
called for a special prosecutor to investigate police misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``They put the words in his mouth that he stabbed her repeatedly  
and tussled about the apartment,'' said lawyer R. Eugene Pincham, a 
former appellate judge. ``But they didn't get the script right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors Caren Armbrust, Bernard Murray and Dan Fahlgren had  
no comment after the verdict. Bob Benjamin, spokesman for Cook 
County State's Attorney Dick Devine, said there was no reason to 
investigate police. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Huggins after a 17-year-old acquaintance, who  
was arrested on another charge, said Huggins told him that he 
killed a woman. 
</P>
<P>
	But no physical evidence and no eyewitnesses link Huggins to the  
crime. DNA tests showed the victim's and someone else's blood on a 
jacket taken from the 17-year-old who implicated Huggins. Tests 
showed it wasn't Huggins' blood. Tests also excluded Huggins as the 
source of semen recovered from Ms. Gates' body. The 17-year-old's 
DNA has not been tested. 
</P>
<P>
	Local authorities are already under fire for a case last year in  
which two boys, ages 7 and 8, were charged with first degree murder 
in the July slaying of 11-year-old honor student Ryan Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	The two boys were arrested after six hours of questioning by  
detectives, who said the two confessed to killing Ryan because they 
wanted her new bicycle. 
</P>
<P>
	Charges against the boys were dropped in September after crime  
lab tests found semen in Ryan's clothing. A 30-year-old man was 
eventually charged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:32:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WNBA Voting on New Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Members of the WNBA players union were voting  
today on whether to approve a new four-year collective bargaining 
agreement that would pave the way for the start of the league's 
third season. 
</P>
<P>
	``About half the ballots are in and there's been an overwhelming  
response in one direction, but I can't say which way,'' union 
executive director Pam Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	A majority is required for approval.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still optimistic about the agreement being ratified,''  
Wheeler said Friday. ``I don't know when we'll have all the 
ballots. Hopefully, we'll have them by the end of the day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The final result of the voting might not be revealed until  
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The players association and the league reached a deal after a  
four-hour meeting Thursday -- a week after an apparent accord fell 
apart when each side accused the other of trying to change terms at 
the last minute. 
</P>
<P>
	That forced the league to postpone its player draft, scheduled  
for last Tuesday, for a week. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract, if approved, would set a salary scale for draft  
picks of $50,000 for the first four players chosen, $44,000 for the 
fifth through eighth players and $37,500 for the rest of the 
players chosen in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Second-round picks would get $30,000, third-round $27,000 and  
fourth-round picks would earn the rookie minimum of $25,000. The 
deal includes increases of five percent per year in those scales. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosters can include three players from the folded ABL, except  
for the expansion Orlando and Minnesota franchises, which will be 
permitted five former ABL players each. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal has a reopener clause after three years, and both sides  
agreed to no-lockout, no-strike clauses. 
</P>
<P>
	Players will receive a guaranteed percentage of all royalties  
from the sale of player-identified licensed products with a minimum 
payment of $100,000 to be made each year to the union. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract also includes provisions for a 401K plan,  
year-round health and dental insurances and paid maternity leave. 
</P>
<P>
	Players also will be allowed to participate in up to two  
not-for-profit, charitable events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 03:14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PEZ-Heads Making Sweet Pilgrimage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORANGE, Conn. (AP) -- The sugar in the air. The flip-top  
dispensers. The tart rectangular candies. This, undoubtedly, is PEZ 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	You don't have to tell the PEZ-heads. Hundreds of people who  
love the candy and the colorful, collectible dispensers it comes in 
are flocking here from as far away as Austria and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The mother ship, in this case, is PEZ Candy Inc. And the  
occasion is this weekend's first-ever gathering of PEZ aficionados 
in the town where the treats are manufactured. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll be all over the lawn with telephoto lenses. They'll be  
with their noses up against the back window,'' said Scott 
McWhinnie, the ``Pezident'' of PEZ Candy. ``They'll be picking 
through the garbage looking for old dispensers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Convention organizer Richard Belyski said PEZ-heads are mostly  
baby boomers trying to relive their childhood. ``Everybody 
remembers them as a kid. We're people from all walks of life, 
doctors, lawyers,'' said Belyski, 41, a police officer in Glen 
Cove, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	PEZ lovers will tell you their favorite treat is not just a  
hard, fruit-flavored candy. It's an American icon that spans 
generations. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the mystique focuses on the different character  
dispensers, from Mickey Mouse to Fred Flintstone and Spiderman to 
Kermit the Frog. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many of his brethren, Johann Patek, 42, who flew in from  
Vienna, Austria, for the convention, has so many dispensers he has 
lost count. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know. I cannot explain,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	John Laspina, 45, of Middletown, N.J., admits he has spent $850  
or more for a single dispenser -- the ``psychedelic eye'' created in 
the '60s. He has five of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was a kid, between Sunday school and church, I used to  
run to fill up my PEZ,'' said Laspina, a faraway look in his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	David Welch, 37, of Murphysboro, Ill., also had his first  
experience with PEZ as a child and has since become an authority, 
having written two books, ``Pictorial Guide to Plastic Candy 
Dispensers'' and the seminal ``Collecting PEZ.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He specializes in historical dispensers. The originals look like  
cigarette lighters, which is fitting, since Austrian Eduard Haas 
invented PEZ in 1927 as a mint for smokers. The name was derived 
from the German word for peppermint, pfefferminz. 
</P>
<P>
	PEZ didn't arrive in America until 1952. About 3 billion are  
consumed annually in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	A 12-PEZ pack has 35 calories and no nutritional value  
whatsoever, but McWhinnie insisted there are candies that are worse 
for you. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have a lot of dental problems with PEZ,'' he said.  
``PEZ don't stick to your teeth. They dissolve.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:26:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dollar Rises, Japanese Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen in Tokyo today  
despite an indication from a top Japanese economic official that 
the government may consider new stimulus steps. The Tokyo stock 
market's main index lost 1.42 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.58 yen at late afternoon, up 0.50 yen from  
its level of 119.08 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its 
overnight New York level of 119.03 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 240.71 points,  
or 1.42 percent, closing the week at 16,701.53 points. The Nikkei 
dropped 15.03 points, or 0.09 percent, Wednesday. Tokyo financial 
markets were closed Thursday for a national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar advanced as interbank dealers bought the U.S.  
currency despite remarks by Japan's Economic Planning Agency chief, 
Taichi Sakaiya, who said in Washington late Thursday that Japan 
would mull measures to stimulate the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakaiya, speaking after meeting with U.S. Deputy Treasury  
Secretary Lawrence Summers, denied that the government was 
considering a supplementary budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sakaiya's comment may suggest there was a progress toward new  
fiscal steps for the economy. But his words are a bit too vague to 
sell off dollars on,'' said Minoru Shioiri, assistant manager of 
foreign exchange at Nippon Credit Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors were waiting for the outcome of the summit  
between Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and U.S. President Bill Clinton 
in Washington on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite some signs of improvement, Japan's economy remains weak  
as the country struggles to bail out of its worst recession in 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 118.95 yen and 119.68 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 126.86 yen, down  
from 127.22 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Japanese technology shares dropped in line  
with the decline of similar shares overnight in New York. Also 
dampening the Tokyo market was Sony Corp.'s recent announcement of 
falling profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentiment among investors turned bearish quickly today following  
the release of fresh data on the state of Japan's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony said Wednesday that its net income plunged nearly 20  
percent in the fiscal year ending March 31 because of recession at 
home and abroad. Sony stock closed today's trading at $93.70, down 
$4.60 from Wednesday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The Management and Coordination Agency said Japan's jobless rate  
climbed to a record high 4.8 percent in March as corporate 
restructuring efforts forced more people out of work. The previous 
record was 4.6 percent, registered in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the agency said spending by Japanese wage earners  
last month fell 3.6 percent from the year-earlier month in real 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 535  
million shares, down from Wednesday's turnover of 677 million 
shares. Declining issues outnumbered advancers 646 to 512, with 163 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 10.52 points, or 0.78 percent, to 1,337.12 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.405 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.465 
percent, pushing its price up to 103.49 yen from 102.94 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Japan will be closed Monday through  
Wednesday because of national holidays. The markets will reopen on 
Thursday. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0120 </DOCNO>
