<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smoker Wins $2.2M Asbestos Verdict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A cancer sufferer who smoked cigarettes with  
asbestos filters has won a $2.2 million jury verdict against 
manufacturers of the brand. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Connor, 75, sued after he was diagnosed in June 1997  
with mesothelioma, a cancer linked to asbestos. He had smoked a 
pack of Kents a day for eight years before quitting about 37 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury on Thursday returned the verdict against Lorillard Inc.,  
maker of Kents, and Hollingsworth &AMP; Vose Co., which made the 
``Micronite'' filters used in the cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the companies said they would appeal. The companies  
have won nine of the 11 other lawsuits that have been tried. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent cigarettes were the only brand that had asbestos in  
filters. Advertising for the cigarettes sold from 1952 to 1956 
called them ``the protection you need'' against tar and nicotine 
because asbestos would filter the toxins. 
</P>
<P>
	Lorillard lawyer Roger Geary argued that tests done in the 1950s  
found the filters didn't release asbestos into the smoke. At the 
time, medical journals rated Kent as one of the best cigarettes for 
removing tar and nicotine, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company abandoned the filters because they were expensive  
and caused a bad taste, Geary said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit alleged an elaborate cover-up by the companies to  
hide the dangers of the filters. Studies in 1954 about whether 
asbestos was leaking into the smoke have disappeared, the lawsuit 
stated. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers who monitor tobacco litigation said the verdict  
reflected a growing hostility toward cigarette manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very important,'' said Richard Daynard, a law professor  
at Northeastern University and chairman of the Tobacco Products 
Liability Project. ``It shows that juries are now willing to hit 
tobacco companies hard for misbehavior.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 10:47:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Higher; Dow Up 65.87 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks headed higher today, pushing the Dow  
Jones industrial average closer to 11,000, after a government 
report said the U.S. economy grew faster than expected in the first 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
65.87 to 10,944.25, less than 56 points from 11,000. The Dow has 
set a record high close in each of the last three sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also rose. The Nasdaq composite index  
was up 36.57 to 2,565.01 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 
7.82 to 1,350.65. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. economy grew at a strong 4.5 percent annual rate in the  
first three months of this year, far above expectations, as 
consumers spent at the fastest pace in more than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported that the solid growth in the  
gross domestic product, the total output of goods and services, 
came despite the fact that the nation's trade deficit, battered by 
overseas economic turmoil, soared to a record level. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have an economy that is performing exceptionally well,''  
said Michael Moran, chief economist at Daiwa Securities America. 
``We're seeing vigorous demand in the U.S. and have a comfortable 
inflation situation which is a favorable setting for the stock 
market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the Dow higher was Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing,  
up 4 7/8 to 90 1/2, after 3M reported higher than expected first-quarter 
profits. Dow component United Technologies, which announced a 
two-for-one stock split today, was up 3 9/16 to 147 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks also rallied after three days of losses.  
</P>
<P>
	America Online advanced 3 1/8 to 144 1/2. Hewlett-Packard rose 1 1/8 to  
79 1/2 after a Merrill Lynch analyst said the personal computer maker 
will likely top second-quarter earnings estimates of 79 cents per 
share. IBM rose 4 13/16 to 209 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 402.7 million shares, 
slightly below Thursday's level. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 2.66 to 640.75 , and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 2.38 to 781.38. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 11:24:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans Youth Violence Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he will convene a  
White House strategy session with representatives of the Internet 
and entertainment industries, the gun lobby, government and the 
clergy to build a national movement against youth violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The session, a response to last week's Colorado school shooting,  
is slated for May 10. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need nothing less than a grass-roots effort to protect our  
children and turn them away from violence,'' Clinton said in a Rose 
Garden announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	``If citizens, parents and children alike working together in  
their communities can reduce teen pregnancy, reduce drunk driving, 
make seat-belt use nearly universal, then working together we can 
protect our children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton emphasized that he wanted gun manufacturers and gun  
owners, whose political lobbies have bitterly fought him on 
gun-control legislation, to be part of the White House discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's bury the hatchet and build a future for our children  
together,'' he offered. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, in an interview broadcast on NBC's ``Today,''  
Clinton made clear that he would not limit any White House youth 
violence summit to the influence of the entertainment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``What should we do about guns? What should we do about culture?  
What should we do about the schools? How can we help the parents? 
And, what is government's responsibility? Those are the big 
questions. We should ask and answer all of them -- not just one,'' 
Clinton said on the television program. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Congress asked Clinton earlier this week to convene  
an emergency summit of entertainment industry executives to address 
the kind of youth rage that erupted at Columbine High School in 
Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
