<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smoker Wins $2.2M Asbestos Verdict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A cancer sufferer who smoked cigarettes with  
asbestos filters has won a $2.2 million jury verdict against 
manufacturers of the brand. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Connor, 75, sued after he was diagnosed in June 1997  
with mesothelioma, a cancer linked to asbestos. He had smoked a 
pack of Kents a day for eight years before quitting about 37 years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury on Thursday returned the verdict against Lorillard Inc.,  
maker of Kents, and Hollingsworth &AMP; Vose Co., which made the 
``Micronite'' filters used in the cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the companies said they would appeal. The companies  
have won nine of the 11 other lawsuits that have been tried. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent cigarettes were the only brand that had asbestos in  
filters. Advertising for the cigarettes sold from 1952 to 1956 
called them ``the protection you need'' against tar and nicotine 
because asbestos would filter the toxins. 
</P>
<P>
	Lorillard lawyer Roger Geary argued that tests done in the 1950s  
found the filters didn't release asbestos into the smoke. At the 
time, medical journals rated Kent as one of the best cigarettes for 
removing tar and nicotine, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company abandoned the filters because they were expensive  
and caused a bad taste, Geary said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit alleged an elaborate cover-up by the companies to  
hide the dangers of the filters. Studies in 1954 about whether 
asbestos was leaking into the smoke have disappeared, the lawsuit 
stated. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers who monitor tobacco litigation said the verdict  
reflected a growing hostility toward cigarette manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very important,'' said Richard Daynard, a law professor  
at Northeastern University and chairman of the Tobacco Products 
Liability Project. ``It shows that juries are now willing to hit 
tobacco companies hard for misbehavior.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
