<HEADLINE> Prices Mixed on Wall Street / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed on Wall Street today after  
analysts found data in the government's latest economic assessment 
that rekindled inflation fears. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average  
was down 89.34 at 10,789.04. Broader market indicators were mixed, 
with the Nasdaq composite closing modestly higher and the Standard 
&AMP; Poor's 500 index falling. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow, up during morning trading, began sinking after the bond  
market dropped markedly in response to the Commerce Department's 
report that the U.S. economy grew at a strong 4.5 percent annual 
rate in the first three months of this year, far above 
expectations. The gain was attributed to consumers spending at the 
fastest pace in more than a decade . 
</P>
<P>
	Bond traders reacted to an inflation measure tied to the GDP,  
which rose at an annual rate of 1.4 from January through March, up 
from a 0.8 percent increase in the fourth quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The price hike overshadowed the solid growth in the gross  
domestic product, the total output of goods and services, which 
soared despite the nation's worsening trade deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond market yields soared to 5.65 percent from late Thursday's  
5.52 percent as investors feared the economic strength would 
reignite inflation and prompt the Federal Reserve to push interest 
rates higher. Higher rates raised the specter of high borrowing 
costs and lower corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like the bond market clobbered the stock market,''  
said David Orr, chief economist at First Union Capital Markets 
Group in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The down mood in the financial markets was compounded by a  
report from corporate purchasing executives that said manufacturing 
activity surged in the Midwest during April. The report by the 
Purchasing Management Association of Chicago is often viewed as a 
precursor to the survey on the economy by the National Association 
of Purchasing Management, which issues its report on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Dow stocks, American Express slipped 4 11/16 to 130 11/16  
and J.P. Morgan fell 3 1/4 to 134 3/4 because a rise in interest rates is 
likely to hurt financial service companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But technology stocks rallied after three days of losses.  
America Online rose 1 5/8 to 143. Amazon.com was up 3 13/16 to 172 
1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard rose 3/8 to 78 3/4 after a Merrill Lynch analyst said  
the personal computer maker will likely top second-quarter earnings 
estimates of 79 cents per share. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
