<HEADLINE> CheckFree Says Problem Nearly Resolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- CheckFree said Friday that it was almost  
glitch-free again after services were disrupted this week for some 
home-banking consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswoman Stephanie Norton said the system was working at 98  
percent capacity and the company expected to soon be operating 
without any problems. 
</P>
<P>
	She said technical staffers had identified a software  
application problem that caused up to 500,000 people who used 
Quicken or Microsoft Money software to face sporadic difficulty 
accessing their bank accounts or completing transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 20 banks that had been switched to a new processing system  
over the last six months were affected in a problem that began 
showing up early Monday. Customers were advised to use paper checks 
or telephone or automatic tellers to make transactions if they were 
having problems. 
</P>
<P>
	CheckFree representatives will work with each bank to resolve  
any problems caused by late payments related to the glitch, the 
company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Based in Norcross, Ga., CheckFree Holdings Co. has some 2.8  
million customers and helps provide electronic payment services at 
350 institutions. 

</P>
</TEXT>
