<HEADLINE> Vanderbilt Assistant Faces Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Dennis Harrison, a former NFL player and  
defensive line coach at Vanderbilt, was charged with assault for 
allegedly hitting his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrison's lawyer denied the charges against his client, The  
Tennessean reported on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrison, 42, was arrested Thursday after an incident at his  
home last Saturday, police said. He was charged with assault and 
released the same day on $5,000 bond. 
</P>
<P>
	Nashville police said Harrison, who is 6-foot-8 and weighs 300  
pounds, knocked his wife across the kitchen, knocking her to the 
floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Ida Harrison, 46, was treated at Vanderbilt Hospital. The arrest  
warrant said she received a severe black and blue right eye, 
swelling to her face and other bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrison faces a court date May 25 in General Sessions Court.  
</P>
<P>
	Harrison played for Philadelphia, the Los Angeles Rams, San  
Francisco and Atlanta. He was hired by Vanderbilt in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrison and wife Ida have 11 children.  
</P>
<P>
	Ida Harrison could not be reached for comment Friday.  
</P>
