<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Safety Varies Among Flight Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- International travelers buying tickets from an  
airline with a good safety record may end up traveling on a carrier 
with a lesser one, thanks to the spread of worldwide airline 
partnerships. 
</P>
<P>
	Continental Airlines, for example, offers regular service from  
Newark, N.J., to Taipei, Taiwan. On one trip, passengers carrying 
Continental tickets bearing Continental flight numbers fly on a 
Continental plane to San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	When they arrive, their tickets and flight numbers continue to  
read ``Continental,'' but they are transferred to a plane of one of 
the carrier's Asian partners, China Airlines, for the leg to 
Taipei. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the Air Travelers Association, a Washington passenger  
advocacy group, gave Continental an A for flight safety. China 
Airlines, which had fatal accidents in 1994 and 1989, as well as a 
747 skid into Hong Kong harbor in 1993, got an F. 
</P>
<P>
	Another survey, conducted in 1996 by the travel publisher Conde  
Naste, listed the Taiwan-based China Airlines with an accident rate 
of 11.43 fatal accidents per million flights. Continental had a 
fatal accident rate of 0.29. 
</P>
<P>
	The growing practice of flight partnerships known as  
``code-shares'' makes the problem of inconsistent flight safety 
especially vexing. While airlines have been passing off customers 
for years, they used to do so with separate tickets and flight 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Code-shares present the illusion that one airline is providing  
all of a passenger's flight service. Airlines favor the arrangement 
because it allows them to project the image of a larger route 
network, while giving passengers the ability to make seamless 
connections between airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	The government requires airlines to warn passengers when they  
will be switched to another carrier, but it concedes the warnings 
sometimes aren't given or don't filter through a travel agent. 
</P>
<P>
	That has prompted action:  
</P>
<P>
	--The Transportation Department, which must approve code-shares,  
is considering changing its policies so it can directly weigh the 
quality of the foreign airline partner. Under existing rules, the 
department looks only at the safety standards of the country where 
the foreign carrier is based, not at the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Defense Department, which spends $1.2 billion annually on  
travel, is about to ask six major airlines -- American, Continental, 
Delta, Northwest, TWA and United -- to complete safety checks of 
their code-share partners. 
</P>
<P>
	--The inspector general for the Transportation Department is  
analyzing whether code-share policy assesses foreign airline 
safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of this is fairly new and it's growing, so we're reviewing  
how we ought to look at these,'' said Patrick Murphy, deputy 
assistant secretary of transportation for aviation and 
international affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, Delta Air Lines suspended its partnership with  
Korean Air after a cargo jet flown by the Asian carrier crashed in 
Shanghai, China. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming in the aftermath of other Korean Air accidents, and a  
report by two Korean Air pilots critical of the airline's safety, 
Delta said it would not put its passengers on the planes ``pending 
a thorough review.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is that when you put your code on another  
carrier's flight, you're putting your cloak of respectability and 
safety onto that carrier's airplane,'' said David Stempler, 
president of the Air Travelers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines are reluctant to say how they check the safety of their  
flight partners, but most say they would not knowingly put their 
passengers at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Dave Messing said Continental Airlines cannot control  
partners' flights, but ``we do monitor the safety and performance 
of alliance airlines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	United Airlines, which participates in the Star Alliance with  
such major carriers as Lufthansa and Air Canada, said airlines must 
agree to a 20-point safety program before they are admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the requirements: that they share safety data and that the  
leader of each airline make a public statement saying employees 
will not be punished if they report safety problems. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
