<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firstar To Acquire Mercantile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Firstar Corporation will acquire Mercantile  
Bancorporation Inc. for about $10.6 billion in stock, creating a 
Midwestern banking powerhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined bank would be the 13th largest bank holding company  
in the United States, with assets of more than $75 billion and 
deposits of $59 billion. It would have assets under management of 
$67 billion and a market capitalization of $32 billion, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal values Mercantile at $66 per share, a premium of 29  
percent over Mercantile's closing stock price Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition was announced after the market closed Friday.  
Takeover speculation during the trading session helped send shares 
of Mercantile up $5.75, or 11 percent, to close at $57 on the New 
York Stock Exchange. Shares of Firstar slipped $1.50, or 5 percent, 
to close at $30.06 1/4 on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	This transaction will create the second largest Midwest banking  
franchise, providing a full line of consumer banking, commercial 
banking and trust and investment management services and products. 
It would have more than 5 million customers through its 
approximately 1,180 branch locations in nine Midwest states and 
Tennessee, Arkansas and Arizona, plus trust operations in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined companies' corporate headquarters will remain in  
Milwaukee, with St. Louis becoming the headquarters for corporate 
banking and Cincinnati continuing as the headquarters for consumer 
banking. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry A. Grundhofer, Firstar's president and chief executive  
officer, will continue in that position, Firstar said. Thomas H. 
Jacobsen, Mercantile's chairman, president and chief executive 
officer, will become chairman of the board of Firstar and will 
co-chair the board's executive committee with Grundhofer. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger L. Fitzsimonds, Firstar's current chairman, plans to  
retire upon the closing of the acquisition and will be named 
chairman emeritus at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	The board of directors will be comprised of 14 representatives  
of Firstar and four representatives of Mercantile. 
</P>
<P>
	Firstar Corporation, based in Milwaukee, now has $38 billion in  
assets and about 720 banking offices in Ohio, Wisconsin, Kentucky, 
Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Minnesota, Tennessee and Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercantile, with $36 billion in asset, is based in St. Louis.  
The company operates banks in nearly 500 locations in Missouri, 
Iowa, Kansas, Illinois, Arkansas and Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercantile's non-banking subsidiaries include companies  
providing brokerage services, asset-based lending, factoring, 
investment advisory services, leasing services and credit life and 
other insurance products as agent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
