<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Repsol Offers $13B for YPF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADRID, Spain (AP) -- The Spanish energy company Repsol is  
offering $13.4 billion for the Argentine oil giant YPF in a deal 
that would create a more formidable Latin American rival to the 
state oil companies of Venezuela and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer announced late Thursday could lead to the latest  
merger in the rapidly consolidating oil industry. A deal would 
create one of the world's 10 biggest oil companies with revenue of 
more than $27 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Last December, Exxon and Mobil agreed to merge in a deal now  
worth nearly $88 billion that will create the world's largest oil 
company. Earlier this year, BP Amoco announced it planned to 
acquire Atlantic Richfield Co. in a deal now valued at nearly $30 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Repsol's cash offer of $44.78 a share for the 85 percent of YPF  
that it doesn't already own represents a 25 percent premium over 
the Argentine company's closing price Thursday on the Buenos Aires 
Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	If the deal between the two former state-owned oil companies  
goes through, Repsol hopes to achieve double-digit earnings growth 
until 2002, Repsol chairman Alfonso Cortina told a news conference 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	While the bid was uninvited, Cortina declined to describe it a  
hostile, adding that he hoped the YPF board would recommend the 
offer to shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate comment from YPF.  
</P>
<P>
	Cortina said the takeover would allow Repsol to cut costs by  
between $300 million and $350 million a year, primarily through 
merging YPF with Repsol's Astra unit in Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to give a figure on potential job cuts, and said  
that the net affect of the deal would be to create employment 
opportunities as the company would grow so fast. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company would be among the world oil industry's top 10,  
Cortina told reporters. It would be the seventh largest in refining 
capacity, the eighth in terms of crude reserves and the ninth 
measured on crude oil and natural gas production, Spanish news 
agency Efe reported. 
</P>
<P>
	To pay for its cash offer, Repsol has arranged a syndicated loan  
$15.5 billion with Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co, La 
Caixa, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., Citigroup Inc. and UBS AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite this heavy debt, Cortina said the bid won't put too much  
pressure on the company's balance sheet. He said Repsol will reduce 
the impact of the debt through a large capital increase and by 
issuing convertible bonds. Another $2.5 billion of the debt will be 
reduced through the sale of non-core assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Repsol offer expires June 23, and will be conditioned on,  
among other things, Repsol's acquisition of more than 50 percent of 
YPF's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Cortina said any opposing bid for YPF must be more than $47 a  
share because of an agreement between Repsol and the Argentine 
government signed when the Spanish company bought 15 percent of the 
Argentine oil giant in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Repsol currently has refining operations in four countries and  
nearly 1 billion barrels in oil and gas reserves, primarily in 
North Africa, the Middle East and Latin America. It earned $1.9 
billion on revenue of $22.2 billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	YPF owns and operates three refineries, and owns 2,253 service  
stations in Argentina; it has more than 3 billion barrels in oil 
and gas reserves. It earned $1.1 billion on revenue of $5.5 billion 
in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
