<HEADLINE> U.S. May See Trouble in World Hockey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        OSLO, Norway (AP) -- The United States will be relying on a  
makeshift squad of NHL and European-based players at hockey's world 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
        The Americans, led by Kevin Stevens of the New York Rangers,  
need to finish at least second in its four-team group to advance to 
the second round. 
</P>
<P>
        Six NHL players turned down invitations to play for American  
squad this week, including Edmonton's Bill Guerin, Doug Weight, Todd 
Marchant, Tom Poti and Mike Grier and Ottawa's Shawn McEachern. 
</P>
<P>
        The United States, which beat Canada in the final of the 1996  
World Cup with its best players, finished 12th last year in Switzerland 
and had to qualify for these championships. 
</P>
<P>
        ``The margins are small,'' said Art Berglund, general manager  
of Team USA. ``In Switzerland, we beat the Swiss 5-2 in the first game. 
The Swiss then went on to the semifinals while we ended up 12th.'' 
</P>
<P>
        One highlight will be the debut of Sweden's 18-year-old twins,  
Daniel and Henrik Sedin. 
</P>
<P>
        In their debut in Sweden's 4-3 exhibition loss to Finland in  
Stockholm last week, Henrik set up his brother for a goal. 
</P>
<P>
        Both are likely first-round picks in the NHL Draft this summer.  
But only one is expected to enter, with the other one waiting until 
next year's draft to improve their hopes of playing on the same NHL 
club. 
</P>
<P>
        Sweden added 1996 NHL Rookie of the Year Daniel Alfredsson  
to its roster after the Ottawa Senators were eliminated in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
        Among other Swedish NHLers accepting invitations were goalie  
Tommy Salo of the Edmonton Oilers, high-scoring Markus Naslund of the 
Vancouver Canucks and Niklas Sundstrom of the Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
        Canada's strength lies in its defense, anchored by Rob Blake  
of the Los Angeles Kings, who won the 1998 Norris Trophy as the NHL's 
top defenseman. 
</P>
<P>
        Ron Tugnutt of Ottawa is likely to be Canada's No. 1 goalie.  
He had the best NHL's best goals-against average (1.79). 
</P>
<P>
        Forwards will include Adam Graves of the New York Rangers (38  
goal this season), Eric Daze of the Chicago Blackhawks (22 goals), 
Ray Whitney of the Florida Panthers (26 goals) and Cory Stillman of 
the Calgary Flames (27 goals). 
</P>
<P>
        Teemu Selanne of the Anaheim Mighty Ducks, who was the NHL's  
top goal scorer (47 goals) this season, will be reunited on the same 
line with Saku Koivu of the Montreal Canadiens. 
</P>
<P>
        Another high scoring forward, Alexei Yashin of Ottawa (44 goals  
and 94 points this season), is expected to join the Russian squad. 
</P>
<P>
        The tournament starts Saturday with Canada against Slovakia  
in the Group A opener and Austria against the Czech Republic in Group 
C in Oslo. Italy plays host nation Norway (Group A) and the U.S. meets 
Japan in an evening game. 
</P>
<P>
        Latvia and Switzerland meet in the Group B opener on Sunday  
followed by Sweden against France. In Group D games, Russia takes on 
Belarus and Finland plays Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
