<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Wallstreet.com' Sells for $1M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- What's in a name? For Eric ``Wall  
Street'' Wade and his two partners, it's more than $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The trio sold Wade's Internet name -- wallstreet.com -- to Players  
Only, a Venezuelan company, for about $343,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Players Only plans to use the site for a gambling game based on  
stock performance. Players Only has said it will offer stock 
quotes, company information and online trading -- along with 
gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade, a former Albuquerque stockbroker, and a friend registered  
wallstreet.com for $70 in 1994. They had planned to develop a 
full-scale financial services site, but then they started getting 
unsolicited offers for the name. 
</P>
<P>
	The partners and a friend sold wallstreet.com last week through  
online auctioneers New Commerce Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	Domain names -- the combinations of letters, numbers and-or  
symbols that serve as Internet addresses -- can pay off big. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, the name altavista.com sold for $3.35 million last  
year. Other recent sales include business.com for $150,000, 
internet.com for $100,000 and tv.com for $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The name wallstreet.com attracted attention immediately, Wade  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Between 4,000 and 17,000 people a day would just type `Wall  
Street' into their browser. We called it background noise. People 
were just typing it in to see what would happen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
