<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 02:34:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC To Help Pay for Scandal Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- International Olympic Committee members  
might have to accept less than first-class service at the Sydney 
2000 Games to help pay for budgetary damage caused by the Olympics 
bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Rogge, a senior executive board member and chairman of  
the IOC coordination commission, said today the IOC has agreed to 
cut the cost of services it will demand from Sydney to help meet a 
reduced budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG)  
last week announced it would cut $48.7 million from the budget, 
blaming in part a lack of sponsorship interest caused by the 
Olympic corruption scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge, visiting Sydney to review preparations for the games, met  
with Sydney Olympic sponsors on Tuesday and apologized for the 
damage the scandal caused to the games' marketing potential. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course we played a role in the difficulties of SOCOG to  
reach that (sponsorship) target,'' Rogge said today at the end of 
commission's visit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will take our responsibilities. By reducing the services  
that SOCOG will have to provide to us, we're going to give them a 
substantial saving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Services to the IOC are included in the host city contract.  
Rogge said IOC members' travel, accommodation and some other 
running costs are paid for by the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said the budget shortfall -- $32.5 million of expected  
sponsor revenue written off and an extra $16 million allocated for 
``contingencies'' -- was not all the IOC's fault. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG president Michael Knight, who directly blamed the  
sponsorship shortfall on the IOC scandal, said the IOC accepted 
that ``they are some of the problem and they must go some way 
towards assisting us to resolve it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After visiting games venues and being briefed on Sydney's  
readiness, Rogge said preparations were generally up to speed. 
</P>
<P>
	Two areas had been singled out for special attention -- the  
budget and technology. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a delay in the implementation and testing of the sport  
results system -- a major headache at Atlanta in 1996 -- has been 
addressed with more personnel and money being allocated. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said the commission gave the thumbs-up to arrangements for  
the sports venues, the Olympic villages, hotel accommodation, 
transport, security and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	One venue problem exists -- some local residents oppose part of  
Sydney's famous Bondi beach being closed for the beach volleyball. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight said he would consider legal action against the local  
council if it sought to withdraw from an in-principle agreement to 
hold the competition on the beach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
