<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Convicted in Mass. Standoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A man who barricaded himself on his 14-acre estate  
for nine months in a fight over whether he had to repay a $1.6 
million bank loan was convicted of contempt Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	John Sweeney, who was captured in his home February 1998 by six  
marshals after they broke a window to get in, faces a maximum six 
months in prison when sentenced in August. He said he planned to 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials say they own the estate because Sweeney and  
his wife, Rhetta, defaulted on their 1987 bank loan, which had been 
taken over by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney, 59, was evicted but refused to leave the estate, which  
once belonged to his great-grandfather, a secretary of the Navy, 
postmaster general and an ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also said the Sweeneys owed $1.4 million in taxes  
in addition to the loan payments, but the Sweeneys said they had 
been swindled by the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, anti-government militia members allied themselves  
with the Sweeneys and patrolled the estate, 20 miles outside Boston 
and a few miles up the road from the fox-hunting and polo grounds 
of the Myopia Hunt Club. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
