<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Faulk Surprise Show at Rams' Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Running back Marshall Faulk, who wants a fresh  
start as well as a new deal, changed his mind about holding out 
until the St. Louis Rams re-work his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk showed up for the team's three-day minicamp, which began  
Friday, in what he said was a show of good faith. It didn't hurt 
that Faulk's agent, Rocky Arceneaux, and Rams executive vice 
president Jay Zygmunt have begun talks on renegotiating the 
seven-year deal he signed as a rookie in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it has anything to do with that,'' Faulk said.  
``I have no clue, to be honest with you, how the contract talks are 
going. I try to stay out of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk is set to make a base salary of $2.2 million next season  
and is seeking a multiyear deal that would pay him closer to $5 
million a year. The Rams indicated they're serious about upgrading 
Faulk's pay by releasing offensive guard Zach Wiegert, who had been 
due to make $3.2 million as the team's transition player, earlier 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk, acquired two days before the draft from the Indianapolis  
Colts for second- and fifth-round draft picks, backed off his 
no-show stance after he found out there would be 100 percent 
attendance at what the Rams called a voluntary minicamp. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was my decision,'' Faulk said. ``I felt if everybody else  
was going to make the commitment, I should put my issues aside and 
come in and show them I'm dedicated to winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk spent his first five professional seasons with the Colts,  
and he's looking forward to the change of scenery. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost like getting the opportunity to start all over  
again,'' he said. ``But to know what to expect, to know how to deal 
with it, to know what questions are going to be asked, and what's 
going to be asked of you from a team standpoint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk, who rushed for 1,319 yards and caught 86 passes last  
year, is among 82 players at the minicamp. The Rams also are 
getting a first look at new quarterback Trent Green, offensive 
guard Adam Timmerman, linebacker Todd Collins, safety Devin Bush 
and the seven-player draft class headed by wide receiver Torry 
Holt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
