<HEADLINE> Olympic Committee Hires Ad Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. Olympic Committee has hired an  
advertising firm to develop its first ad campaign even as it tries 
to help cover a shortfall in fund-raising for the scandal-ridden 
2002 Salt Lake City Games. 
</P>
<P>
	USA Today reported Friday that the committee expects to start a  
$10 million campaign in print media June 24 and that the ads would 
likely feature past and present Olympic athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from ad agency GSD&AMP;M included confirmation from  
Olympic officials, who did not immediately return calls for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Clay Russ, a senior vice president at the ad agency  
GSD&AMP;M, said his agency had been hired about a week ago to develop 
the campaign but said work was just starting. He was unable to 
confirm the spending figure, the starting date or any other 
details. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad plans are being disclosed as the Salt Lake Organizing  
Committee is still $300 million short of the $859 million in 
sponsor fees budgeted for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one sponsor -- timekeeper Seiko -- has signed up since the  
reports broke in November that members of the International Olympic 
Committee were given cash and other favors before Salt Lake was 
chosen as host for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson &AMP; Johnson broke off negotiations on a $30 million  
package in part because of the bribery case. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members have resigned or been expelled in the scandal.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
