<DOCNO> APW19990430.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Brantley Needs Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jeff Brantley doesn't know how or when he  
hurt his shoulder this time. The Philadelphia Phillies closer just 
knows he needs surgery and probably won't pitch again this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Brantley learned Friday that he needs surgery on his torn labrum  
-- the same type of injury that sidelined him for most of the 1997 
season. The only bright spot is that Dr. Craig Morgan told him the 
injury isn't career-threatening. 
</P>
<P>
	Brantley expects Dr. James Andrews to confirm the diagnosis when  
he visits him Monday in Birmingham, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed that I can't do this job,'' said  
Brantley, acquired from the Cardinals with Ron Gant in an offseason 
trade that sent former Phillies closer Ricky Bottalico to St. 
Louis. ``But I think that they will be happy with me one of these 
days. It may be spring training next year, but they'll get their 
money's worth out of Jeff Brantley.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan couldn't determine when Brantley injured his shoulder  
this time. He had arthroscopic surgery in 1997, came back in 1998 
with the Cardinals and pitched through pain all season. Brantley 
said he never had an MRI while with the Cardinals, and believes the 
labrum was torn last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody really asked me about my shoulder last year,'' Brantley  
said. ``They just sat me down in the bullpen and I got a free 
ticket. I really doubt that it happened in spring training. I would 
say, and this is just my feeling, that this was there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brantley had a dominant spring and started the season strong,  
recording four saves with a 2.84 ERA in seven games. He was 
sidelined for 11 days with a sore shoulder, returning to get a save 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting the ninth on Wednesday night, Brantley walked one  
batter and struck out another, then squatted behind the mound 
shaking his head in obvious pain and disappointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Brantley said the pain was nothing like what he felt at spring  
training in 1997, when he blew out his shoulder with one pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the only time that I've ever felt like my arm was going  
to explode,'' Brantley said. ``After that, it's just been very 
uncomfortable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just as he did in 1997 with the Reds, Brantley said he will stay  
with the Phillies while doing his rehab. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have to be here,'' Brantley said. ``I could go home  
and hang out with my family and watch my boy play ball, but these 
guys are paying me a lot of money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brantley makes $2.8 million this season in the last year of his  
contract. The Cardinals are paying $1 million of it as part of the 
trade. 
</P>
<P>
	While ruling over the bullpen as an elder statesman in  
Cincinnati, Brantley groomed Jeff Shaw into a dominant closer. He 
taught Shaw everything from how to read scouting reports and what 
to look for in newspapers to the importance of watching early 
batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure enough, Shaw, now with the Dodgers, was the only one in the  
dugout before the game Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It still amazes me that he can sit there and watch two or  
three pitches and know how to get a guy out,'' Shaw said. ``I'm 
like, `How do you see that?' And he says, `You don't see that? It's 
right there.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately for Brantley, it appears he'll be doing a lot of  
watching again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
