<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 10:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Orders Firms To Get Y2K Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's securities regulator urged listed firms  
Friday to take the threat of the Year 2000 computer problem 
seriously and purge their computer systems of any glitches, the 
official Xinhua News Agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In an open letter, the China Securities Regulatory Commission  
told the 878 listed firms to spend enough money and acquire enough 
expertise to modify and replace key computer systems so that they 
will not fail at year's end, Xinhua said. 
</P>
<P>
	Firms need to recognize the serious risks the computer glitch,  
known as Y2K, poses to the stability of markets and investor 
confidence, Xinhua cited the letter as saying. It added that firms 
ought to be prepared for lawsuits arising from any problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts fear that computers which use only the last two digits  
to mark the year will mistake 2000 for 1900 and malfunction. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the letter gave no indication how far along most firms  
were, its underlying tone confirmed assessments by foreign analysts 
that China's preparations were lagging. Last month, the 
government's top Y2K troubleshooter said a lack of money and 
experience were hampering China's readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial securities is one of 18 key sectors in which the  
government is expending all efforts to make sure are Y2K-compliant. 
The government troubleshooter, Zhang Qi, last month praised the 
securities sector for doing an ``excellent job'' in rooting out Y2K 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Securities exchanges and brokerages are supposed to have cleared  
their computer systems of the glitch by May 30. The sector has run 
three tests so far, Xinhua said. The last one, in February, turned 
up some problems, as was expected, officials have said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 14:35:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New `Swan Lake' Opens Ballet Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Arts and Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York City Ballet opened its season with  
a full-evening ballet, a new, two-act ``Swan Lake,'' choreographed 
by Peter Martins. 
</P>
<P>
	It's largely a success, though some scenes lag in the extended  
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Darci Kistler, clear in line and sublimely graceful, was  
glorious as the Swan Queen. Damian Woetzel danced a self-effacing 
Prince and Jock Soto was the evil Von Rotbart, a part expanded by 
Martins, ballet master in chief. 
</P>
<P>
	Martins choreographed the production after the 1895 work of  
Marius Petipa and Lev Ivanov and borrowed steps from George 
Balanchine's one-act version. 
</P>
<P>
	The first scene, at the Prince's 21st birthday party, has women  
guests in green dresses and men in orange tights and blouson tops, 
dancing in flowing patterns. But the scene becomes overlong. 
</P>
<P>
	Several times, Martins introduces tiny boy and girl dancers who  
momentarily steal the show. Providing variety are Benjamin Bowman 
as a spirited jester and a dance by Benjamin Millepied, Jennifer 
Tinsley and Pascale van Kipnis. 
</P>
<P>
	But one wonders, when do we get to the swans?  
</P>
<P>
	The Prince finally goes hunting, where he sees the women who  
have been changed to swans by Rotbart. Kistler uses arm motions to 
express her fear of the Prince and then, arms quivering, indicates 
she is intrigued. Kistler becomes a Swan Queen to make a Prince 
fall in love; she is feminine and self-sufficient, neither weak nor 
tough. 
</P>
<P>
	The four cygnets, Amanda Edge, Carrie Lee Riggins, Janie Taylor  
and Elizabeth Walker, none yet classified as a company soloist, 
were pert and diamond-sharp. 
</P>
<P>
	The corps de ballet was excellent. Martins moves them in  
semicircle and V lines instead of straight lines, keeping the 
classical look but subtly updating it. We missed solos by swans, 
but the length of the first scene apparently prevented those. 
</P>
<P>
	In Act 2, in the palace ballroom, six princesses in pastel gowns  
dance for the Prince, followed by Hungarian, Russian, Spanish and 
Neapolitan diversions. 
</P>
<P>
	Then enter the Black Swan, Rotbart's daughter cloned to look  
like the Swan Queen. In her new guise, Kistler doesn't turn cold; 
her gestures are delicate and feminine enough to fool the Prince. 
Often, near the end of their pas de deux, Rotbart yanks his 
daughter away from the Prince. This breaks the duet's building 
excitement. 
</P>
<P>
	In Martins' ending, the Swan Queen suffers heartbreakingly,  
crumbling to the ground, one leg bent under her. Black swans dance 
with white swans. After a short love duet by the Prince and Swan 
Queen, Rotbart falls and dies. But, because the Prince was tricked 
into declaring love for another, the Swan must leave him, 
despairing. 
</P>
<P>
	Per Kirkeby's and Kirsten Lund Nielsen's costumes were elaborate  
while Kirkeby's scenery was usually an abstract painting. In the 
final scene, the backdrop was brown wood, making the stage look 
like a courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Hugo Fiorato conducted the Tchaikovsky music. The New York City  
Ballet will dance at the New York State Theater through June 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
