<DOCNO> APW19990430.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 11:24:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Launches Another Titan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Anxious for a win after two failed  
missions, the Air Force today launched its most powerful rocket 
with an advanced military communication satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	Everything appeared to go well as the 2 million-pound Titan IV  
rumbled into a cloudy sky at 12:30 p.m. Liftoff was 1 1/2 hours late 
because of minor technical problems and overnight thunderstorms 
that put the launch team behind schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	A half-hour into the flight, the Air Force confirmed the first  
phase of launch had gone as planned. 
</P>
<P>
	The rocket carried an $800 million Milstar satellite for the  
Defense Department. It was bound for a 22,300-mile-high orbit where 
the first Milstar was placed in 1994 and the second in 1995. In 
all, six Milstars are planned. The satellites are designed to 
provide secure, jam-proof communication between U.S. commanders and 
troops in the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force officials said once the newest Milstar reached orbit,  
they would be unable to release any information if something goes 
wrong until a security review is conducted. Even then, certain 
information may be withheld if officials determine it could be 
exploited by an enemy. 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks ago, the last time a Titan IV rocket flew, the  
missile-warning satellite on board ended up in a useless orbit 
because of a malfunctioning upper-stage motor. Air Force officials 
acknowledged this week that the satellite will never reach the 
desired 22,300-mile-high orbit and therefore will never perform its 
intended mission. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the first Titan IV launch since last August, when the  
rocket and a spy satellite were destroyed in an explosion shortly 
after liftoff. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined losses of those two missions: nearly $2 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Today's mission cost $1.23 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	The Milstar program, criticized by the General Accounting Office  
last fall for being outdated and inefficient, was conceived during 
the Cold War and therefore designed to withstand the radiation 
fallout of a nuclear blast. 
</P>
<P>
	The military is less worried about nuclear war and more worried  
about conflicts like the one in Yugoslavia, said Air Force Col. 
Mike Kelly, a deputy commander. But he said the satellites are 
still useful. They have carried targeting information for cruise 
missiles, for instance, Kelly noted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reports that say Milstar can't do the job, I think those are  
flat wrong,'' he said. ``If there's only one communication system 
left in the United States in a catastrophe, it will be Milstar -- 
and Milstar will get the word through.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
