<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Islanders Introduce Coach Goring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) -- The New York Islanders have taken  
another spin on the coaching carousel. This time they wound up with 
a former player. 
</P>
<P>
	Butch Goring was introduced Friday as the ninth head coach in  
the franchise's 27-year history, replacing interim coach Bill 
Stewart who was fired after going 11-19-7. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had a long and successful career as a coach and player,''  
Islanders general manager Mike Milbury said of Goring. ``We've had 
problems as an organization in the last few years with regards to 
stability in our coaching situation. We think he's solved that 
problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goring becomes the fifth coach for the Islanders since the  
1994-95 season, a span that saw Milbury hold the job on two 
occasions. He started as coach last season and resigned Jan. 21, 
turning the team over to Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Goring's playing career spanned 16 seasons with Los Angeles, the  
Islanders and Boston. Immediately after retiring in 1985, he became 
the head coach of the Bruins and was fired during the 1986-87 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, he has coached on the junior level and in the minor  
leagues, winning consecutive International Hockey League 
championships with the Utah Grizzlies in 1995 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``He thinks very creatively, and more so offensively than  
defensively,'' Milbury said. ``His being a former Islander is also 
a plus, but it's certainly not the reason to go about things. I 
think I have more integrity than to bring in a guy with (this 
former) Stanley Cup team if I didn't think he could do the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goring, who agreed to a multiyear contract, coached Utah to a  
39-34 record last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, this is almost a dream come true,'' Goring said.  
``Since Al Arbour made me an assistant coach, there hasn't been a 
day that I haven't wanted to step in Al Arbour's shoes and be as 
successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goring promised the Islanders, who won four consecutive Stanley  
Cups in the 1980s under Arbour, would be more offensive minded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing good happens when the puck is in our end, so I want to  
forecheck and keep the puck in the other end,'' he said. ``Hockey 
is a game of emotions and reactions. I coach that way, and I want 
my players to play that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goring said he isn't concerned about any of the distractions  
that plagued the Islanders the last few seasons, from changes in 
ownership to losing talent to budgetary constraints. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will just coach the team I'm given,'' he said. ``I bleed  
Islander blue. I walked into a practice in Utah last season wearing 
an Islander jacket, and someone said to me, `Old habits die hard.' 
'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
