<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Attendants Agree To Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- America West flight attendants have approved a  
five-year labor contract, ending more than four years of bitter 
negotiations, officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	A tentative agreement had been reached last month, hours after a  
strike deadline had expired. That agreement was subject to approval 
by the union's 2,200 members. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 83 percent of those members voted to approve the  
contract by turning in their ballots by Friday's deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``The high turnout and high approval rate make this a clear  
mandate in favor of the contract,'' said Bill McGlashen, president 
of the Association of Flight Attendants Council representing 
America West. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight attendants are the fourth employee group to ratify a  
labor contract at America West, the nation's ninth-largest carrier. 
Pilots were first, followed by mechanics and dispatchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight attendants with 10 to 16 years' experience will see their  
annual pay increase from about $25,000 to $32,200 effective 
Saturday. After 3 1/2 years, that would increase to $33,800. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning Aug. 1, flight attendants will receive for the first  
time a per diem, or daily allowance, of $1.30 per hour for all 
hours spent away from their home base. The rate would increase to 
$1.50 per hour after 2 1/2 years. 
</P>
<P>
	David Nary of Tempe, Ariz., an America West flight attendant for  
14 years, said he won't have to work overtime any longer to make 
ends meet. His hourly pay will jump from $24.41 to $35.80 under the 
new contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we can hold our heads up high. We fought for a contract  
and now we'll be treated as a major league airline, not a 
second-rate one,'' Nary said. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the contract process was wrapping up for the flight  
attendants, it's just getting starting for other America West 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Trotti, interim president for the union representing the  
airline's 2,200 baggage handlers, said the company expects to set 
dates for the start of contract negotiations within the next two 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Mediation Board on April 13 upheld the handlers'  
vote to join the Transport Workers Union. The airline had claimed 
the vote violated election secrecy rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn Engel, an analyst at Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., welcomed the  
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good news is that (America West) has no more contracts  
coming due for a while,'' Engel said. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots' contract expires in May 2000, but Engel said neither  
it nor the pending baggage handlers' negotiations were likely to 
present problems in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
