<HEADLINE> Skier Moran Out of Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) -- Former U.S. Olympic freestyle skier Jim  
Moran was released from a hospital today, two months after 
suffering a brain injury when he landed badly during a competition 
at Vail. 
</P>
<P>
	Moran, 26, was released from Craig Hospital and will live in the  
area with his mother and receive outpatient therapy, the hospital 
said in a news release. He hopes later to live in Page, Ariz., for 
a time and eventually return to Park City, Utah, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital said Moran has a ``terrific attitude'' and has made  
``significant progress'' since he was admitted to Craig in 
mid-March. He had been at nearby Swedish Medical Center since his 
accident at the U.S. Freeskiing Open Feb. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Moran is walking on his own even though his right arm and leg  
remain partially paralyzed, Craig spokesman Kenny Hosack said. But 
he still needs therapy for coordination and endurance. He also 
needs therapy for speech clarity and hoarseness, though he can 
speak. 
</P>
<P>
	Moran is beginning to manage his own affairs, Hosack said, but  
he still requires therapy for short-term memory, planning, 
problem-solving and ``other higher cognitive processes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moran left the U.S. team after finishing 23rd in the moguls  
competition in the Winter Games last year. He skied to two World 
Cup moguls victories, a 1993 event in Breckenridge and a 1996 
competition in Altenmarkt, Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	He has said he hopes to ski competitively again someday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
