<HEADLINE> Spandau Ballet Loses Royalties Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The High Court rejected a claim Friday by three  
former members of the pop group Spandau Ballet for hundreds of 
thousands of dollars in royalties from the band's former 
songwriter. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Sir Hugh Park said he found it ``unconscionable'' for  
singer Tony Hadley, drummer John Keeble and sax player Steve Norman 
to claim large sums in royalties from Gary Kemp for songs he had 
written. 
</P>
<P>
	The three argued they were entitled to a share of Kemp's  
earnings from the publishing rights to the band's string of 1980s 
hits, including ``True'' and ``Gold.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They said they had a verbal agreement with Kemp that they would  
each receive one-twelfth of all the royalties from the songs. 
</P>
<P>
	All three have struggled to build successful careers since the  
band folded while Kemp and his brother, Martin, the group's bass 
player, have become successful actors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
