<HEADLINE> Bus of Deaf Children Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRAIDWOOD, Ill. (AP) -- A bus carrying deaf children to a  
spelling bee flipped over on Interstate 55 today, killing one man 
and injuring 23 people, one critically. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus was carrying deaf schoolchildren from the John Powers  
Center in Vernon Hills, a Chicago suburb, to the gathering in 
downstate East Peoria when it crashed at about 7 a.m. near 
Braidwood, about 50 miles southwest of Chicago, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The southbound bus had drifted into the center median and was  
clipped by a northbound car while the bus' driver was trying to get 
back into the southbound lanes, according to Wilmington Police 
Chief Jim Metta. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus appears to have flipped over more than once before  
coming to rest in a ditch, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the approximately seven adults on the bus were pinned  
underneath it, and one of the two was killed, he said. The man was 
the father of a girl on the bus. 
</P>
<P>
	At Provena Saint Joseph Medical Center in Joliet, 31-year-old  
man was in critical condition and three adults were in serious 
condition, a hospital spokeswoman said. Three others -- two children 
and an adult -- at Provena were in good condition, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen others were taken to three other hospitals. None of  
their injuries were considered life-threatening, according to 
hospital spokeswomen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
