<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reliever Slocumb Released by Orioles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles released reliever  
Heathcliff Slocumb on Friday, less than 24 hours after he yielded 
seven runs in one inning and walked off the mound with a 12.46 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	Slocumb, who signed with Baltimore as a free agent in January,  
allowed 12 earned runs in 10 appearances. He had not given up a run 
in four straight outings before Kansas City homered twice in a 
seven-run ninth inning Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like I had a bad game last night. Other than that I  
thought I was throwing fine,'' Slocumb said. ``It's definitely a 
surprise to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents were batting .395 against Slocumb, who never showed  
the form he displayed while compiling a 2.08 ERA in spring 
training. The Orioles are responsible for his entire $1.1 million 
salary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got some good guys going in the minors, and I figure  
it's time to go with some youth,'' Orioles manager Ray Miller said. 
``Maybe a breath of fresh air will do us some good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Slocumb, 32, has pitched in 434 major league games since making  
his debut with the Chicago Cubs in 1991. He came to Baltimore after 
spending 1 1/2 years with the Seattle Mariners. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I had a pretty decent spring,'' he said. ``The only  
thing anybody can ask for is opportunity. I felt like I was going 
to get that, with this being a pretty successful organization. 
Obviously it didn't happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles filled the void by calling up right-handed reliever  
Gabe Molina, who had four saves and a 0.00 in nine games with 
Triple-A Rochester. Molina, 23, has never pitched in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want to bring up some young kids that's fine by me,''  
Slocumb said. 
</P>
<P>
	Slocumb was only part of the reason why the Orioles entered  
Friday night's game against Minnesota with a major league high 6.76 
ERA 
</P>
<P>
	``I made a point of telling him I wasn't blaming him,'' Miller  
said. ``We've got to do something. We're scoring almost five runs a 
game and giving up seven. It doesn't take a genius to know why 
we're 5-16.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Slocumb: ``I know the nature of the game and I know there  
is a lot of pressure on this organization to be successful. Whether 
I thought things were done fairly or unfairly is irrelevant.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 01:43:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Attorneys Spar in Cable Car Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A videotape made during a Marine jet  
training mission that resulted in the deaths of 20 people at an 
Italian ski resort would have provided irrefutable evidence about 
the flight before the accident, a Navy investigator testified. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigator, Mark Fallon, also said Thursday that he  
considered his work a criminal investigation from the day it 
started -- one day after the Feb. 3, 1998, accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The date is important because prosecutors say Capt. Richard  
Ashby, 32, should have known an inquiry was under way when he 
helped get rid of the video a few days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby, of Mission Viejo, Calif., is accused of obstruction of  
justice for allegedly tampering with the tape. He could be 
sentenced to 10 years in prison or dismissed from the service if 
convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	A separate jury acquitted him of 20 counts of involuntary  
manslaughter stemming from the tragedy near Cavalese, Italy, when a 
gondola plunged to the ground after a support cable was cut by 
Ashby's jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby has admitted taking the tape from the jet, leaving a blank  
one in its place and later giving it to his navigator, Capt. Joseph 
Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y. But he maintains he did not 
intend to obstruct justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer pleaded guilty to obstruction of justice and  
conspiracy and was sentenced to dismissal from the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, a firefighter testified that after the jet  
landed, Ashby tried twice to get into the cockpit of the EA-6B 
Prowler ``to get a map and some other equipment.'' Master Sgt. 
Richard Henry said he denied Ashby access both times because of 
safety concerns. The crippled jet was leaking hydraulic fluid and 
its right wing was nearly sheared off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 10:59:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Matches Iraq Air War Duration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Now in its 38th day, NATO's air war in  
Yugoslavia has lasted as long as the U.S.-led air campaign in the 
1991 Gulf War, which on Day 39 added a ground attack to kick Iraq 
out of Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	On Day 38 of Operation Allied Force -- designed to compel  
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to give up his grip on Kosovo 
-- the bombs kept falling with little sign that Milosevic was near 
the breaking point. NATO warplanes today struck Yugoslav army 
headquarters and the interior ministry in Belgrade in what alliance 
officials called the strongest attack so far on the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no consensus in NATO for committing ground troops, and,  
some say, no political will to go all out. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're setting it out piecemeal,'' said retired Gen. Michael  
Dugan, who was Air Force chief of staff when the Iraqis invaded 
Kuwait in August 1990. He said in an interview Thursday that he saw 
signs of a toughening in NATO's approach, including the decision to 
send more B-52 bombers into the fight. 
</P>
<P>
	At this stage of the U.S.-led air war against Iraq, there was  
little doubt about the outcome. The allies had wrecked Iraqi air 
defenses and destroyed an estimated one-third of his armor in 
Kuwait. Hundreds of Iraqi soldiers already had been taken prisoner 
and those that remained in Kuwait were desperate. 
</P>
<P>
	When President Bush gave Iraqi President Saddam Hussein a  
deadline of Feb. 23 to give up Kuwait or face a U.S.-led land 
invasion, there were about 700,000 allied troops -- including 
520,000 Americans -- poised on the Saudi Arabian border to barrel 
across desert sand berms into Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Balkans, by contrast, NATO has fewer than 20,000 soldiers  
on the ground, and most of them are occupied with housing refugees 
in Albania and Macedonia. What's more, NATO says it has not even 
begun to develop a battle plan for ground troops; it insists that a 
land campaign will not be needed. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 38 days of the air war against Iraq, 46 Americans  
were killed in action. Thus far in the current conflict, not a 
single U.S. or allied troop has been reported killed, either in 
combat or in accidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Comparisons between the air campaigns against Iraq and  
Yugoslavia are limited in many respects, although many military 
analysts use the Gulf War example in criticizing NATO for not using 
overwhelming force. By Day 38 in the Gulf, the allies had flown 
about 90,000 missions, compared with 12,000 so far in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	It might also be said, however, that the United States is still  
fighting the air war in Iraq. American and British planes carried 
out a four-day bombing campaign in Iraq last December, and since 
then have been bombing air defense targets in northern and southern 
Iraq with almost daily regularity. 
</P>
<P>
	On Day 38 of the U.S.-led air war against Iraq, U.S. officials  
announced that allied bombing had destroyed 39 percent of Iraqi 
tanks in Kuwait, 32 percent of all armored vehicles and 48 percent 
of artillery. Once the ground troops stormed into Kuwait, the 
Iraqis were ready to quit within 100 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	So far in Kosovo, by NATO's estimate, the Serbs have lost no  
more than 15 percent of their tanks, although the efficiency of 
attacks on armor is likely to improve once the Army puts its Apache 
attack helicopters into action. Defense Secretary William Cohen 
said Thursday the Apache crews have ``some more training to do'' 
before the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, will send them into 
combat. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen and other U.S. officials are quick to point out the  
differences between Yugoslavia and the Gulf War. One is that 
bombing is more difficult in the Balkans, where frequent low cloud 
cover makes it difficult to target from high altitude. The Iraqis 
were mostly exposed in the open desert, whereas the Serbs have 
hills and forest to hide their armor and air defense systems. There 
also are more civilians to keep out of the line of fire in Serbia, 
where many military and communications targets are near civilian 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers comparison also is somewhat misleading. The allies  
were flying as many as 2,900 missions a day in Iraq, compared with 
600 on a big day in Yugoslavia. While there is no question that the 
air campaign in Iraq was more intense, technological advances since 
1991 have enabled NATO planes to hit more targets in Yugoslavia 
with fewer total bombs than was true during the Gulf War. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 9 percent of bombs used in the Gulf were of the  
precision-guided variety, compared with more than 90 percent in the 
current campaign, according to Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of 
the Joint Chiefs of Staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 10:59:15 </DATE_TIME>
