<DOCNO> APW19990430.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 11:05:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Economy Cuts 3M Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAPLEWOOD, Minn. (AP) -- 3M reported a 4 percent drop in  
first-quarter earnings due to the weak Brazilian economy and a 
strong dollar overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maplewood-based maker of Scotch brand tape, scouring pads  
and other consumer, industrial and electronics products, said 
Friday it earned $384 million, or 95 cents per share, compared with 
$400 million, or 98 cents a share, a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	That was above Wall Street's expectations. Analysts surveyed by  
First Call Corp. expected earnings of 91 cents a share for 
Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter sales rose 2 percent to $3.78 billion from $3.70  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Results benefited from an improvement in sales in the  
Asia-Pacific area, healthy productivity gains and solid growth in 
several of our U.S. businesses, but were negatively affected by the 
Brazilian economic situation and continued strengthening of the 
U.S. dollar,'' said L.D. DeSimone, chairman and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Changes in currency exchange rates reduced earnings by an  
estimated 2 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	DeSimone said the company is on schedule with its restructuring  
activities, which involve reductions in corporate structure, 
consolidation of manufacturing operations and withdrawal from 
low-return and non-core product lines. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
