<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Govt Takes Low Profile in Cuba Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- State Department officials view Monday's  
rematch between the Baltimore Orioles and Cuba as a ``significant 
people-to-people event'' and say it will have little impact on 
relations with Fidel Castro's government. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the game Baltimore won 3-2 in extra innings in Havana a  
month ago, the Cuban president will not be in the stands. Neither 
will President Clinton, or any other high U.S. official. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department isn't talking much about the game with the  
Cuban all-stars, except to acknowledge that a few of its employees 
might show up -- if they buy their own tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Clinton administration official briefed reporters  
Friday on the nearly sold-out game, but said his name couldn't be 
used. ``We're not in the position of encouraging defection; we're 
not in the position of discouraging defection,'' he said when asked 
about the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	He said no special measures were being taken to deal with any  
defectors but added that Immigration and Naturalization Service 
personnel would likely be at the game. There is also no indication 
the Cubans will be bringing along security personnel to deflect any 
defectors, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cuban team is expected to arrive on two chartered planes wit  
a total of about 300 people -- roughly the same number of Americans 
in the Orioles entourage to Cuba. Traveling with the team will be 
Cuban journalists, retired players and students. 
</P>
<P>
	The top Cuban official at the game is expected to be Jose  
Fernandez, head of the Cuban Olympic Committee. Fernandez also 
attended the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
