<DOCNO> APW19990430.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 07:55:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deputy Had Been Watching Harris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The sheriff's deputy stationed at Columbine High  
School had been keeping an eye on gunman Eric Harris for about a 
year before last week's massacre, officials confirmed today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Denver Rocky Mountain News reported today that Neil Gardner,  
the sheriff's deputy stationed at Columbine, received a report in 
March 1998 that Harris was detonating pipe bombs and talked of 
committing mass murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper obtained a copy of a ``suspicious incident''  
police report sent to Gardner. It was based on information that 
Columbine parent Randy Brown filed with the sheriff's office on 
March 18, 1998. It included printouts of Harris' Internet warnings 
that he was ready to kill. 
</P>
<P>
	``God, I can't wait until I can kill you people'' read one of  
the postings contained in report. ``I'll just go to some downtown 
area in some big (expletive) city and blow up and shoot everything 
I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner was at Columbine April 20 when Harris and Dylan Klebold  
attacked the school with bombs and assault weapons. Gardner 
exchanged fire with one of the gunmen. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis confirmed that Gardner  
``had been watching Eric for quite some time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Gardner had been keeping an eye on Harris at school,  
observing his actions and noting his associates. But, without proof 
of a chargeable offense, there was nothing that he could do, Davis 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff's Sgt. Jim Parr told the News: ``It was sent to him, and  
he was aware of it, and nothing came of it. There was simply 
nothing else we could do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives have traced guns used in the Columbine High School  
massacre, seized dozens of bombs and recovered dramatic video 
evidence of the nightmare inside. 
</P>
<P>
	But 11 days after the attack, the only person who has been  
arrested is a hardware store clerk accused of concocting a story 
about selling the gunmen material used in their bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators had hoped for more as they seek evidence that  
others helped Harris and Klebold plot their April 20 assault on the 
Littleton school. The gunmen killed 12 students and a teacher 
before committing suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials were questioning a man who may have supplied the  
semiautomatic pistol used by one of the young attackers. But 
authorities said no arrests were imminent -- a sharp about-face from 
earlier suggestions that the man would be arrested ``in a day or 
two'' after negotiating terms of his surrender. 
</P>
<P>
	Others have been questioned, but prosecutor Mark Pautler  
declined to label them as suspects. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not a good idea to let people know ahead of time that we  
are going to arrest them,'' he said Thursday. ``They have a 
tendency to disappear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agents from the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms  
earlier this week visited the Blackjack Pizza shop where Harris, 
18, and Klebold, 17, worked. The agents were investigating whether 
a pizza deliveryman acted as a middleman between the students and 
the gun seller. The ATF and pizza shop managers declined to discuss 
the inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Crime laboratory technicians are conducting ballistics tests to  
determine which guns fired the ammunition that killed each of the 
13 victims. If bullets fired by the paramilitary-style TEC DC-9 did 
not hit anyone, the gun seller may only face charges of illegal gun 
peddling rather than being implicated in the murders. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said Klebold's prom date, Robyn Anderson, 18,  
bought three of the four weapons -- two rifles and a shotgun -- used 
in the massacre. Authorities insist she, too, is only a witness. 
Under Colorado law, an 18-year old without a felony record can 
legally furnish minors with rifles and shotguns. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Anderson has made no public comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said they have not formally interviewed the  
killers' parents, blaming scheduling problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are trying to set it up now,'' Pautler told The Washington  
Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Thursday, Thornton gun dealer Larry Russell told the  
News that he sold the semiautomatic pistol used in the shootings to 
an unidentified adult last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell says the TEC-DC-9 was one of several he bought from gun  
dealer Royce Spain when Spain's Federal Heights gun shop closed. 
Russell said he sold the gun at a Tanner Gun Show at the Denver 
Merchandise Mart last year. But he didn't keep a record of the sale 
and isn't sure when he sold it, or who bought it. He said he would 
have asked for identification and is sure the buyer was not a 
minor. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell said he has seen pictures of gunmen Harris and Klebold,  
and did not recognize them. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Sheriff John Stone said investigators who examined  
inventory records and receipts at a hardware store have concluded 
that Gary Sowell, 50, lied about selling the youths propane tanks, 
wire, screws and other materials used to make the bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sowell was charged Thursday with making a false report to  
authorities, a misdemeanor, and booked in the Jefferson County jail 
on $1,000 bond. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe this will slow down some of these crackpot calls that  
we're getting,'' Stone said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, heartbroken residents held the last of the funerals  
for massacre victims, a gospel-infused memorial to 18-year-old 
Isaiah Shoels. 
</P>
<P>
	Choir singers raised their hands skyward while belting out  
joyous praise. In between hymns, speakers mixed fond memories of 
the 4-foot-11 football player -- described as ``small in stature but 
large in heart'' -- with calls for societal change. 
</P>
<P>
	``When does this stop? When does it end?'' asked William  
Collins, Isaiah's grandfather. ``I'm tired of laying to rest 
politicians, engineers, athletes, musicians, artists, janitors and 
sanitation haulers who are robbed of reaching their potential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shoels' father, Michael, said his son ``had two strikes against  
him'' in the minds of the gunmen: He was an athlete and he was 
black. Students said the gunmen were seeking athletes and singled 
Shoels out because of his race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 21:52:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Media Wins in Mich. Riot Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Eleven newspapers and television stations  
don't have to give prosecutors unpublished photographs and video of 
a campus riot that prosecutors want for their investigation, the 
Michigan Supreme Court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said the wrong kind of subpoena was used, and sent the  
case back to District Court so prosecutors could request a type of 
subpoena known as an investigative subpoena. 
</P>
<P>
	But even if prosecutors make that request, it is unlikely the  
case would go very far. A Circuit Court judge has already forbidden 
the use of investigative subpoenas in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Stuart Dunnings III was unavailable for comment  
Friday, an assistant prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunnings sought hundreds of unpublished photographs and video  
footage taken the night of March 27, when more than 5,000 people 
rioted on the Michigan State University campus and in downtown East 
Lansing. The riots began in the final moments of the NCAA semifinal 
game in which Michigan State lost to Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	Herschel Fink, an attorney for the Detroit Free Press, said they  
were pleased with the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The news outlets contend that turning over unpublished photos  
and video would compromise their ability to gather the news. Fink 
has said that such orders place reporters in jeopardy by forcing 
them to act as agents of the police. 
</P>
<P>
	Two lower court judges have ruled the materials aren't protected  
because the riot was filmed in a public place and media laws are 
only meant to protect confidential sources. The judges have also 
ruled that people filming the riot were witnesses to crimes and are 
therefore compelled to give evidence to prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Free Press, media involved in the case are  
the Lansing State Journal, The State News -- Michigan State's 
student newspaper -- and eight TV stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0194 </DOCNO>
