<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celtics' Minor Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Boston Celtics forward Greg Minor will miss the  
rest of the season because of a hairline fracture in his right hip, 
the team announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-6 swingman was injured during Thursday's game at  
Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Initial X-rays in Miami were inconclusive, but further tests in  
Boston revealed the fracture in the socket of Minor's right hip, 
said Celtics spokesman Jeff Twiss. 
</P>
<P>
	Minor, who averaged 4.9 points and 2.7 rebounds in 44 games this  
season, fell while running downcourt early in the first quarter in 
the Celtics' 107-96 victory. He was screaming in pain and had to be 
helped off the court by teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	The fracture could take three to five weeks to heal, but will  
not require surgery, Twiss said. 
</P>
<P>
	Minor was hospitalized at New England Baptist Hospital in  
Boston. He could be released over the next few days, Twiss said. 
</P>
<P>
	Minor, a first-round draft pick of the Los Angeles Clippers out  
of Louisville in 1994, is in his fifth season with the Celtics, who 
signed him as a free agent before the 1994-95 season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 07:15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Auction Team Backs Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Scratch ``team of high-priced,  
professionally-trained cybergeeks'' off your Internet shopping 
list. 
</P>
<P>
	The group of 16 managers and engineers who offered their  
services for $3.14 million on an online auction house has backed 
out. The team pulled its posting without explanation Thursday from 
eBay, the Web's largest bidding site. 
</P>
<P>
	``The seller ended the auction. He did not give a reason when we  
talked to him,'' said eBay spokesman Kevin Pursglove. ``They didn't 
explain anything. We have no idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The posting had three or four bids before it was pulled, he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The group members, who declined to identify themselves for fear  
of getting fired, sparked interest with its posting on eBay, which 
usually auctions off things like autographed baseballs and Beanie 
Babies. 
</P>
<P>
	The 16 workers -- including a director, two managers, three  
engineers and five administrators -- claim they currently work, 
unhappily, for a Silicon Valley company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were just sitting around talking, watching our company  
disintegrate and watching all these great people leaving,'' said a 
spokesman for the group calling itself ``ispteam.'' They had been 
working together for years, and hated the idea of splitting up. 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman could not be reached for comment Thursday.  



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 09:25:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consolidation Loans Aren't for All / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- You probably have seen a television  
ad with the theme: A happy couple in a beautiful home smiling as 
bright as the sunbeams streaming in the windows. 
</P>
<P>
	All their bills have been crammed into one through debt  
consolidation and they're saving hundreds of dollars a month. 
</P>
<P>
	But credit counselors say financial doom could dim the bright  
picture if the happy couple hasn't learned to manage money. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've just wrapped it up in a neat little package; they  
still owe the money,'' said Gail M. Merrill, education director at 
Consumer Credit Counseling Services of Maine Inc. in South 
Portland, which provides financial counseling services throughout 
the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate over the best way to deal with debt is heating up  
around the country. Opponents of consolidation contend that tying 
unsecured debt to collateral like one's home is not the best option 
for those who can't rein in their spending. 
</P>
<P>
	The nonprofit National Foundation for Consumer Credit of Silver  
Spring, Md., which runs a national network of 1,500 Consumer Credit 
Counseling Services offices, has already been airing ads against 
consolidation in Maine and plans to start a nationwide campaign in 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	With personal debt high and personal bankruptcies at a record  
1.4 million filings last year, lending companies have been jumping 
at the opportunity to consolidate various debts into one payment. 
The loan companies buy unsecured debt, like money owed to credit 
card companies, and replace it with one loan payment. They make 
their money from the interest on the loan, and have the collateral 
of the house if the borrower isn't able to come through with the 
loan payments. 
</P>
<P>
	But Merrill says many consolidation loans do little to tackle  
the underlying problem of overspending. 
</P>
<P>
	Counselors with the National Foundation for Consumer Credit, who  
helped 1.5 million people last year, work with creditors to set up 
debt repayment plans, which may include waived fees, interest and 
penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Clients deposit money each month with the counseling service,  
which pays the creditors. The rules usually require clients to cut 
up their credit cards and refrain from applying for new plastic. 
</P>
<P>
	While debt repayment plans don't erase credit history, they can  
demonstrate that a client has learned to budget better. 
</P>
<P>
	However, lenders maintain debt consolidation could be the answer  
for certain borrowers, particularly homeowners or those who have 
equity in real estate, since property is often used as collateral. 
It can be a good idea for those who already know how to manage 
money and are looking for lower interest on debts or for a tax 
advantage, they say. The interest paid on most home-equity loans is 
tax deductible. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Benson, a senior vice president at The Money Store in  
Sacramento, Calif., says his clients are either looking for lower 
rates, are tired of paying on several credit cards or have suffered 
a financial setback due to job loss, a medical problem, or divorce. 
</P>
<P>
	Benson says loan rates, which depend on borrowers' credit  
history and income, range from around 8 percent to 13 percent. 
That's lower than average credit card rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Vernita and Leonard Cox of Los Angeles took out a consolidation  
loan at 10.5 percent from The Money Store in 1997 and were so happy 
they recommended that Mrs. Cox's mother do the same. They also 
agreed to appear in a commercial that aired in November. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were just too many itty-bitty bills. That can drive you  
crazy,'' said Mrs. Cox, a business owner. ``We were able to 
refinance, pay off some of the credit cards and basically just get 
right back starting all over again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission warns that some lenders may pack  
hidden fees and extra costs into contracts, encourage people to pad 
their incomes to qualify or try to persuade applicants to 
repeatedly refinance loans. Victims of such practices may end up 
losing their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill says its important for consumers to be aware of their  
options -- and to be sure to read the fine print. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't be afraid to ask the same question over and over again  
until you get the answer you're looking for,'' she said. ``People 
in banking and finance tend to use their lingo, leaving the rest of 
us in the dust.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:24:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stroh Brewery Completes Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Stroh Brewery Co. has completed the sale of all  
of its brands to Miller Brewing Co. and Pabst Brewing Co., ending a 
century and a half of beer-making after tough competition and a 
trend toward consolidation hurt its sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, the nation's second-largest brewer behind Anheuser-Busch  
Inc., agreed to buy Stroh's Henry Weinhard's and Mickeys brands. 
</P>
<P>
	Pabst agreed to buy the rest of Stroh's brands, including  
Stroh's, Old Milwaukee and Schlitz. It also is buying Stroh's 
brewery in Lehigh Valley, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Stroh said it would continue to operate its five remaining  
breweries until production can be shifted to Miller or Pabst. All 
hourly and more than 75 percent of salaried workers will keep their 
jobs during the transition, expected to last until the end of the 
year, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stroh Brewery has about 1,900 hourly and 765 salaried employees.  
</P>
<P>
	The companies have not disclosed complete terms of the deals,  
though Pabst said it borrowed $185 million to pay for it. The 
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel estimated the two deals at $400 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Stroh began brewing in Detroit in 1850, after the family already  
had been brewing for two generations in Germany. During Prohibition 
the company made products ranging from ice cream and soda to the 
ingredients necessary for home brewing. 
</P>
<P>
	Beer industry analysts say the move reflects a trend toward  
consolidation made necessary because the top companies carry so 
much weight. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
