<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Baseball Defections Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rey Ordonez scaled a 15-foot fence in Buffalo, N.Y. Rolando  
Arrojo slipped into a waiting car in Georgia. Livan Hernandez 
sneaked out of a hotel in Mexico. Orlando Hernandez simply floated 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	And three others made their break on a cold, dark night in a  
cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, about 30 Cuban baseball players have defected in the  
last 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	So, it's no surprise that the big question in Baltimore is not  
who will win Monday night's exhibition between the Orioles and 
Cuban all-star team. Instead, it's this: How many of the 25 Cuban 
players will be heading back to Havana after the game at Camden 
Yards? 
</P>
<P>
	Agent Joe Cubas has helped several star players defect in the  
past, and has already said he plans to be in Baltimore this weekend 
with the same intent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans kept their roster secret going into the weekend,  
along with the logistics of their visit. Several key players who 
did not take part in the Orioles' 3-2 win in Havana on March 28 
might be on this team, including flashy shortstop German Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
	Mesa was the starting shortstop on the Havana Industriales when  
Ordonez was a backup. Ordonez later defected and became a Gold 
Glover with the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	A look at some of the high-profile defections:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Ordonez. He was 20 when he left the Cuban team at the 1993  
World University Games in Buffalo. He left the athlete's village, 
climbed a fence and got into a friend's Cadillac before flying 
first-class to Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Arrojo. Following a plan set up by Cubas, the pitcher got a  
late-night knock on his hotel door in Albany, Ga., where the Cuban 
Olympic team was preparing for the 1996 Summer Olympics. Cubas was 
in a car across the street and flashed its lights. Arrojo jumped in 
and they drove away. He now plays for Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Livan Hernandez. Without telling anyone, he walked out of a  
hotel in Monterrey, Mexico, where the Cuban national team was 
training in 1995. The future World Series MVP for the Florida 
Marlins headed to the airport and took a flight to Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Orlando Hernandez. In a daring escape a day after Christmas  
1997, El Duque and seven others left on a small boat from Cuba and 
were picked up a few days later on an island in the Bahamas by the 
U.S. Coast Guard. Hernandez later joined the New York Yankees and 
helped them win the 1998 World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Rene Arocha. Began the influx of top Cuban defectors in 1991  
when he walked away at the Miami airport, right before a flight 
home. A day earlier, the pitcher had met his father for the first 
time since he defected 12 years earlier. Arocha was 18-17 for St. 
Louis and San Francisco from 1993-97. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Osvaldo Fernandez. Slipped away in 1995 before the Cuban  
national team played a game in Millington, Tenn. The pitcher 
traveled to Miami to watch Arocha and the Cardinals, and later 
signed with San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Roberto Colina. In 1996, he defected with two other players  
during a tournament in Mexico. They walked out of their hotel and 
met Cubas late at night in a graveyard. Colina is a first baseman 
in Tampa Bay's minor league system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:34:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Silverbulletday Wins Kentucky Oaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- ``The move'' worked again for  
Silverbulletday. 
</P>
<P>
	Going three wide on the turn for home, Bob Baffert's super filly  
cruised to an easy two-length victory over Dreams Gallore TODAY in 
the Kentucky Oaks. Silverbulletday won her seventh straight and 
10th in 11 career starts. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1-9 favorite rewarded the confidence of an Oaks-record crowd  
of 101,034 by going 1 1/8 miles in 1:49 4/5. Her easy victory will 
only encourage speculation that she is the class of this year's 
crop of 3-year-olds, Saturday's Kentucky Derby result 
notwithstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Owner Mike Pegram won the Derby last year with the  
Baffert-trained Real Quiet and had said he didn't want 
Silverbulletday in the crowded Derby, which expects 19 starters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason she wasn't in the Kentucky Derby is we want to take  
care of her and today she showed she wants to take care of us,'' 
Pegram said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the second race in a row, Silverbulletday won with a  
three-wide surge, the same that won her the Ashland Stakes at 
Keeneland earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Gary Stevens kept Silverbulletday wide and out of trouble  
around the first turn and along the backstretch, waiting to make 
his move. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt more pressure today than I probably felt in any horse  
race in 20 years,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As the pack compressed toward the rail around the second turn,  
Stevens urged Silverbulletday forward, and she responded, passing 
Marley Vale and Sweeping Story. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like riding a turbo-horse,'' the jockey said.  
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday earned $341,620 and gave Baffert, who will have  
three horses in Saturday's Kentucky Derby, a shot at a rare 
Derby-Oaks double. 
</P>
<P>
	The last trainer to win both races in the same year was Ben A.  
Jones, who saddled winners Real Delight in the Oaks and Hill Gail 
in the Derby in 1952. Jones also turned the trick in 1949, with 
Ponder in the Derby and Wistful in the Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday paid $2.20, $2.20 and $2.10. Dreams Gallore paid  
$4.40 and $2.10 and the show horse, Sweeping Story, paid $2.10, 
finishing 6 3/4 lengths off the pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Happy Hopper was fourth, followed by Marley Vale, Positive  
Gal and Gold From The West. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday is now five-for-five lifetime at Churchill  
Downs, including a win last November in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile 
Fillies. Her only loss was last August in the Del Mar Debutante, 
when she finished fourth, 7 1/2 lengths behind stablemate Excellent 
Meeting, who'll start the Derby on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Friday, Silent Eskimo ($13.80) beat 1-2 favorite Lu Ravi  
by 1 1/4 lengths in the Louisville Breeders' Cup Handicap. Silent 
Eskimo covered 1 1-16 miles in 1:43 4-5 and earned $169,415 from 
the $268,250 purse. 
</P>
<P>
	Favored Howbaddouwantit ($6.40) caught the leaders in the middle  
of the stretch and went on to a one-length victory in the $115,300 
Turf Sprint Stakes. Mike Smith rode the 4-year-old over five 
furlongs in 57 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Rocket ($7.60), briefly blocked behind horses at the top of  
the stretch, got clear to win the $115,400 American Turf Stakes by 
a half-length over Haus of Dehere in a $115,400 turf race. Air 
Rocket ran 1 1-16 miles in 1:42 3-5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
