<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Horry May Be Forgotten No More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Robert Horry has been the forgotten man  
for the Los Angeles Lakers this season. 
</P>
<P>
	After what he did against the Portland Trail Blazers on Thursday  
night, that might change. 
</P>
<P>
	Horry made six 3-point shots and scored a season-high 22 points  
as the Lakers overpowered the Pacific Division-champion Blazers 
108-89. 
</P>
<P>
	``Robert Horry played a great game,'' said Lakers center  
Shaquille O'Neal, who wasn't bad himself, equaling a season-high 
with 38 points. ``That's the Robert Horry I know. He's been taking 
a lot of heat, a lot of criticism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So has the entire team, and it's difficult to say it hasn't been  
deserved. The Lakers had lost their previous two games, at San 
Antonio and Houston, by a total of 49 points. The win over Portland 
was just their third in nine games. 
</P>
<P>
	So after playing two of their worst games of the season, the  
Lakers played one of their best. Considering the playoffs are a 
week away, it couldn't have come at a better time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a total team effort,'' said Horry, who played 27  
minutes -- eight over his average. ``These last two days have been 
really good for us, we've been able to talk to each other and find 
out what's wrong with our defense and offense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the wake of their two one-sided losses in Texas, the Lakers  
spent nearly 2 1/2 hours behind closed doors Tuesday before taking the 
practice floor. They had what coach Kurt Rambis called their best 
practices of the year Tuesday and Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Horry, 28, played a prominent role on championship teams in  
Houston in 1994 and 1995, and made 71 starts and averaged over 31 
minutes of action for a Lakers' team that went 61-21 and reached 
the Western Conference finals last season. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a different story this year -- he's started only five  
games, and was held out of two games by Rambis midway through the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Horry's playing time diminished when the Lakers signed  
seven-time NBA rebounding champion Dennis Rodman in late February. 
It's been increasing since Rodman was waived two weeks ago, but 
J.R. Reid has been starting recently at power forward. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite what Horry did against the Blazers, some of them sounded  
unconvinced. 
</P>
<P>
	``How many times do you expect Horry to hit all those 3's? They  
just had a good night,'' Portland guard Isaiah Rider said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you've got Shaq going, there's pressure to defend him in  
the post and double-team him,'' Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy said. 
``And some of Robert's shots, I mean, it wasn't like they were even 
open looks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe not, but they went in.  
</P>
<P>
	Horry hadn't made more than two 3-point shots in a game this  
season, and entered the game having made 55 of his 123 attempts 
from 3-point range. He was 6-of-8 against the Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	``That first one felt good, the second one felt even better,  
that one I shot from way downtown felt even better,'' Horry said 
with a smile. ``Sometimes when you get that feeling, you have to 
keep shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the past, I tried to do the little things. Now, I figured,  
`Keep looking for your shot, stay on the outside, and keep looking 
for your shot, and try to make it easier for Shaq and the rest of 
the guys.' '' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
