<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:53:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Contract Advice Plentiful for James </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- A group forged by friendship and family will  
be advising first-round draft pick Edgerrin James as he wades 
through contract negotiations with the Indianapolis Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Team Edgerrin'' is in the process of selecting an agent to  
represent the fourth overall pick in upcoming contract talks aimed 
at providing financial security for the running back and his 
family. The team includes James, his half-brother Ed German, 
attorney Tyrone Williams and friend Pierre Rutledge. 
</P>
<P>
	James is the only first-round pick without an agent and he's  
been receiving heavy attention from those offering their services. 
</P>
<P>
	The collective bargaining agreement requires that a player  
either negotiate his own contract, a rare occurrence, or have 
someone certified by the NFL Players Association represent him. No 
member of James' team is certified by the NFLPA and there are no 
plans to have any of them become certified, Williams said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are in the process of interviewing some agents who have  
stepped forward recently,'' Williams said, adding that the fee the 
agent will receive is a part of the interview process. 
</P>
<P>
	``The average agent charges between 2 and 3 percent,'' said  
Williams, explaining that that fee usually is agreed to January and 
the agent provides services starting with the signing. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this case, the agent coming in is only going to have to  
negotiate the contract. Everything else has been done, so I feel 
based on that the fee arrangement should be quite different,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of dollars are involved. Last year's No. 4 pick was  
defensive back Charles Woodson, who reportedly signed a six-year 
deal worth $14.5 million with Oakland. Chicago signed Curtis Enis, 
who like James was the first running back selected in the draft, as 
the fifth overall selection and he reportedly signed a three-year 
contract worth $5.6 million with a $3.6 million signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pierre and I are not being paid for our roles, there's no  
compensation at all,'' Williams said. ``We're doing it because 
we're friends. We've all known each other. Pierre and I have been 
friends for 14-to-15 years. Everything in life isn't based on 
money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, money will certainly produce major changes in the lifestyle  
of James, who previously spent summers harvesting watermelons to 
raise money to assist a family that had to rely on food stamps to 
get by in the rural farming community of Immokalee, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	James passed up his senior year of college eligibility at Miami  
to help support his 22-month-old daughter and his mother, a high 
school cafeteria worker at Immokalee High School. His mother raised 
six sons on her own, never earning more than $17,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the money will change Edgerrin at all. If he was  
going to change, he had ample opportunity after he decided to turn 
pro. All the agents were coming after him with all the glamour, the 
glitz, offering trips, offering bizarre credit lines, cars and all 
those other toys that come with increased money,'' Williams said. 
``He has remained the same person and hasn't been lured into all 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said James is concentrating on preparing for his rookie  
season and plans to report to the Colts' complex on May 16 when he 
is allowed by league rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no timetable for reaching a contract agreement. I  
understand that is usually done in June or July before training 
camp begins,'' Williams said. ``We haven't discussed a timetable 
with the Colts and anticipate no problems.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
