<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat, Soybeans Advance; Corn Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat and soybean futures advanced Friday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while corn finished mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat and soybean futures early in the session were pressured by  
heavier-than-expected deliveries of supplies for the May contract -- 
a sign that farmers are settling for lower prices amid fears 
matters will become worse in the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But wheat later rose on marginal export demand and news the  
government made another large purchase for donation to needy 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans found some support on conflicting forecasts  
for weather next week in Midwest growing regions. The National 
Weather Service is calling for above-normal rainfall, which could 
delay farmer fieldwork. But some private forecasters are saying 
skies will remain clear at least through Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 4 1/2 cents to $2.68 a bushel; July  
corn was unchanged at $2.18 3/4 a bushel; July oats fell 1 1/4 cents to 
$1.18 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 2 cents to $4.86 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork bellies futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while lean hogs were mostly higher. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .07 cent to 62.82 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle fell .17 cent to 71.15 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .50 cent to 59.07 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .05 
cent to 59 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
