<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charge Dismissed in Carnival Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- A murder indictment was dismissed Friday  
against amusement company executives, workers and inspectors over 
the death of a girl who was thrown from a carnival ride. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said they needed more time to investigate, but the  
amusement company said the case never should have gotten so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought that the murder indictment was inappropriate from  
the very day it was issued,'' said Sam Bassett, who represents ride 
owners Robert Dale Merten Sr., his wife, Shara Merten, and their 
son Robert Merten II. 
</P>
<P>
	``We also have a strong opinion that nobody involved in the  
running of the carnival or the ride committed any crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The motion to dismiss came from prosecutors, and was granted by  
State District Judge Wilford Flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This additional investigation may very well lead to new and  
different charges being filed against new or different parties,'' 
District Attorney Ronnie Earle said. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment accused people connected with Yuma, Ariz.-based  
B&AMP;B Amusements and Florida-based inspection company Bob Gill and 
Associates of ``knowingly and intentionally'' causing 15-year-old 
Leslie Lane's death. 
</P>
<P>
	She was catapulted from the Himalaya ride in March 1998 at the  
Austin-Travis County Livestock Show and Rodeo, struck a wall and 
died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
