<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Boys Choir and Men's Chorale  
began a tour of Cuba on Friday with a visit to a school for young 
music students. 
</P>
<P>
	Principal Carmen Rosa Lopez welcomed the group of 87 boys and 25  
men at the Alejandro Garcia Caturla, a specialized public school 
for children with musical aptitude. The Americans arrived in Havana 
Thursday on an invitation by the Cuban Music Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Although other American performing groups have visited Havana,  
this is the first to actually tour the country since the 1959 
revolution brought Fidel Castro to power, choir spokesmen say. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- When kids play soccer in the streets of  
Mexico City, it could now be their parents who get hit by the 
penalty card. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a law approved Thursday by the municipal assembly, playing  
soccer on the street without neighbors' approval is punishable by a 
fine of up to $111 and up to 36 hours in jail, the newspaper 
Reforma reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Minors are spared punishment for their first soccer offense, but  
on a second foul the penalties could be applied to their parents or 
guardians. 
</P>
<P>
	Street soccer is an old tradition in this soccer-crazy nation,  
but it often irks residents whose windows are sometimes broken as a 
result. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Gunmen ambushed and killed the director of a  
prison near the Texas border as he headed to work, newspapers 
reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Paz Sanchez Garza, director of the La Loma prison in Nuevo  
Laredo, died in a hospital after being shot repeatedly Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The killing may be linked to drug trafficking, said Gilberto  
Garcia, commander of the Ministerial Police in Tamaulipas state, 
according to the newspaper Reforma. 
</P>
<P>
	Nuevo Laredo is across the border from Laredo, Texas.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- The former head of Brazil's Central  
Bank, arrested for refusing to testify under oath at a Senate probe 
about alleged irregularities, now says he will answer questions 
that don't incriminate him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate panel is investigating reports that some banks  
received insider information from a Central Bank source to reap 
profits from the January devaluation of the currency, the real, 
which took place during Francisco Lopes' 20-day stint heading the 
bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Francisco Lopes had appeared on Monday for questioning by the  
Senate panel, but he refused to sign a document committing him to 
tell the truth. He was immediately arrested, then released on bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Backed by a subsequent Supreme Court order saying he could not  
be forced to answer questions that could incriminate him, Lopes 
said, through his attorneys, he was willing to testify. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A military patrol seized a half ton of cocaine  
hidden in metal drums on a motor boat on the Ene River in Peru's 
Amazon jungle and detained five people on board, police said on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1,056 pounds of cocaine were found Sunday in the department  
of Junin, 200 miles east of Lima, on a rustic river boat headed to 
Brazil, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug bust was the second major cocaine seizure this year.  
Police in April seized 2.3 tons of cocaine hidden under frozen fish 
in a warehouse in Lima. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug traffickers are increasingly refining cocaine in Peru,  
instead of exporting it as cocaine paste, a semi-processed form of 
cocaine, as they had previously done, anti-drug officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Peru is one of the world's largest growers of the coca leaf used  
to make cocaine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
