<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 05:55:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seminole Mascot May Become Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Nearly 80,000 people in full war chant  
and spurred by the low beating of drums whoop and holler at the 
sight of Chief Osceola, adorned in war paint, as he rides forth on 
his appaloosa horse and throws a flaming spear into the ground, 
taunting the enemy. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the football game tradition of the Florida State University  
Seminoles, not a ritual of the Indians the army fought in Florida 
in the last century. 
</P>
<P>
	Some people want those images and the school's Seminoles  
nickname retired to history, saying they're insensitive to Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who want the traditions and Seminoles name to stay at  
Florida State have found an ally in FSU alumnus Jim King, who also 
happens to be a state senator from Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	King, a Republican, has proposed an amendment to a minor bill  
that names university buildings. The amendment would put into state 
law that FSU's teams are the Seminoles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's arrogant and disgraceful,'' said Suzan Shown Harjo,  
president of The Morning Star Institute, a Washington-based Indian 
rights group. 
</P>
<P>
	``The name Seminole is the name of the native nation of people  
still alive,'' she said. ``It's also stupid. If I started a 
university, it would never occur to me to call it the France or the 
French.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But those who want to keep the name have another ally: the  
Seminoles. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not offended, why should they be offended?'' asked Jim  
Shore, a Seminole and the lawyer for the 2,500 member tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	Shore said the tribe has no objections to the university using  
its name or other characterizations, even if they aren't always 
historically accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	King said he has recently spoken to the tribe's leader, Chairman  
James Billie, who told him the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``At what point does the chairman of the Seminole tribe get his  
way?'' King asked. ``His way is `I want to be identified, I want to 
be related.''' 
</P>
<P>
	King said Billie ``loves FSU.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Some people are comfortable with their own oppression,'' Harjo  
said. ``Osceola died because he stabbed a removal treaty and said 
`We're going nowhere' ... That's how strongly he felt about not 
compromising -- not being complicitous in his own oppression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to putting it in the law that FSU's sports teams are  
called the ``Seminoles,'' the amendment also makes the school's 
mascot legally ``Chief Osceola riding atop an appaloosa horse named 
`Renegade.''' It also puts the school colors of garnet and gold 
into statute. 
</P>
<P>
	If it becomes law, someone would have to go before the  
Legislature, which has several FSU graduates, to change the name. 
</P>
<P>
	King said he thinks the amendment will go through and the bill  
will pass. It is on a bill in the House, which is controlled by FSU 
grad John Thrasher. 
</P>
<P>
	Many college and professional teams have been pressured to  
change their Indian-related names and mascots. Protesters who find 
the Cleveland Indians' cartoonish ``Chief Wahoo'' logo offensive 
demonstrated outside the World Series in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Several groups are suing the NFL's Washington Redskins in an  
effort to force the team to change its name. 
</P>
<P>
	Some universities have changed nicknames in recent years. The  
Marquette Warriors became the Golden Eagles; Eastern Michigan 
dropped the Hurons and are now the Eagles; St. John's switched from 
the Redmen to the Red Storm and Miami University of Ohio went from 
the Redskins to the RedHawks. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana University of Pennsylvania reached a compromise of sorts  
by continuing to call its teams the Indians while adopting a new 
logo depicting a bear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
