<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawks Chase Title for Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Hawks don't want to get left behind  
by the other hometown teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The baseball Braves have a streak of seven straight playoff  
appearances, while the NFL Falcons made a stunning run to the Super 
Bowl in January. Now, the Hawks are in position for their first 
division title since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``The door is open for us,'' said Dikembe Mutombo, who has led  
the Hawks with 18-point, 18-rebound performances in each of the 
last two games. ``I don't want to let this pass me by.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks take a seven-game winning streak heading into  
tonight's critical contest against struggling Indiana, which leads 
the Central Division by a half-game after an overtime victory over 
Charlotte on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers were touted as an NBA title contender at the  
beginning of the season. With less than a week to go, they're 
simply trying to hold off Atlanta to win the division and capture 
at least a No. 2 seed in the Eastern Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're looking at a real confident team,'' Hawks forward Alan  
Henderson said. ``Management has done a great job putting this 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just a couple of weeks ago, the Hawks were a floundering team,  
closer to falling out of the playoffs than they were to gaining 
home-court advantage in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta had a four-game losing streak after a 91-84 defeat at  
Milwaukee on April 13, falling to sixth in the East. In the tightly 
bunched field, there was a possibility the Hawks could miss the 
playoffs for the first time in seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	Not anymore. The Hawks haven't lost since that Milwaukee game  
and hold a tiebreaker edge over the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks are a deeper team than past seasons, making several  
key moves to bolster their reserves. They re-signed Tyrone Corbin 
and brought in free agents Anthony Johnson and Grant Long. 
</P>
<P>
	Corbin, the starting small forward for two seasons, filled in  
capably at shooting guard when Steve Smith twice went to the 
injured list with ailing knees and former first-round pick Ed Gray 
floundered. 
</P>
<P>
	Long, who spent two years in purgatory at Detroit, has been very  
helpful at strong forward with Henderson experiencing an 
up-and-down season. The Hawks won the first six games on their 
streak with Henderson sidelined by a bruised tailbone. 
</P>
<P>
	The most surprising player is second-year forward Chris  
Crawford, who hardly played last season and didn't seem to have 
much of a future in Atlanta after the signing of LaPhonso Ellis. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis struggled to mesh with the offense, then was diagnosed  
with a hernia that ended his season after only 20 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Crawford, who averaged less than five minutes per game prior to  
Ellis' injury, has been a major presence during the winning streak, 
averaging 13.1 points. He has brought much-needed energy and 
athletic ability to the Hawks, whose three core players -- Mookie 
Blaylock, Smith and Mutombo -- are all over 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt if he got a year under his belt, he could develop into  
a good role player,'' coach Lenny Wilkens said. ``I didn't know it 
would mushroom like it has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their success, the Hawks are still a team saddled with  
glaring weaknesses and the burden of never getting past the second 
round of the playoffs since moving to Atlanta in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to win a championship,'' general manager Pete Babcock  
said. ``We're working hard to get to the point where we're a true 
contender. We haven't gotten past the second round. That's a fact 
of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blaylock has trouble beating most point guards off the dribble  
and is a major reason the Hawks rank next-to-last in assists. 
Smith, the team's leading scorer, is playing on gimpy knees. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta is averaging only 86.3 points -- more than eight points  
below the next-lowest figure in team history -- and Wilkens would 
love to have ``a drop-dead outside shooter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, in the post-Michael Jordan era, the Hawks are one of  
several teams that believe they can make a run at a championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hitting on all cylinders now,'' Crawford said. ``There's  
no doubt we can do some damage in the playoffs.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
