<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Date Set for Trial of Kurd Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey set a date Friday for the treason  
trial of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan, saying its case 
against the nation's No. 1 enemy would begin May 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Turgut Okyay ruled during a pre-trial hearing that only 90  
people, including lawyers, journalists and spectators, will be 
allowed to attend Ocalan's trial on charges of treason and 
separatism. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreigners will be banned from participating in any official way  
to prevent interference with Turkey's justice system, Okyay said. 
Ocalan has several foreign lawyers, and international human rights 
groups have already expressed concerns about whether he will get a 
fair trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lawyers (of Ocalan) are clearly impeded from preparing  
their defense,'' said Wesley Gryk, an American lawyer with Amnesty 
International. ``The defense has been seen as a symbol of the 
defendant and his crimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan's lawyers have long complained that they were not being  
allowed to confer with their client alone to prepare the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	During Friday's hearing, Ocalan's lawyers were often interrupted  
by relatives of soldiers and others who died during the 15 years of 
fighting between the Turkish army and Kurdish separatists in the 
southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives shouted obscenities, draped themselves in Turkish  
flags, and held pictures of loved ones who died in clashes with 
guerillas in Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK). 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Ocalan's lawyers were punched when they walked into the  
courthouse, prompting police to take the legal team downtown in 
armored cars after the hearing. But the lawyers said police punched 
and kicked them when they got out of the cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan, the sole inmate on the prison island of Imrali, is  
widely expected to get the death penalty if convicted. For security 
reasons, his trial will take place on the heavily guarded island in 
the Sea of Marmara. The island was emptied of inmates when Ocalan 
arrived following his capture in February by Turkish forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike standard, lengthy Turkish trials, which are often  
interrupted for months between sessions, Ocalan's trial will be 
carried out without interruption, the judge said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Ocalan is sentenced to death as expected, the far-right  
Nationalist Movement Party has said it will push parliament to 
approve the execution. Parliament has not given permission for an 
execution since 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	The party's campaign posters in the recent election depicted  
Ocalan as a devil devouring a child, and they contained the slogan, 
``Turkish nation made its decision: Execution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if he is hanged, my tears will never cease. I lost my  
son, my only son,'' said Sami Sulun, father of a commando, Hamza 
Ali, who was killed by Kurdish rebels four years ago at the age 21. 
</P>
<P>
	The government blames the PKK rebels for the deaths of more than  
9,800 civilians, soldiers, police officers and government-paid 
village guards. The rebel losses since 1984 stand at around 27,000 
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
