<HEADLINE> Thai Co., Dow Chemical Open Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Siam Polyethylene Co., a joint venture  
between Siam Cement and U.S.-based Dow Chemical, announced Friday 
that it has opened one of the world's largest polyethylene 
production plants in Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	Siam Polyethylene said the $100 million plant, located in  
Thailand's eastern seaboard industrial zone, has an annual capacity 
of 300,000 tons of polyethylene, an ingredient in plastics. 
</P>
<P>
	Output will be sold regionally, the company said.  
</P>
<P>
	The plant initially will produce low-density polyethylene  
resins, with Dow Chemical's trademark DOWLEX polyethylene coming 
into production toward the end of the year, it said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Siam Cement, Thailand's largest industrial conglomerate, and Dow  
Chemical have worked together for more than a decade, producing 
chemicals, plastics and related products. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are proud to open this world-scale polyethylene production  
facility, which is our first in the Asia-Pacific region,'' said Dow 
Chemical, which is headquartered in Midland, Mich. 

</P>
</TEXT>
