<DOCNO> APW19990430.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 17:12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Civil Rights Leader Meets U.S. POWs  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Three U.S. soldiers held prisoner by  
Yugoslavia today recounted their days of isolation to civil rights 
leader Jesse Jackson, their first public remarks since they were 
captured a month ago. ``Sorry I put you through so much pain and 
agony,'' one said in a message to his family. Jackson, who is 
expected to meet tomorrow with Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic, flew to Belgrade in an attempt to win their release. But 
Assistant Foreign Minister Nebojsa Vujovic said their release 
wasn't on the agenda. 

</P>
<P>
	US Says Yugoslavia Has Little Fuel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon said today Yugoslavia's troops  
are running dangerously low on fuel and other supplies and that 
President Slobodan Milosevic is on a course that will only lead to 
a ``dead end.'' Meanwhile, Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Michael 
Ryan said he had ``no reservations'' about NATO's air strategy, 
which some retired military officers have criticized as a form of 
gradualism akin to the approach the United States took in Vietnam, 
with disastrous results. He also defended the performance of Air 
Force crews and said they still face high risk from Serb air 
defenses. Nonetheless, he said, ``We're going to keep at it until 
they are completely disintegrated.'' 

</P>
<P>
	NRA Protesters Marching in Denver  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Students, gun-control groups and lawmakers have  
planned a day of protests tomorrow to tell the National Rifle 
Association it's not welcome. The group had scheduled its annual 
meeting in Denver for May 1, long before the Columbine High 
massacre. ``When a community is grieving and going through a 
mourning ... you shouldn't have a meeting that talks about selling 
more guns,'' Denver Mayor Wellington Webb said. But the NRA scaled 
back its meeting ``out of respect for the community.'' Fifteen 
people were killed during the April 20 rampage in Littleton, Colo, 
about 15 miles away. 

</P>
<P>
	London Explosion Kills Two  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Two people were killed and more than 70 were  
injured tonight when an explosion ripped through a crowded gay pub 
in central London. Authorities believe the blast was linked to two 
bombings in minority communities in the past two weeks. Gay 
businesses were put on alert after those attacks, and some victims 
in tonight's blast appeared to have nail wounds. The two previous 
bomb attacks have been claimed by an extreme right-wing group 
calling itself Combat 18. 

</P>
<P>
	Staid Finland Ready To Party  
</P>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Police today erected riot fences and  
first-aid workers were summoned to duty in Finland's capital in 
preparation for the nation's annual bacchanal, Vappu. Celebrated on 
May 1, Vappu is the holiday when masked Finns take to the streets 
with alcoholic beverages, defying their taciturn image. The name 
Vappu derives from St. Walpurgis, whose feast day is observed May 
1. The eve of the feast is considered a night when witches and evil 
spirits come out en masse. But it's also developed an ugly side 
marked by robberies, alcohol poisoning and public urination. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Spares Dogs, Banishes Them  
</P>
<P>
	FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) -- Two dogs were given stays of execution after  
they were sentenced to death for starting an ostrich stampede in 
which 12 birds were killed and another dozen went missing. Instead, 
Judge Stanley P. Klein banished Nikita, a Siberian husky and Max, a 
Doberman pinscher, from Virginia and bordering states. Jonathan 
Fouche, the ostrich breeder, said the ruling was fine. ``As long as 
they're going to be kept from doing it again,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Falls 89.34  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed on Wall Street today after  
analysts found data in the government's latest economic assessment 
that rekindled inflation fears. The Dow Jones industrial average 
closed down 89.34 at 10,789.04. Losers on the NYSE led gainers 
1,665-1,339. The Nasdaq was up 14.41 to 2,542.85. 

</P>
<P>
	Deal To Move Pats To Conn. Off  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The New England Patriots today nixed deal to move  
to Connecticut's capital because a stadium could not be built fast 
enough. Gov. John Rowland promised legal action against Patriots 
owner Robert Kraft and possibly the NFL as well. In December, Kraft 
signed a deal with Rowland to move the team after the state offered 
to build a $380 million stadium in Hartford. Under a plan designed 
to keep the Patriots in Massachusetts, the state would pay $70 
million for infrastructure supporting a new stadium in Foxboro, the 
team's current home. But Kraft would have to pay for the stadium. 
The announcement comes two days before Sunday's deadline for Kraft 
to back out of the deal with Connecticut without financial penalty. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
