<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 06:36:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  War Gives Albania Chance To Impress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIRANA, Albania (AP) -- A Balkan war that is bedeviling almost  
every participant is likely to produce at least one surprising and 
clear-cut winner: tiny, impoverished and long-neglected Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	For decades after World War II, Albania was closed off from the  
outside world, a Stalinist enclave so primitive and isolated that 
it scarcely seemed part of its continent. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, in the full glare of the international media spotlight,  
Albania plays earnest host to more than 370,000 Kosovo refugees and 
welcomes NATO troops by the thousands to wage war on Yugoslavia. 
The new national motto seems to be: Come On In. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of begrudging the throngs of refugees, or griping over  
NATO pushiness, Albanians are rolling out as much of a red carpet 
as possible in a country where most roads are riddled with potholes 
and most buildings are in disrepair. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a saying that every bad thing has a good side,'' said  
Information Minister Musa Ulqini. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen the terrible images of what has happened in Kosovo,  
and it's difficult for us as a poor country to take in so many 
refugees,'' he said in an interview. ``But it has positive aspects 
-- Albania has showed the world its good side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under Communist dictator Enver Hoxha, Albanians couldn't show  
the world much of anything. Few foreigners were allowed in, and few 
Albanians allowed out as the country wallowed in state-controlled 
backwardness. 
</P>
<P>
	Communist rule ended in 1991, but Albania's image problems  
persisted. 
</P>
<P>
	Riots erupted in March 1997 as thousands of Albanians lost their  
life savings in the collapse of pyramid investment schemes. 
Government facilities were looted; an estimated 800,000 automatic 
weapons and 1 billion rounds of ammunition were snatched from 
security-force warehouses. 
</P>
<P>
	More riots broke out in the capital of Tirana last year after a  
popular opposition leader was assassinated. 
</P>
<P>
	Crime, corruption and tax evasion remain rampant, but the  
country has suddenly found a keen sense of national purpose because 
of the forced expulsion of the ethnic Albanian majority from 
Yugoslavia's Kosovo province. There has been minimal bickering over 
the government's pivotal decisions -- to allow an unchecked influx 
of refugees and give NATO free rein to use Albania as a staging 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	``Albania's politics is usually not unified,'' said Remzi Lani,  
a political analyst in Tirana. ``On this, support is 100 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A vast military and relief operation is unfolding. Some 100  
planes a day are landing at Tirana's modest airport, and activity 
has more than doubled at Durres, the main port. 
</P>
<P>
	The refugees -- equal to about one-eighth of Albania's 3-million  
population -- are being accommodated in some 200 camps, as well as 
in thousands of private homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of us in government expected Albanians would do what they  
did,'' Ulqini said of the remarkable hospitality. ``In the first 10 
days, while we were trying to make the international community 
aware, no one died of hunger or lack of medicine. It makes me very 
proud to be an Albanian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albanian leaders stress that their decisions arose from a sense  
of moral obligation to the refugees and NATO, not from a 
calculating desire for economic aid. But they are optimistic that 
aid will expand, and that seemingly impossible dreams of one day 
joining NATO and the European Union will henceforth seem less 
far-fetched. 
</P>
<P>
	Western governments don't want to fuel unrealistic expectations,  
but they agree that the Kosovo war has enabled Albania to remake 
its image after the 1997 debacle. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an unbelievable second chance for Albania, in a very  
weird and twisted sense,'' said one Western diplomat in Tirana, who 
discussed developments on condition he and his government not be 
named. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Albanian politicians and the public, there is anticipation  
of a massive Western aid program for the Balkans, comparable to the 
Marshall Plan that rebuilt Western Europe after World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``The world is getting to know the spirit and the dignity of the  
Albanian people,'' said Myrvet Domnori, 50, owner of a Tirana 
pharmacy and host to three Kosovo refugees at her apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people are so pleased that the Marshall Plan will be  
implemented,'' she said. ``It would be such a shame if the world 
did not do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A note of caution was sounded by Zef Preci, director of  
Albania's first independent economic think tank. He said foreign 
aid might breed over-dependency and won't won't help Albania in the 
long run as much as institutional reforms to reduce corruption, 
fight crime, improve the banking system and streamline the 
bureaucracy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a matter of improving the business culture,'' he said.  
``We need to change the old-fashioned way of thinking -- of waiting 
for the government to suggest the solution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The unemployment rate is probably double the official figure of  
17 percent, Preci said, and an estimated 60 percent of the economy 
is the so-called informal sector that produces virtually no tax 
revenue. Though potentially capable of feeding itself, Albania is 
importing 80 percent of its food because of its economic disarray. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a controlled economy, it's not a free-market  
economy,'' Preci said. ``It's a survival economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lani, who directs a media institute aimed at improving the  
quality of Albanian journalism, said any regional reconstruction 
plan must be accompanied by reconciliation and diminished 
nationalism. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot have a Marshall Plan and at the same time treat each  
other as the enemy,'' he said. ``We can't be teaching history with 
the same old textbooks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of those old books, Lani noted, was written by Hoxha: ``The  
Anglo-American Threat to Albania.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now the United States and Britain are in the front lines to  
help us,'' he said. ``It's a good lesson, though a bitter lesson, 
that our friends of the last 60 years -- Yugoslavia, Russia and 
China -- are all against us now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lani said Albania's current president, Rexhep Meidani, is the  
right man for the times, a low-key former professor with little 
zest for partisan power politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Balkans, we are tired of heroes,'' Lani said. ``Our  
heroes have been disasters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At no point during the Kosovo conflict has there been any  
serious push in Albania for taking charge of post-war Kosovo or 
forming any sort of ``Greater Albania'' -- a vague concept feared in 
some neighboring countries with Albanian minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is not to create a greater Albania, but to create a  
region in the Balkans that could be part of an integrated Europe,'' 
said Ulqini. 
</P>
<P>
	``Albanians want to be part of European civilization, but for  
500 years it wasn't possible,'' he said. ``Now is the time... We 
dare to look beyond today. We dare to be optimistic.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 06:36:34 </DATE_TIME>
