<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:32:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Cholesterol Spread Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new spread touted as the first to contain a  
soybean extract that can help promote healthy cholesterol levels is 
heading to store shelves, after the government reviewed research 
showing the key ingredient is safe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration said Friday it had evaluated  
materials submitted by Lipton, the manufacturer of Take Control, 
and did not question the conclusion that the ingredient was safe. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipton says Take Control is the first butter-margarine  
substitute to contain a soybean extract called plant sterols that 
helps promote healthy cholesterol levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``The agency has no questions at this time regarding Lipton's  
conclusion that vegetable oil sterol esters are generally 
recognized as safe under the intended conditions of use,'' the FDA 
said in a letter to Lipton. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law says that new food ingredients must either win FDA  
approval or be certified by qualified experts as a generally safe 
substance. The company agreed earlier this year to submit studies 
and information from an independent panel of experts supporting the 
assertion that the product was safe. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA, while reviewing this material, noted in its letter to  
Lipton that it did not do its own research on Take Control's 
ingredients to determine whether it was generally recognized as 
safe. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipton also worked with the FDA to come up with appropriate  
language to describe the product's claim that it helps promote 
healthy cholesterol levels, said David Blanchard, the company's 
vice president of research and development. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA places strict requirements for scientific proof before  
allowing companies to claim their products help prevent or treat 
disease. The law, however, allows more vague claims about how a 
food supports bodily ``structure or function'' without supporting 
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Blanchard said Take Control will benefit people trying to manage  
their cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first entry for the company, based in Englewood,  
N.J., into the market of ``functional foods'' -- those said to 
include new ingredients that promote good health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
