<HEADLINE> Best Mystery Book of 1999 Chosen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Mr. White's Confession'' by Robert Clark of  
Seattle has been named best novel by the Mystery Writers of America 
as part of its 1999 Edgar Allen Poe awards. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, set in 1939 St. Paul, Minn., is the story of a  
photographer who finds himself suspected of committing two murders. 
The author said he was stunned by the award because he never 
intended it as a mystery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just so flabbergasted that I won this thing,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Other winners named Thursday were: Steve Hamilton's ``A Cold Day  
in Paradise,'' for best first novel by an American author; Rick 
Riordan's ``The Widower's Two Step,'' for best paperback original; 
Carlton Stowers' ``To the Last Breath,'' for best fact crime; Robin 
Winks and Maureen Corrigam's ``Mystery and Suspense Writers,'' for 
best critical or biographical work; Tom Franklin's ``Poachers,'' 
for best short story; Nancy Werlin's ``The Killer's Cousin,'' in 
the best young adult category; and Wendelin Van Draanen's ``Sammy 
Keyes and the Hotel Thief,'' for best children's mystery. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Law &AMP; Order'' took home two awards; ``Out of Sight'' won  
for best movie; and television producer Steven Bochco received a 
special citation. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1946, Mystery Writers of America is an organization  
dedicated to promoting the genre. It represents more than 3,000 
writers, editors, agents, booksellers, librarians and others with 
an interest in mystery writing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
