<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US To Bring 7 New Cases Before WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is targeting  
countries from Argentina to South Korea in seven cases before the 
World Trade Organization in an effort to knock down barriers to 
American exports. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration announced Friday it was bringing two cases  
against the 15-nation European Union, two cases against South Korea 
and one case each against India, Canada and Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade actions involve use of a process known as ``Super  
301,'' which President Clinton renewed two months ago under an 
executive order. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign countries have long complained about the Super 301  
process, which they view as American bullying. It allows the 
administration to bring cases against other nations without waiting 
for U.S. industries to file complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Hugo Paemen, the EU's ambassador to the United States, said in  
an interview that the administration had not given the EU ``the 
slightest early warning'' that it would be bringing these cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration renewed the Super 301 process as part of its  
effort to respond to congressional complaints that it has done too 
little to counteract a trade deficit that hit a record $169 billion 
last year and is projected to climb even higher this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Absent from the targeted countries were the two nations with  
which the United States is suffering its biggest deficits -- Japan, 
with an imbalance of $64 billion, and China, where the deficit hit 
a record $57 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials said Japan and China were not targeted  
because the administration is involved in aggressive market-opening 
negotiations outside the Super 301 process. 
</P>
<P>
	When Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi visits Washington on  
Monday, the administration plans to propose measures to further 
deregulate the Japanese economy to help expand sales opportunities 
for American companies. It also is pressing Tokyo to take new steps 
to pull the nation out of a persistent recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, U.S. officials are trying to reach a broad  
market-opening package with China as part of that country's bid to 
join the WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, announcing the  
seven new trade cases, said they had been selected in an effort to 
ensure that countries were abiding by commitments made in previous 
global trade negotiations before a new round of talks begins in 
Seattle this November. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we move toward the launch of a new round of global trade  
negotiations ... it is critical that our trading partners fully 
implement their Uruguay Round commitments,'' Barshefsky said, 
referring to the last round of talks, launched in Uruguay in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States made these allegations in the cases it will  
bring before the Geneva-based WTO: 
</P>
<P>
	-- A case against the 15-nation European Union that contends  
Europe is unfairly subsidizing Airbus Industrie, the world's No. 2 
maker of airliners and chief rival to Seattle-based Boeing, through 
government support of a new flight management system designed for 
Airbus planes. U.S. officials said this could the first of a number 
of cases brought against the EU on the subsidy issue. 
</P>
<P>
	--A second case against the EU alleging unfair treatment for  
American cheese and wine products because of European copyright and 
trademark practices that violate WTO rules. 
</P>
<P>
	--A charge that India is imposing unfair requirements on American  
automakers seeking to set up operations there. 
</P>
<P>
	--A case charging South Korea with unfairly restricting the  
ability of American construction companies to bid on airport work. 
</P>
<P>
	--A charge that South Korea imposes unfair import restrictions  
against American beef. 
</P>
<P>
	--A contention that Canada is unfairly restricting the time  
American products can receive patent protection, limiting it to 17 
years instead of the 20 under WTO rules. 
</P>
<P>
	--A case charging Argentina with failing to provide proper patent  
protection for U.S. pharmaceutical products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
