<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990430.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 00:24:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: No Media Violence Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says many factors could be  
contributing to the recent rash of school shootings and he won't 
limit any White House youth violence summit to the influence of the 
entertainment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``What should we do about guns? What should we do about culture?  
What should we do about the schools? How can we help the parents? 
And, what is government's responsibility? Those are the big 
questions. We should ask and answer all of them -- not just one,'' 
Clinton said in an interview for broadcast today on NBC's ``Today'' 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Congress asked Clinton earlier this week to convene  
an emergency summit of entertainment industry executives to address 
the kind of youth rage that erupted at Columbine High School in 
Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked in the NBC interview if he would call such a summit,  
Clinton said: 
</P>
<P>
	``I plan to bring some high-level folks from the entertainment  
industry and from other sectors of our society that I think can be 
active here together at the White House in the near future and then 
figure out how we can put together the elements of a national 
campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the entertainment industry must have ``a big part'' of any  
solution to youth violence, Clinton said, he indicated he believes 
that the National Rifle Association also has a role. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a mistake for the people who don't want to offend  
the NRA to blame Hollywood and the people that don't want to offend 
Hollywood to blame the NRA,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
